                  <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Il Canzoniere di Petrarca e Le Rime di Dante:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-ENGLISH-00113/1">Italian MS 1</ref></p></cell>
              </row>
            </table>
            <p>As a general rule, encode descriptive information at the most specific level to which it applies. This principle applies to both <gi>msItem</gi> and <gi>msPart</gi>. Accordingly, <gi>author</gi> should normally be encoded within the most specific <gi>msItem</gi> to which the authorship relates.</p>
            <p>Where no nested <gi>msItem</gi> or <gi>msPart</gi> structure is present, the top-level <gi>msItem</gi> is the appropriate level at which to record authorship. Where a single author is responsible for the entire work, <gi>author</gi> may be recorded once on the top-level <gi>msItem</gi> rather than repeated within nested components.</p>
            <p><hi rend="bold"><code>&lt;author&gt;</code> name variants</hi></p>
            <p>Where an author's name appears in more than one form, whether due to transliteration, translation, or script variation, use <gi>persName</gi> within <gi>author</gi> to record each form separately. Each <gi>persName</gi> should include <att>xml:lang</att> to specify the language and script of that form. Record the authority source and identifier once on <gi>author</gi>, using <att>source</att> and <att>key</att>.</p>
            <p>Here is an example of names in both Latin and Farsi script:</p>
            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><author source="#viaf" key="90042997"><persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc">Jāmī, 1414-1492</persName> <persName xml:lang="per">جامی</persName></author></egXML></p>
            <p>The value <val>per-Latn-x-lc</val> combines the ISO 639-2 language code for Persian (per), the ISO 15924 script code for Latin (Latn), and the private-use extension x-lc to indicate Library of Congress romanisation.</p>
            <p><hi rend="italic">Do</hi> <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> use <gi>foreign</gi> in this context.</p>
            <p><hi rend="bold"><code>&lt;author&gt;</code> unknown | anonymous</hi></p>
            <p>For items where the author is <hi rend="italic">anonymous</hi>, <gi>author</gi> should not be omitted. Where authorship is <hi rend="italic">unknown</hi>, the use of <gi>author</gi> is optional and depends on the project’s requirements. In either case, the status of the authorship should be recorded clearly and consistently.</p>
            <p><hi rend="bold">Unknown authorship</hi></p>
            <p><val>unknown</val> the identity of the author is unknown or cannot be determined.</p>
            <p>Use <gi>author</gi> with <att>cert</att>=<val>unknown</val> to indicate that the identity of the author is not ascertainable with the current information. If the absence is the result of analytical judgement, include <att>evidence</att>=<val>conjecture</val> as well.</p>
            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><author cert="unknown" evidence="conjecture">Unknown</author></egXML></p>
            <p>Where adopted, it should be applied consistently across a project wherever authorship cannot be determined.</p>
            <p><hi rend="bold">Consider using Unknown when:</hi></p>
            <p>No authorship information: there is no available information about the author, and historical or textual analysis does not suggest any intentional anonymity.</p>
            <p>Lost identity: historical records do not provide any clues about the author's identity, possibly due to the age of the work or loss of records over time.</p>
            <p>Inadequate evidence: you cannot conclusively determine why there is no author credited due to insufficient evidence.</p>
            <p><hi rend="bold">Anonymous authorship</hi></p>
            <p><hi rend="italic">Anonymous</hi> is used when it is known that the author deliberately chose not to reveal their identity. This status is typically confirmed through historical or contextual evidence.</p>
            <p>Use <gi>author</gi> without <att>cert</att>, as the anonymity is a known and intentional attribute of the work.</p>
            <table rend="rules">
              <row>
                <cell><p>Anonymous  </p>
                  <p>VIAF ID: 53223366 (Personal) | <code>source="#viaf" key="53223366"</code></p>
                  <p>Permalink: <ref target="http://viaf.org/viaf/53223366">http://viaf.org/viaf/53223366</ref></p>
                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><author source="#viaf" key="53223366">Anonymous</author></egXML></p></cell>
                </row>
              </table>
              <p><hi rend="bold">Use Anonymous when:</hi></p>
              <p>Intentional anonymity: there is evidence (textual, historical, contextual) that suggests the author deliberately chose not to reveal their identity. This could be inferred from the text itself, prefaces, or from historical practices and norms of the time.</p>
              <p>Cultural or social reasons: the work fits into a broader cultural or social practice where works were commonly published without author names for reasons like humility, fear of persecution, or a cultural norm that de-emphasized individual authorship.</p>
              <p>Explicit indications: the work or accompanying documentation explicitly states that the author wished to remain anonymous.</p>
              <p>The terms <hi rend="italic">Unknown</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Anonymous</hi> should always be capitalised when used as textual values. Care should be taken to distinguish between unknown authorship and deliberate anonymity. <hi rend="italic">Anonymous</hi> should be used only where there is evidence that the author's identity was intentionally concealed. <hi rend="italic">Unknown</hi> should be used only where the author's identity cannot be determined from the available evidence. This distinction should be applied consistently throughout a project.</p>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="editor">
              <head><code>&lt;editor&gt;</code> | editor | translator | photographer, etc.</head>
              <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-editor.html"><gi>editor</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">contains a secondary statement of responsibility for a bibliographic item, for example the name of an individual, institution or organisation, (or of several such) acting as editor, compiler, translator, etc.</hi></p>
              <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Editors(s)</hi> | <hi rend="bold">Translator(s)</hi> | <hi rend="bold">Photographer(s), etc.</hi></p>
              <p><gi>editor</gi> is used to record the name of a person or organisation that has contributed significantly to a work in a capacity other than the author.</p>
              <p>One or more <gi>editor</gi> may be used, with roles specified accurately to ensure clear attribution of contributions beyond primary authorship.</p>
              <p><gi>editor</gi> follows the same principles as <gi>author</gi>. When applicable, it must include both <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> to provide a persistent identifier from an authority file, such as VIAF.  <gi>persName</gi> may be used to encode name variants.</p>
              <p><gi>editor</gi> must include an appropriate <att>role</att>.</p>
              <p rend="attHead"><code>@role</code></p>
              <p><att>role</att> specifies the exact role of a person or organisation in relation to the item.</p>
              <p><att>role</att> should be encoded using standardised codes from the MARC Code List for Relators.</p>
              <table rend="rules">
                <row>
                  <cell><p><val>marcrelator</val></p></cell>
                  <cell><p>MARC Code List for Relators | Library of Congress</p></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell cols="2"><p>The <ref target="https://www.loc.gov/marc/relators/relaterm.html">MARC Code List for Relators</ref> is a standardised list published by the Library of Congress that provides three-letter (alpha-3) codes used in MARC (Machine-Readable Cataloguing) records to designate the roles of people, organisations or entities in the creation or contribution to a work.</p>
                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><taxonomy xml:id="marcrelator">
<bibl><ref target="https://www.loc.gov/marc/relators/relaterm.html">MARC Code List for Relators (LC)</ref></bibl>
</taxonomy></egXML></p></cell>
                  </row>
                </table>
                <p><att>role</att> on <gi>editor</gi> is constrained by a controlled vocabulary defined in our customised TEI schema, extended via an ODD (One Document Does it all). The permitted values for the MARC relator codes appear in the XML editor as a drop-down list. Additional codes may be included through the ODD. Only these values are valid. Any other value will result in a schema validation error.</p>
                <p>Additional codes may be added through the ODD where required. Their inclusion may also require implementation by the software developer to ensure the correct display.</p>
                <table rend="rules">
                  <row>
                    <cell><p rend="right">visual | photograph album</p>
                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Photographers(s):</hi> Fenton, Roger, 1819-1869; Bedford, Francis, 1816-1894; Wilson, George Washington, 1823-1893</p>
                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<msItem>
<!-- additional metadata -->
