<editor source="#viaf" key="22414011" role="pht">Bedford, Francis, 1816-1894</editor>
<editor source="#viaf" key="54421826" role="pht">Wilson, George Washington, 1823-1893</editor>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</msItem>
</msContents>]]></egXML></p>
                      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">English architecture and landscapes:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/VS-VPH-00007/1">VPH.7</ref></p></cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell><p rend="right">printed | map</p>
                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Cartographer(s):</hi> Mitsukuri, Shōgo, 1821-1846　箕作, 省吾</p>
                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Engraver(s):</hi> Takeguchi, Teisai　竹口, 貞斎; Sugita, Yūsai　杉田, 祐斎</p>
                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Contributor(s):</hi> Ōtsuki, Bankei, 1801-1878　大槻, 盤渓</p>
                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<msItem>
<!-- additional metadata -->
<editor source="#viaf" key="19539126" role="ctg"><persName xml:lang="jpn-Latn-x-lc">Mitsukuri, Shōgo, 1821-1846</persName> <persName xml:lang="jpn">箕作, 省吾</persName</editor>
<editor role="egr"><persName xml:lang="jpn-Latn-x-lc">Takeguchi, Teisai</persName> <persName xml:lang="jpn">竹口, 貞斎</persName</editor>
<editor role="egr"><persName xml:lang="jpn-Latn-x-lc">Sugita, Yūsai</persName> <persName xml:lang="jpn">杉田, 祐斎</persName</editor>
<editor source="#viaf" key="122320757" role="ctb"><persName xml:lang="jpn-Latn-x-lc">Ōtsuki, Bankei, 1801-1878 /persName> <persName xml:lang="jpn">大槻, 盤渓</persName</editor>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</msItem>
</msContents>]]></egXML></p>
                      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Shinsei yochi zenzu:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-JAPANESE-00118-A/5">Japanese 118a</ref></p></cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell><p rend="right">printed | incunable</p>
                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Author(s):</hi> Dante Alighieri, 1265-1321</p>
                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Commentator(s):</hi> Landino, Cristoforo, 1424-1504</p>
                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Editor(s):</hi> Pietro, da Figino, active 15th century</p>
                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Printer(s):</hi> Piasi, Piero de, active 15th century</p>
                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<msItem>
<!-- additional metadata -->
<author source="#viaf" key="97105654">Dante Alighieri, 1265-1321</author>
<editor source="#viaf" key="30887708" role="cwt">Landino, Cristoforo, 1424-1504</editor>
<editor source="#viaf" key="39514283" role="edt">Pietro, da Figino, active 15th century</editor>
<editor source="#viaf" key="311356730" role="prt">Piasi, Piero de, active 15th century </editor>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</msItem>
</msContents>]]></egXML></p>
                      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Comento di christophoro Landino fiorentino sopra la comedia di Danthe alighieri poeta fiorentino:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-INCU-05121/1">5121</ref></p></cell>
                  </row>
                </table>
                <p>Always consider the specific nature of each role's involvement in a work. Roles concerned with physical production or general association are often more appropriately recorded elsewhere, such as within <gi>physDesc</gi> or <gi>history</gi>. For example, an artist may be more appropriately encoded within <gi>decoDesc</gi>, and a former owner within <gi>provenance</gi>.</p>
                <p>Where possible, contributors should be encoded within the most contextually relevant element for the role being recorded, using <gi>name</gi> with <att>role</att>, together with <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi>. Where this is not feasible, the use of <gi>editor</gi> is acceptable.</p>
                <p>Once a person or organisation has been encoded in full at its first occurrence, it is <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> necessary to repeat the same level of encoding for subsequent occurrences.</p>
                <p>Where the same person or organisation has more than one role, record all applicable codes within the same <att>role</att>, separated by a single space. Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> separate multiple codes with commas or other punctuation.</p>
                <p><hi rend="italic">Do</hi> <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> use <code>&lt;persName type="alt"&gt;</code>.</p>
                <p><hi rend="bold">Recommended best practice | <code>&lt;name&gt;</code> | @role</hi></p>
                <p>The preferred approach is to record individuals and organisations within the most contextually relevant element for the role being recorded, using <gi>name</gi> with <att>role</att> containing either <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi>.</p>
                <p>This is particularly useful where a distinction is required between the form of a name used in prose and the form used for indexing.</p>
                <p>One common application of this approach is within <gi>decoDesc</gi>, where artists, illuminators, engravers, and other individuals or organisations associated with the decoration may be recorded.</p>
                <p>Any name associated with the production or execution of the decoration should be encoded using <gi>name</gi>, containing either <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> as appropriate, and must include <att>role</att> indicating the nature of the relationship to the decoration. If the name is listed in VIAF, include both <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> on <gi>name</gi> to reference the relevant VIAF authority record. Where both display and standard forms are required, include two <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> within <gi>name</gi>, one with <att>type</att>=<val>display</val> and one with <att>type</att>=<val>standard</val>. Otherwise, a single <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> within <gi>name</gi> may be used.</p>
                <p>When the value <val>#viaf</val> is used for <att>source</att>, it indicates that the identifier recorded in <att>key</att> is drawn from this authority file. The prefix <code>#</code> indicates a reference to an identifier defined elsewhere in the same file. In this case, it refers to the <gi>taxonomy</gi> declared in the header with <att>xml:id</att>=<val>viaf</val>. This value can be selected from a controlled dropdown list when entering the attribute and does not need to be typed manually.</p>
                <p><att>role</att> specifies the relationship of a person or organisation to the decoration. In most cases, this value will be <val>art</val>, used for artists. Other MARC relator codes, such as <val>ilu</val> for illuminators, <val>ill</val> for illustrators, or <val>egr</val> for engravers, may be used where appropriate, and additional values may also be applied as required.</p>
                <table rend="rules">
                  <row>
                    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Illuminator(s):</hi> Simone Camaldolese, Don, active 1378-1405</p>
                      <p>—</p>
                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Decoration:</hi></p>
                      <p>The illuminated decoration on 3r, 105r, and 149r is attributed to Don Simone Camaldolese (active 1378-1405), also known as Simone da Siena. A monk of the Camaldolese Order at the Monastery of Santa Maria degli Angeli in Florence, Don Simone was a prominent miniaturist and illuminator of the late fourteenth century, primarily active in Florence and Tuscany.  ... ... ...</p>
                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><decoDesc>
<summary>
<p>The illuminated decoration on <locus from="3r" to="3r">3r</locus>, <locus from="105r" to="105r">105r</locus>, and <locus from="149r" to="149r">149r</locus> is attributed to <name source="#viaf" key="313279739" role="ilu"><persName type="display">Don Simone Camaldolese (active 1378-1405), also known as Simone da Siena</persName><persName type="standard">Simone Camaldolese, Don, active 1378-1405</persName></name>. A monk of the Camaldolese Order at the Monastery of Santa Maria degli Angeli in Florence, Don Simone was a prominent miniaturist and illuminator of the late fourteenth century, primarily active in Florence and Tuscany. ...</p></summary>
<!-- additional metadata -->
<decoNote>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</decoNote>
</decoDesc></egXML></p>
                      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Il Canzoniere di Petrarca e Le Rime di Dante:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-ITALIAN-00001/1">Italian MS 1</ref></p></cell>
                  </row>
                </table>
                <p> <att>type</att>=<val>display</val> provides the form used in the prose description, while <att>type</att>=<val>standard</val> records the authorised form used for indexing and display fields in MDC. <att>role</att> determines the corresponding display label. <gi>name</gi> encoded in <gi>provenance</gi> with <att>role</att>=<val>fmo</val> will display as <hi rend="bold">Former Owner(s)</hi>, and in <gi>decoDesc</gi> with <att>role</att>=<val>ilu</val> will display as <hi rend="bold">Illuminator(s)</hi>, among others.</p>
                <p><hi rend="bold">Attributed name(s)</hi></p>
                <p>In some cases, a person is traditionally or historically associated with a work, but conclusive evidence of authorship is lacking. This may include attributions found in manuscript rubrics, colophons, catalogue records, or bibliographic tradition. Such cases should be encoded using <att>role</att>=<val>att</val> on the most appropriate element, such as <gi>author</gi>, <gi>editor</gi>, or <gi>persName</gi> within <gi>name</gi>.</p>
                <p><code>&lt;author role="att"&gt;</code> should be used when the individual is regarded as the author of the work, even if the attribution is uncertain or disputed. This preserves the authorial relationship and is the most semantically appropriate encoding where attributed authorship remains central to the intellectual identity of the work.</p>
                <p>In MDC, however, names encoded as <code>&lt;author role="att"&gt;</code> are displayed under <hi rend="bold">Author(s)</hi>. Where it is preferable to distinguish attributed authorship from established authorship in the user interface, <code>&lt;editor role="att"&gt;</code> may be used instead. Within MDC, <gi>editor</gi> functions as a broader contributor element and is displayed under <hi rend="bold">Attributed name(s)</hi> when used with <att>role</att>=<val>att</val>.</p>
                <p><code>&lt;name</code> <code>role="att"&gt;</code> may be used where the attributed name appears within a context-specific element such as <gi>summary</gi>, <gi>physDesc</gi>, or <gi>history</gi>. This approach also supports extraction to the MDC field <hi rend="bold">Attributed name(s)</hi>.</p>
                <p>An explanatory <gi>note</gi> should accompany any use of <att>role</att>=<val>att</val>, outlining the nature of the attribution and the evidence on which it is based.</p>
              </div>
              <div xml:id="rubrics-incipits-explicits-and-other-quotations">
                <head>rubrics, incipits, explicits, and other quotations</head>
                <p>In a manuscript description, it is customary to record the opening and closing words of a text, along with any headings or colophons. The specialised elements <gi>rubric</gi>, <gi>incipit</gi>, <gi>explicit</gi>, <gi>finalRubric</gi>, <gi>colophon</gi>, which are all contained within <gi>msItem</gi>, support this, along with the more general <gi>quote</gi>, for recording other excerpts of the text not covered by these elements.</p>
                <p rend="attHead"><code>&lt;rubric&gt; | &lt;incipit&gt; | &lt;explicit&gt; | &lt;finalRubric&gt; | &lt;colophon&gt;</code></p>
                <p><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-rubric.html"><gi>rubric</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(rubric) contains the text of any rubric or heading attached to a particular manuscript item, that is, a string of words through which a manuscript or other object signals the beginning of a text division, often with an assertion as to its author and title, which is in some way set off from the text itself, typically in red ink, or by use of different size or type of script, or some other such visual device.</hi></p>
                <p><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-incipit.html"><gi>incipit</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(incipit) contains the incipit of a manuscript or similar object item, that is the opening words of the text proper, exclusive of any rubric which might precede it, of sufficient length to identify the work uniquely; such incipits were, in former times, frequently used a means of reference to a work, in place of a title.</hi></p>
                <p><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-explicit.html"><gi>explicit</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(explicit) contains the explicit of an item, that is, the closing words of the text proper, exclusive of any rubric or colophon which might follow it.</hi></p>
                <p><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-finalRubric.html"><gi>finalRubric</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(final rubric) contains the string of words that denotes the end of a text division, often with an assertion as to its author and title, usually set off from the text itself by red ink, by a different size or type of script, or by some other such visual device.</hi></p>
                <p><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-colophon.html"><gi>colophon</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(colophon) contains the colophon of an item: that is, a statement providing information regarding the date, place, agency, or reason for production of the manuscript or other object.</hi></p>
                <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Excerpts: Rubric</hi> | <hi rend="bold">Incipit</hi> | <hi rend="bold">Explicit</hi> | <hi rend="bold">Final Rubric</hi> | <hi rend="bold">Colophon</hi></p>
                <p>These elements are optional. They should be used within <gi>msItem</gi> for the text or section to which the excerpt belongs. Where there are no nested <gi>msItem</gi>, they may be used within the top-level <gi>msItem</gi>.</p>
                <p><gi>locus</gi> should be included within each element to indicate the location of the excerpt within the item.</p>
                <p>The language of <gi>rubric</gi>, <gi>incipit</gi>, <gi>explicit</gi>, <gi>finalRubric</gi>, and <gi>colophon</gi> is normally assumed to be the same as that specified in <gi>textLang</gi>. It is therefore <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> necessary to use <att>xml:lang</att> on these elements unless an excerpt is in a different language, for example, where a manuscript contains a rubric in French but an incipit in Latin.</p>
                <p><att>defective</att> may be used on <gi>incipit</gi> and <gi>explicit</gi> to indicate whether the beginning or end of a text is s not preserved. In the case of an incipit, the excerpt records the first surviving words of the text rather than its true opening. In the case of an explicit, the excerpt records the final surviving words of the text rather than its true ending.</p>
