<note/>
</msItem>
</msContents></egXML></p>
                      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Tefillin: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-GASTER-AMULET-00196/2">Gaster Amulet 196</ref></hi></p></cell>
                  </row>
                </table>
              </div>
              <div xml:id="filiation">
                <head><code>&lt;filiation&gt;</code> | filiation</head>
                <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-filiation.html"><gi>filiation</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(filiation) contains information concerning the manuscript or other object's filiation, i.e. its relationship to other surviving manuscripts or other objects of the same text or contents, its protographs, antigraphs and apographs.</hi></p>
                <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Filiations</hi></p>
                <p><gi>filiation</gi> may be used to record the relationship between the text being described and other witnesses of the same textual tradition. This may include direct copies, shared exemplars, or classification into manuscript families or textual lineages. It may also note the manuscript’s place within a scholarly stemma or filiation hypothesis.</p>
                <p><gi>filiation</gi> is repeatable. When more than one relationship or hypothesis of descent is present, it is acceptable to record them together within a single <gi>filiation</gi>. However, best practice is to record each separately, using multiple <gi>filiation</gi> to ensure clarity, consistency, and ease of future processing.</p>
                <p><gi>filiation</gi> is typically placed after core textual excerpt elements and quotations. Each entry within <gi>filiation</gi> should follow this format:</p>
                <p><code>Institution Name, City: Identifier</code></p>
                <p>The institution name should appear first, followed by the city in which the holding institution is located. The identifier, such as a catalogue number, shelfmark, accession number, or collection code, should follow the city and be separated by a colon (:). It should be transcribed exactly as used by the institution, including any prefixes, spacing, punctuation, and capitalisation.</p>
                <p>If a stable URL or persistent digital identifier is available for the item, the entire string, <hi rend="italic">Institution Name, City: Identifier</hi>, should be wrapped in <code>&lt;ref target="..."&gt;</code>...<gi>ref</gi>.</p>
                <p><hi rend="bold">Multiple <code>&lt;filiation&gt;</code> | structured, one per relationship</hi></p>
                <p>Multiple <gi>filiation</gi> should be used when recording distinct relationships, witnesses, or hypotheses of descent. Each relationship should be recorded separately, using one <gi>filiation</gi> per entry. When the content of <gi>filiation</gi> comprises a simple citation, pointer, or reference, whether structured or descriptive, the entry should be recorded directly within <gi>filiation</gi>, without enclosing it in a <gi>p</gi>.</p>
                <table rend="rules">
                  <row>
                    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Title:</hi> Le terze rime di Dante</p>
                      <p>—</p>
                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Author(s):</hi> Dante Alighieri, 1265-1321</p>
                      <p>—</p>
                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Filiations:</hi></p>
                      <p>Aldine Collection: R213785</p>
                      <p>The Morgan Library &amp; Museum, New York: PML 1257</p>
                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><title xml:lang="ita">Le terze rime di Dante </title>
<!-- additional metadata -->
<author source="#viaf" key="97105654">Dante Alighieri, 1265-1321 </author>
<!-- additional metadata -->
<filiation>
<ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-ALDI-R-00002-13785/1">Aldine Collection: R213785</ref>
</filiation>
<filiation>
<ref target="https://www.themorgan.org/printed-books/175532">The Morgan Library &amp; Museum, New York: PML 1257</ref>
</filiation></egXML></p>
                      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Le terze rime di Dante:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-ALDI-18873/1">18873</ref></p></cell>
                  </row>
                </table>
                <p>When the reference is internal to the same holding institution, for example, Aldine Collection: R213785, it is not necessary to include the institution name and city. In such cases, provide only the collection name and identifier, following local practice.</p>
                <p><hi rend="bold">Single <code>&lt;filiation&gt;</code> | narrative prose</hi></p>
                <p>A single <gi>filiation</gi> containing multiple entries may also be used in descriptive or interpretative contexts, particularly when hypotheses are closely connected and cannot be meaningfully separated. In such cases, prose may be used directly within <gi>filiation</gi> to describe how a manuscript or book fits within a textual tradition or to refer to a scholarly classification.</p>
                <table rend="rules">
                  <row>
                    <cell><p>Section shown in images 231 to 594</p>
                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Title:</hi> Ἑξαημέρον</p>
                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Author(s):</hi> Anastasius, Sinaita, Saint, active 640-700</p>
                      <p>—</p>
                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Filiations:</hi></p>
                      <p>Kuehn and Baggarly have placed this manuscript in family IIIc of this text. This family also contains Biblioteca Nacional, Madrid: MS 4773, Biblioteca Nazionale, Turin: MS C.IV.26, Biblioteca Vallicelliana, Rome: MS F.58 (99) and (more distantly related) Madrid, Biblioteca Nacional, Madrid: MS 4775 and Real Biblioteca, Escorial: MS Ψ.I.4.</p>
                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<msItem n="2">
<locus from="111r" to="292v">111r-292v</locus>
<title xml:lang="gcr">Ἑξαημέρον</title>
<!-- additional metadata -->
<author source="#viaf" key="314808225">Anastasius, Sinaita, Saint, active 640-700</author>
<!-- additional metadata -->
<filiation>Kuehn and Baggarly have placed this manuscript in family IIIc of this text. This family also contains <ref target="http://bdh.bne.es/bnesearch/detalle/bdh0000246391">Biblioteca Nacional, Madrid: MS 4773</ref>, Biblioteca Nazionale, Turin: MS C.IV.26, Biblioteca Vallicelliana, Rome: MS F.58 (99), and more distantly related: <ref target="http://bdh.bne.es/bnesearch/detalle/bdh0000246393">Biblioteca Nacional, Madrid: MS 4775</ref>, and Real Biblioteca, Escorial: MS Ψ.I.4.</filiation>
</msItem>
</msContents>]]></egXML></p>
                      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Late Antique commentaries on the Book of Genesis:  Part III: Ἑξαημέρον:</hi> <ref target="https://cudl.lib.cam.ac.uk/view/MS-FF-00004-00002/231">Cambridge, University Library, MS Ff.4.2</ref></p></cell>
                  </row>
                </table>
                <p>Where multiple works within an item have independent filiations, record each <gi>filiation</gi> within the appropriate <gi>msItem</gi>.</p>
              </div>
              <div xml:id="note">
                <head><code>&lt;note&gt;</code> | note</head>
                <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-note.html"><gi>note</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(note) contains a note or annotation.</hi></p>
                <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Note(s)</hi></p>
                <p><gi>note</gi> is intended for recording annotations or explanatory comments. While it is not considered a core element in MDC, it serves as a valuable supplementary field that can enhance the description and interpretation of the material.</p>
                <p><gi>note</gi> is highly flexible and can be used in various sections of <gi>teiHeader</gi>. In the context of MDC, its placement within <gi>msItem</gi> allows the inclusion of general notes about the item or its intellectual content, particularly when such information does not fit naturally into <gi>summary</gi> or other elements within <gi>teiHeader</gi>, with a preference for using more semantically precise elements wherever possible.</p>
                <p><gi>note</gi> may consist of one or more <gi>p</gi> to structure content into separate paragraphs.</p>
                <p>With the exception of specialised <code>&lt;note type="..."&gt;</code>  defined in Section X &lt;!--insert hyperlink--&gt;: customised &lt;note&gt; types and display fields, all <gi>note</gi> within a top-level <gi>msItem</gi> will be surfaced in the <hi rend="bold">Note(s)</hi> field in the MDC interface.</p>
                <p>In some projects, particularly those involving MARC-derived metadata and retroconversion workflows, TEI XML files have not been further edited or refined after conversion. They therefore remain largely in their post-conversion state and may contain one or more <gi>note</gi> with multiple <gi>p</gi>. This should be understood as an outcome of the conversion process, rather than as a model for TEI encoding practice.</p>
              </div>
              <div xml:id="physDesc">
                <head><code>&lt;physDesc&gt;</code> | physical description</head>
                <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-physDesc.html"><gi>physDesc</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(physical description) contains a full physical description of a manuscript, manuscript part, or other object optionally subdivided using more specialized elements from the <ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-model.physDescPart.html">model.physDescPart</ref> class.</hi></p>
                <p><gi>physDesc</gi> within <gi>msDesc</gi> brings together the elements used to describe the item's physical form, production, appearance, and related physical characteristics.</p>
                <p>The following elements may be included within <gi>physDesc</gi> whenever information is available:</p>
                <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<teiHeader>
<fileDesc>|<titleStmt>|<publicationStmt>|<sourceDesc>
<msDesc>|<msIdentifier>|<msContents>
<physDesc>
<!-- Metadata describing all physical characteristics: material, size, format, script, decoration, binding, etc. -->
<objectDesc>
<!-- Metadata describing the object: form, type, support, extent, and layout -->
<!-- Contains <objectType> | <supportDesc> | <layoutDesc> -->
<!-- May contain <material> | <extent> | <foliation> | <collation> | <condition> -->
</objectDesc>
<handDesc>|<typeDesc>
<!-- Metadata describing the style(s) of scripts or typeface used in the item -->
<!-- Contain <handNote>|<typeNote> -->
</handDesc>|<typeDesc>
<musicNotation>
<!-- Metadata about musical notation if present -->
</musicNotation>
<decoDesc>
<!-- Metadata describing decorative features -->
<!-- Contains <decoNote>
</decoDesc>
<additions>
<!-- Metadata describing any marginalia or other, later additions to the item -->
</additions>
<bindingDesc>
<!-- Metadata describing the binding of the item -->
<!-- Contains <binding>
</bindingDesc>
<sealDesc>
<!-- Metadata describing applied and pendent seals -->
<!-- Contains <seal>
</sealDesc>
<accMat>
<!-- Metadata describing any material not originally part of the item but bound with it or otherwise accompanying it -->
</accMat>
</physDesc>
<history>|<additional>
</msDesc>|</sourceDesc>|</fileDesc>|<encodingDesc>|<profileDesc>|<revisionDesc>
</teiHeader>]]></egXML></p>
                <p>The degree of obligation for including specific elements within <gi>physDesc</gi> depends on the nature of the item and the requirements of the project. A structured and precise description is usually preferable, but the time required for detailed encoding should be balanced against the value it adds to the resource.</p>
                <p><gi>physDesc</gi> may take one of two forms:</p>
                <p>Unstructured | a sequence of prose paragraphs, using one or more <gi>p</gi>, describing physical features narratively.</p>
                <p>Structured | a group of specialised elements from the <ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-model.physDescPart.html">model.physDescPart</ref> class, which may themselves contain one or more &lt;p&gt;.</p>
                <p>Although unstructured encoding using one or more <gi>p</gi> is permitted, it is <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> recommended as the default. Wherever possible, physical description should be organised using specialised elements, as this supports clearer distinction between different types of physical characteristics.</p>
                <p>Combining structured and unstructured content within a single <gi>physDesc</gi> is generally discouraged. Hybrid encoding should be treated as an exception rather than standard practice. It may occasionally be necessary in retroconversion workflows, particularly when some information can be encoded using specialised elements, but other details cannot be reliably separated from prose or mapped to an appropriate element.</p>
                <p>In the MDC interface, any <gi>p</gi> placed immediately after <gi>physDesc</gi> will be pulled through into the display field labelled <hi rend="bold">Physical Description</hi>. This happens regardless of whether additional structured elements, such as <gi>objectDesc</gi>, <gi>handDesc</gi>, or <gi>decoDesc</gi>, are present. If this is not the intended behaviour, the content of the <gi>p</gi> should instead be placed within appropriate specialised elements to avoid unintended display output.</p>
              </div>
              <div xml:id="objectDesc">
                <head><code>&lt;objectDesc&gt;</code> | object description</head>
                <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-objectDesc.html"><gi>objectDesc</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(object description) contains a description of the physical components making up the object which is being described.</hi></p>
                <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Format</hi></p>
                <p><gi>objectDesc</gi> is the first component within <gi>physDesc</gi> and brings together elements used to describe the item’s physical format, support, extent, and layout.</p>
                <p><att>form</att> should be used on <gi>objectDesc</gi> to describe the physical format of the item in its current state, <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> its original or intended format at the time of creation.</p>
                <p rend="attHead"><code>@form</code></p>
                <p><att>form</att> a term identifying the physical form or format of the item</p>
                <p>Values for <att>form</att> should be selected from the approved controlled vocabulary below. The <ref target="https://www.getty.edu/research/tools/vocabularies/aat">Getty Art &amp; Architecture Thesaurus (AAT)</ref> should be consulted where appropriate to confirm the meaning and scope of terms.</p>
                <p>The <att>form</att> value must be a concise, singular noun that accurately describes the physical structure or format of the item. It should <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> be used to record content, function, or genre.</p>
                <table rend="rules">
                  <row>
                    <cell><p><att>form</att></p></cell>
                    <cell><p><gi>objectDesc</gi> | <att>form</att></p></cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell><p><val>accordion</val></p>
                      <p rend="right">Accordion</p></cell>
                    <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<objectDesc form="accordion">]]></egXML></p>
                    <p>Physical format comprising a continuous or joined substrate folded into accordion- or concertina-style pleats, often attached at one or both ends to covers or boards.</p>
                    <p rend="right">Related GETTY (AAT) | accordion books | ID: <ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300438814">300438814</ref></p>
                    <p>The use of <att>form</att>=<val>accordion</val> covers:</p>
                    <list rend="bulleted">
                      <item>Manuscripts and printed items with a continuous or joined substrate folded into zigzag or pleated panels (accordion, concertina, fanfold, or screenfold structure)</item>
                      <item>Folded books such as medieval European almanacs (faltbuchs)</item>
                      <item>Asian folding manuscripts, such as Thai samut khoi or Burmese parabaik</item>
                      <item>Leporello-style books and similar folded formats</item>
                    </list></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><p><val>booklet</val></p>
                    <p rend="right">Booklet</p></cell>
                  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<objectDesc form="booklet">]]></egXML></p>
                  <p>Physical format comprising small books consisting of a few sheets that are glued, stitched or stapled together between thin card or paper covers.</p>
                  <p rend="right">Related GETTY (AAT) | booklets | ID: <ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300311670">300311670</ref></p>
                  <p>The use of <att>form</att>=<val>booklet</val> covers:</p>
                  <list rend="bulleted">
                    <item>Self-contained slim publications, such as pamphlets or chapbooks, including examples later incorporated into bound volumes</item>
                    <item>Single issues of magazines or periodicals issued in paper wrappers or light covers.</item>
                    <item>Manuscript traditions, including many Naxi Dongba | Mo-so manuscripts, comprising separate leaves stitched or thread-bound along one edge for leaf-turning.</item>
                  </list></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell><p><val>codex</val></p>
                  <p rend="right">Codex</p></cell>
                <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<objectDesc form="codex">]]></egXML></p>
                <p>Physical format comprising multiple gatherings of separate leaves, cut or folded, stacked, and bound along one edge within a cover or binding, designed to be read by turning the leaves.</p>
                <p rend="right">Related GETTY (AAT) | codices (bound manuscripts) | ID: <ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300224200">300224200</ref></p>
                <p>The use of <att>form</att>=<val>codex</val> covers:</p>
                <list rend="bulleted">
                  <item>Bound volumes consisting of multiple leaves or gatherings</item>
                  <item>Handwritten manuscripts, early printed books, incunabula</item>
                  <item>Structurally bound modern works such as notebooks, diaries, albums, scrapbooks</item>
                  <item>Bound chapbooks, periodicals, pamphlets, and similar items.</item>
                  <item>Composite manuscripts or volumes whose overall physical structure remains codex-form.</item>
                </list></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><p><val>fragment</val></p>
                <p rend="right">Fragment</p></cell>
              <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<objectDesc form="fragment">]]></egXML></p>
              <p>Physical format comprising incomplete or detached portions of a formerly whole object.</p>
              <p rend="right">Related GETTY (AAT) | fragments (object portions) | ID: <ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300117130">300117130</ref></p>
              <p>The use of <att>form</att>=<val>fragment</val> covers:</p>
              <list rend="bulleted">
                <item>Detached or broken pieces of a manuscript or other object.</item>
                <item>Disassociated elements from scrolls, codices, or tablets.</item>
                <item>Cuttings or torn pieces lacking evidence of original structure.</item>
                <item>Material remains without binding or support, possibly reused.</item>
              </list>
              <p>Use <att>form</att>=<val>fragment</val> for broken or disassociated parts of an object whose original wholeness is presumed or documentable, especially when the object was not purposefully reused for inscription.</p>
              <p><gi>msFrag</gi> may be used within <gi>msDesc</gi> when encoding one or more fragments of a scattered or fragmented manuscript.</p></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><p><val>leaf</val></p>
              <p rend="right">Leaf</p></cell>
            <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<objectDesc form="leaf">]]></egXML></p>
            <p>Physical format comprising a single leaf originating from a codex or gathering structure, typically consisting of recto and verso surfaces.</p>
            <p rend="right">Related GETTY (AAT) | leaves (gathered matter) | ID: <ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300115833">300115833</ref></p>
            <p>The use of <att>form</att>=<val>leaf</val> covers:</p>
            <list rend="bulleted">
              <item>Individual manuscript leaves surviving separately from their original codex structure.</item>
              <item>Detached printed or written leaves that show codicological features.</item>
              <item>Reuse cases where leaves were repurposed in bindings, or inserted into albums, scrapbooks, or collections but clearly originated from a codex.</item>
              <item>Unbound gatherings or quires of two or more bifolia surviving independently.</item>
            </list></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><p><val>object</val></p>
            <p rend="right">Object</p></cell>
          <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<objectDesc form="object">]]></egXML></p>
          <p>Physical format comprising discrete three-dimensional artefacts or a composite material object.</p>
          <p rend="right">Related GETTY (AAT) | objects | ID: <ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300311889">300196838</ref></p>
          <p>The use of <att>form</att>=<val>object</val> covers:</p>
          <list rend="bulleted">
            <item>Three-dimensional artefacts such as coins, medals, seals, textiles, models, instruments, sculptural pieces, and composite or mixed-media items.</item>
            <item>Detached or decorative binding elements, including independent covers, treasure bindings, and jewelled bindings incorporating materials such as metal, ivory, or gemstones.</item>
            <item>Encased or three-dimensional photographic formats, including cased photographs, framed photographic works, sculptural photographic objects, and photographic jewellery or miniatures.</item>
          </list>
          <p>Getty AAT uses the term <hi rend="italic">object</hi> in the inclusive, museum-object sense, encompassing anything that can be accessioned or catalogued, including two-dimensional works such as photographs. In this guidance, <att>form</att>=<val>object</val> is used primarily for three-dimensional physical forms rather than flat textual supports.</p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p><val>ostracon</val></p>
          <p rend="right">Ostracon</p></cell>
        <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<objectDesc form="ostracon">]]></egXML></p>
        <p>Physical format comprising fragments of pottery or stone containing inscriptions.</p>
        <p rend="right">Related GETTY (AAT) | ostraka | ID: <ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300185396">300185396</ref></p>
        <p>The use of <att>form</att>=<val>ostracon</val> covers:</p>
        <list rend="bulleted">
          <item>Inscribed fragments of pottery or stone, typically casual or administrative</item>
          <item>Greek, Coptic, and Egyptian voting ostraca</item>
          <item>Everyday notetaking on broken ceramic or stone shards</item>
        </list>
        <p>Use <att>form</att>=<val>ostracon</val> when the inscriptional use of the broken ceramic or stone defines the object (i.e. the fragment was repurposed as an intentional writing surface).</p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><p><val>pothi</val></p>
        <p rend="right">Pothi</p></cell>
      <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<objectDesc form="pothi">]]></egXML></p>
      <p>Physical format comprising a stack of separate leaves, typically in horizontal orientation, not bound along one edge and designed to be read by flipping the leaves upwards rather than sideways, with leaves either loose or strung and often held between protective boards or within wrappers.</p>
      <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | N/A</p>
      <p>The use of <att>form</att>=<val>pothi</val> covers:</p>
      <list rend="bulleted">
        <item>Traditional South and Southeast Asian manuscripts (India, Nepal, Tibet, Sri Lanka) in pothī format.</item>
        <item>Palm-leaf, bark, and paper manuscripts produced within this tradition.</item>
      </list></cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell><p><val>roll</val></p>
      <p rend="right">Roll</p></cell>
    <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<objectDesc form="roll">]]></egXML></p>
    <p>Physical format comprising long strips of flexible material used for written documents and rolled for ease of handling and storage.</p>
    <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | N/A</p>
    <p>The use of <att>form</att>=<val>roll</val> covers:</p>
    <list rend="bulleted">
      <item>Rolled manuscripts made of paper, parchment, papyrus, or similar material</item>
      <item>Inscribed rolls intended for reading or ceremonial use (Torah scrolls, historical scrolls)</item>
      <item>Literary, religious, or administrative documents produced as continuous inscribed rolls</item>
    </list></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p><val>sheet</val></p>
    <p rend="right">Sheet</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<objectDesc form="sheet">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Physical format comprising a single flat support, typically of paper, parchment, or similar material, not primarily defined by attachment to a codex or gathering structure.</p>
  <p rend="right">Related GETTY (AAT) | sheets (paper artifacts) | ID: <ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300189648">300189648</ref></p>
  <p>The use of <att>form</att>=<val>sheet</val> covers:</p>
  <list rend="bulleted">
    <item>Single flat sheets bearing written, printed, drawn, or photographic content.</item>
    <item>Broadsides, flyers, proclamations, single-sheet maps, charters, architectural plans, and posters.</item>
    <item>Drawings, prints, and other flat works preserved as self-contained units.</item>
    <item>Flat items for which no clear evidence suggests origin within a codex or gathering structure.</item>
    <item>Correspondence letters, including folded letters, letterfolds, and other self-enclosing forms.</item>
    <item>Mounted flat photographic prints such as cabinet cards, together with unmounted photographic prints such as silver gelatin and albumen prints.</item>
    <item>Photographic supports in sheet form, including glass plate negatives and sheet film.</item>
  </list>
  <p>Use <att>form</att>=<val>sheet</val> for single, flat items that retain the physical characteristics of a sheet, typically unbound, but also applicable to individual components within bound volumes.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p><val>tablet</val></p>
    <p rend="right">Tablet</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<objectDesc form="tablet">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Physical format comprising flat rigid surfaces used for writing or inscription.</p>
  <p rend="right">Related GETTY (AAT) | writing tablets (information artifacts) | ID: <ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300262572">300262572</ref></p>
  <p>The use of <att>form</att>=<val>tablet</val> covers:</p>
  <list rend="bulleted">
    <item>Clay tablets with cuneiform script</item>
    <item>Wax, wooden, metal, and stone tablets bearing script.</item>
  </list></cell>
</row>
</table>
<p>New values should <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> be introduced without consultation with the Digital Metadata Specialist. Additional values may be approved where necessary to describe physical formats that are not represented adequately within the existing vocabulary.</p>
<p rend="attHead"><code>&lt;object&gt; vs &lt;msDesc&gt;</code></p>
<p>As of TEI P5 version 3.5.0, <gi>object</gi> is a general-purpose container for describing identifiable physical objects, regardless of whether they bear text. It expands on the functionality of <gi>msDesc</gi> to support a wider range of cultural heritage artefacts, including non-textual, photographic, and 3D artefacts.</p>
<p>At present, MDC does not yet support <gi>object</gi> and its associated sub-elements. Items that would logically be encoded under <gi>object</gi>, for example, photographs or artefacts, must currently be described using <gi>objectDesc</gi> embedded within <gi>msDesc</gi>.</p>
<p>A practical example is the <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/collections/gasteramulets/1">Gaster Amulets</ref> in MDC: In the current encoding, amuletic objects are described using <gi>msDesc</gi>, although structurally they would be more appropriately modelled under <gi>object</gi> once MDC supports it.</p>
<p>As <gi>object</gi> continues to evolve within TEI P5, projects should anticipate minor structural refinements and expanded support for a broader range of object types in future guideline versions. Accordingly, support for <gi>object</gi> within MDC will also develop in line with these updates.</p>
<p><gi>objectDesc</gi> consists of three principal elements: <gi>objectType</gi>, which identifies the functional or semantic classification of the object, <gi>supportDesc</gi>, which describes the physical support, that is, the material carrier on which the text is written or printed, and <gi>layoutDesc</gi>, which describes the layout, that is, the manner in which the text is arranged on the support.</p>
<p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<teiHeader>
<fileDesc>|<titleStmt>|<publicationStmt>|<sourceDesc>
<msDesc>|<msIdentifier>|<msContents>
<physDesc>
<objectDesc>
<objectType>
<!-- Metadata describing the type of object -->
<!-- Contains
<objectType>
<supportDesc>
<!-- Metadata describing the physical support (carrier) of the item -->
<support>
<!-- Metadata describing the materials comprising the physical support -->
<!-- Contains <material>
<!-- May contain <watermark> -->
</support>
<extent>
<!-- Metadata describing the quantity and size of the leaves -->
<!-- Contains <measure> | <dimensions> | <height> | <width> -->
</extent>
<foliation>
<!-- Metadata describing the foliation [or pagination] system used -->
</foliation>
<collation>
<!-- Metadata describing the structure of gatherings | quires -->
<!-- Contains <list> | <signatures> | <catchwords> | <secFol> -->
<!-- May contain <formula> -->
</collation>
<condition>
<!-- Metadata describing any damage with direct impact on the text, not the entire item -->
<!-- Contains <p> -->
</condition>
</supportDesc>
<layoutDesc>
<!-- Metadata describing how the text is arranged on the support -->
<layout>
<!-- Metadata detailing the text layout such as columns and lines -->
<!-- May contain <dimensions> -->
</layout>
</layoutDesc>
</objectDesc>
<handDesc><typeDesc>|<musicNotation>|<decoDesc>|<additions>|<bindingDesc>|<sealDesc>|<accMat>
</physDesc>
<history>|<additional>
</msDesc>|</sourceDesc>|</fileDesc>|<encodingDesc>|<profileDesc>|<revisionDesc>
</teiHeader>]]></egXML></p>
<p>The degree of obligation for including specific elements within <gi>objectDesc</gi> depends on the nature of the item and the specific requirements of the project.</p>
</div>
<div xml:id="objectType">
  <head><code>&lt;objectType&gt;</code> | object type</head>
  <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-objectType.html"><gi>objectType</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(object type) contains a word or phrase describing the type of object being referred to.</hi></p>
  <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Type</hi></p>
  <p><gi>objectType</gi> within <gi>objectDesc</gi> is used to record the semantic, functional, or bibliographic type of an item.</p>
  <p><att>form</att> on <gi>objectDesc</gi> records the general physical format of the item, such as codex, sheet, or roll, while <gi>objectType</gi> further defines the nature of that item. A codex may therefore be a manuscript or incunabulum (book), a sheet may be a broadside or map, and a roll may be a scroll.</p>
  <p><gi>objectType</gi> is repeatable, allowing a single physical format to be associated with multiple object types.</p>
  <p><gi>objectType</gi> must include <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> where a controlled vocabulary is used.</p>
  <p rend="attHead"><code>@source @key</code></p>
  <p><att>source</att> specifies the source from which some aspect of this element is drawn.</p>
  <p><att>key</att> provides a persistent, unique identifier for the named entity, supplied by that source.</p>
  <p><att>source</att> and <att>key</att> should together provide a unique identifier drawn from a controlled vocabulary or classification system. The preferred source is the Getty Art &amp; Architecture Thesaurus (AAT).</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell><p><val>aat</val></p></cell>
      <cell><p>Getty Art &amp; Architecture Thesaurus® (AAT)</p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell cols="2"><p>The <ref target="https://www.getty.edu/research/tools/vocabularies/aat/">Getty Art &amp; Architecture Thesaurus® (AAT)</ref> is a structured vocabulary for describing concepts relating to art, architecture, and material culture. It provides a hierarchical framework that ensures consistency in cataloguing, indexing, and scholarly research.</p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><taxonomy xml:id="aat">
<bibl><ref target="https://www.getty.edu/research/tools/vocabularies/aat">Getty Art &amp; Architecture Thesaurus® (AAT)</ref></bibl>
</taxonomy></egXML></p></cell>
      </row>
    </table>
    <p>When the value <code>#aat</code> is used for <att>source</att>, it indicates that the identifier recorded in <att>key</att> is drawn from this authority file. The prefix <code>#</code> indicates a reference to an identifier defined elsewhere in the same file. In this case, it refers to the <gi>taxonomy</gi> declared in the header with <att>xml:id</att>=<val>aat</val>. This value can be selected from a controlled dropdown list when entering the attribute and does not need to be typed manually.</p>
    <p>The value of <gi>objectType</gi> should be recorded in lowercase. Terms should not be capitalised for display purposes, as display capitalisation is applied automatically by the XSLT transformation.</p>
    <p>The following examples focus on <gi>objectType</gi> but also show how <gi>material</gi> is encoded using <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> with AAT identifiers.</p>
    <table rend="rules">
      <row>
        <cell><p rend="right">codex | manuscript</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Codex</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Type:</hi> Manuscript</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Parchment</p>
          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="codex">
<objectType source="#aat" key="300028569">manuscript</objectType>
<supportDesc material="parchment">
<support>
<material source="#aat" key="300011851">Parchment</material>
</support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | manuscripts (documents) | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300028569">300028569</ref></p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p rend="right">codex | Incunable (pre-1500)</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Codex</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Type:</hi> Incunabulum (book)</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Paper</p>
          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="codex">
<objectType source="#aat" key="300055021">incunabulum (book)</objectType>
<supportDesc material="paper">
<support>
<material source="#aat" key="300014109">Paper</material>
</support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | incunabulum (book) | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300055021">300055021</ref></p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p rend="right">codex | early printed book (post-1500)</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Codex</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Type:</hi> Book</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Paper</p>
          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="codex">
<objectType source="#aat" key="300028051">book</objectType>
<supportDesc material="paper">
<support>
<material source="#aat" key="300014109">Paper</material>
</support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | book | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300028051">300028051</ref></p></cell>
      </row>
    </table>
    <p>Use clearly defined categories based on historical period and printing technology to ensure consistent terminology. <hi rend="italic">Incunabulum</hi> refers to books printed before 1501 using the hand press. Early printed book refers to books printed between 1501 and around 1800, also using the hand press. <hi rend="italic">Modern book</hi> refers to books printed after 1800 using mechanised printing methods.</p>
    <p><hi rend="bold">Book format + paper size variants</hi></p>
    <p>fo | 4to | 8vo | 12mo | 16mo | 24mo | 32mo</p>
    <p>imperial – royal – medium – chancery</p>
    <p>When describing printed books, particularly those associated with historical paper sizes or bibliographic formats, <gi>objectDesc</gi> should normally be encoded with <att>form</att>=<val>codex</val>. While <att>form</att> records the physical format of the item, one <gi>objectType</gi> may be used to record the type of item, such as book or incunabulum (book), and a second <gi>objectType</gi> may be used to record that format, such as folio (fo), quarto (4to), or octavo (8vo). <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> should be included with the corresponding AAT identifiers.</p>
    <p>Typological paper sizes, such as imperial, royal, or medium, should be recorded separately using <gi>material</gi> with <att>type</att>=<val>paper</val> and an appropriate <att>subtype</att>. <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> should be included with the corresponding AAT identifiers.</p>
    <table rend="rules">
      <row>
        <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Codex</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Type:</hi> Incunabulum (book); Folio (fo)</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Royal paper</p>
          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="codex">
<objectType source="#aat" key="300055021">incunabulum (book)</objectType>
<objectType source="#aat" key="300265438">folio (fo)</objectType>
<supportDesc material="paper">
<support>
<material type="paper" subtype="royal" source="#aat" key="300265462">Royal paper</material>
</support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
          <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">La Commedia (Comm. Martin Paolo Nidobeato):</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-INCU-19561/1">19561</ref></p></cell>
      </row>
    </table>
    <p>Bibliographic formats such as folio (fo), quarto (4to), and octavo (8vo), and paper sizes such as imperial and royal, describe different characteristics of a printed book and should be encoded separately. Bibliographic format refers to how a sheet has been folded to create the leaves of a volume, whereas paper size refers to the dimensions of the original sheet before folding. Where both are known, both may be recorded. For example, a <hi rend="italic">royal folio</hi> consists of a sheet of royal paper folded once. Include whichever is relevant, based on context and the information available in ALMA.</p>
    <table rend="rules">
      <row>
        <cell><p>bibliographic format (how the sheet was folded)</p></cell>
        <cell><p>paper size (the original size of the sheet)</p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p><code>quarto (4to)</code></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | octavo | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300265439">300265439</ref></p></cell>
        <cell><p><code>imperial</code></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | imperial (paper size) | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300265456">300265456</ref></p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p><code>octavo (8vo)</code></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | octavo | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300265440">300265440</ref></p></cell>
        <cell><p><code>royal</code></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | royal (paper size) | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300265462">300265462</ref></p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p><code>folio (fo)</code></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | folio | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300265438">300265438</ref></p></cell>
        <cell><p><code>medium | median</code></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | medium (paper size) | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300265461">300265461</ref></p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p><code>duodecimo (12mo)</code></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | twelvemo | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300265445">300265445</ref></p></cell>
        <cell><p><code>chancery</code></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | n/a</p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p><code>sextodecimo (16mo)</code></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | sixteenmo | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300265441">300265441</ref></p></cell>
        <cell><p><code>crown</code></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | crown (paper size) | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300265463">300265463</ref></p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p><code>vigesimo-quarto (24mo)</code></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | twenty-fourmo | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300265447">300265447</ref></p></cell>
        <cell><p><code>demy</code></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | demy | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300265460">300265460</ref></p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p><code>trigesimo-secundo (32mo)</code></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | thirty-twomo | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300265442">300265442</ref></p></cell>
        <cell><p><code>post</code></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | post (paper size | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300265457">300265457</ref></p></cell>
      </row>
    </table>
    <p>Unless you must preserve historical specificity, use the British traditional set as your standard: imperial, royal, medium (median), chancery, crown, demy, post, etc.</p>
    <table rend="rules">
      <row>
        <cell><p rend="right">codex | book</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Codex</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Type:</hi> Book; Lithographic book (chap-i sangī)</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Paper</p>
          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="codex">
<objectType source="#aat" key="300028051">book</objectType>
<objectType>lithographic book (chap-i sangī)</objectType>
<supportDesc material="paper">
<support>
<material source="#aat" key="300014109">Paper</material>
</support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | book | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300028051">300028051</ref></p>
          <p rend="right">local (in-house) | lithographic book (chap-i sangī)</p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p rend="right">codex | scrapbook</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Codex</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Type:</hi> Scrapbook</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Paper</p>
          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="codex">
<objectType source="#aat" key="300027341">scrapbook</objectType>
<supportDesc material="paper">
<support>
<material source="#aat" key="300014109">Paper</material>
</support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | scrapbooks | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300027341">300027341</ref></p>
          <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Scrapbook with newspaper cuttings and photographs:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-GASTER-SAMARITAN-ADD-00015/1">Gaster Samaritan MS Add 15</ref></p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p rend="right">codex | compilation manuscript</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Codex</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Compilation manuscript</p>
          <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Paper</p>
          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="codex">
<objectType source="#aat" key="300403970">compilation manuscript</objectType>
<supportDesc material="paper">
<support><material source="#aat" key="300014109">Paper</material></support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | compilation manuscripts | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300403970">300403970</ref></p>
          <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">The Pupil:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-SIM-00001/1">SIM/1</ref></p>
          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<!----- <objectType key="300391488">Sammelband (composite volume)</objectType> | for composite, multipart items: the volume consists of separately produced units subsequently combined into a single volume. ----->
.]]></egXML></p></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><p rend="right">codex | photograph album</p>
            <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Codex</p>
            <p><hi rend="bold">• Type:</hi> Photograph album</p>
            <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Paper</p>
            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<objectDesc form="codex>
<objectType source="#aat" key="300026695">photograph album</objectType>
<supportDesc material="paper">
<support>
<material source="#aat" key="300014109">Paper</material>
</support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc>]]></egXML></p>
            <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | photograph albums | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300026695">300026695</ref></p>
            <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Album 'commenced Nov. 26th 1857':</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-JA-00033-00001-00001/1">JA/33/1/1</ref></p></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><p>When individual sheets are mounted in a codex, such as a photograph album, they retain the physical form of sheets. If each item is described as a distinct unit using <gi>msPart</gi>, use <code>&lt;objectDesc</code> <code>form="sheet"&gt;</code> within each <gi>msPart</gi>. The codex structure applies only to the container volume, not to the mounted components.</p></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><p rend="right">codex | sheet — photograph album | photographic prints</p>
            <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Sheet</p>
            <p><hi rend="bold">• Type:</hi> Photographic print</p>
            <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Paper</p>
            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="sheet">
<objectType source="#aat" key="300127104">photographic print</objectType>
<supportDesc material="paper">
<support>
<material source="#aat" key="300014109">Paper</material>
</support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
            <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | photographic prints | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300127104">300127104</ref></p>
            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><!-- To UPDATE WHEN LIVE--> Album 'commenced Nov. 26th 1857': JA/33/1/1</egXML></p></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><p rend="right">sheet | albumen print</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Sheet</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Type:</hi> Albumen print</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Albumen paper</p>
              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="sheet">
<objectType source="#aat" key="300127121">albumen print</objectType>
<supportDesc material="paper">
<support>
<material type="paper" subtype="albumen" source="#aat" key="300411855">Albumen paper</material></support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
              <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | albumen print | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300127121">300127121</ref></p></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><p rend="right">sheet | glass plate negative</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Sheet</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Type:</hi> Glas plate negative</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Glass</p>
              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="sheet">
<objectType source="#aat" key="300393160">glass plate negative</objectType>
<supportDesc material="glass">
<support>
<material source="#aat" key="300010797">Glass</material>
</support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
