<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
              <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | amulets | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300266585">300266585</ref></p>
              <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Amulet for protection and success (fragment):</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-GASTER-AMULET-00104/1">Gaster Amulet 104</ref></p>
              <p><hi rend="italic">Object type = amulet → functional role: protective talisman.</hi></p>
              <p><hi rend="italic">Amulet = Protective object worn on the person (may also attract good fortune).</hi></p>
              <p><hi rend="italic">Talisman = Protective/healing object, not necessarily worn, often inscribed with magical or astrological symbols.</hi></p></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><p rend="right">leaf | single manuscript leaf</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Leaf</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Type:</hi> Manuscript</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Parchment</p>
              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="leaf">
<objectType source="#aat" key="300028569">manuscript</objectType>
<supportDesc material="parchment">
<support>
<material source="#aat" key="300011851">Parchment</material>
</support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
              <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | leaves (gathered matter) | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300115833">300115833</ref></p>
              <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Missing leaf | Psalm 118:71–89:</hi>  <ref target="https://digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00022/347">Latin MS 22 A</ref></p>
              <p><hi rend="italic">Object type = manuscript → the document type the leaf is part of.</hi></p></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><p rend="right">ostrakon | inscribed pottery fragment</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Ostracon</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Ceramic</p>
              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="ostracon">
<supportDesc material="ceramic">
<support><material source="#aat" key="300235507">Ceramic</material></support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
              <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | ostraka | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300185396">300185396</ref></p>
              <p><hi rend="italic">Object type = letter | receipt | inscription → semantic type depending on content.</hi></p></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><p rend="right">scroll | rolled manuscript</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Roll</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Type:</hi> Megillat Esther</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Parchment</p>
              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="roll">
<objectType source="#aat" key="300028629">scroll</objectType>
<objectType>Megillat Esther</objectType>
<supportDesc material="parchment">
<support>
<material source="#aat" key="300011851">Parchment</material>
</support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
              <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | scrolls (information artifacts) | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300028629">300028629</ref></p>
              <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Esther scroll:</hi>  <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-HEBREW-00022/1">Hebrew MS 22</ref></p>
              <p><hi rend="italic">Object type = Megillat Esther → functional role: Jewish liturgical manuscript.</hi></p>
              <p><hi rend="italic">Manuscript → Generic handwritten scroll (content not otherwise specified).
                  Other examples of liturgical scrolls include Torah scrolls (Jewish scripture used in worship), Sutra scrolls (Buddhist scripture) and other ceremonial scripture scrolls.
                  Other examples for scrolls more broadly include charter, decree, map, genealogy, plan, poem, music rolls depending on the scroll’s content and purpose.</hi></p></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><p rend="right">sheet | map</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Sheet</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Type:</hi> Map</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Paper</p>
              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="sheet">
<objectType source="#aat" key="300028094">map</objectType>
<supportDesc material="paper">
<support>
<material source="#aat" key="300014109">Paper</material>
</support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
              <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | maps (documents) | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300028094">300028094</ref></p>
              <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">The drink map of Manchester:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-C-00017-00070-MANCHESTER-00003/1">C17:70 Manchester (3)</ref></p>
              <p><hi rend="italic">Object type = map → functional category.</hi></p>
              <p><hi rend="italic">Other examples of documents on sheets include chart, plan, diagram, poster, print, broadside and letter.</hi></p></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><p rend="right">sheet | lithograph</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Sheet</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Type:</hi> Lithographic engraving (print)</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Paper</p>
              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="sheet">
<objectType source="#aat" key="300254773">lithographic engraving (print)</objectType>
<supportDesc material="paper">
<support>
<material source="#aat" key="300014109">Paper</material>
</support>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
              <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | lithographic engravings (prints) | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300254773">300254773</ref></p>
              <p>Object type = lithographic engraving (print) → functional category.</p></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><p rend="right">tablet | cuneiform tablet</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Format:</hi> Tablet</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Type:</hi> Writing tablet</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Material(s):</hi> Clay</p>
              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><objectDesc form="tablet">
<objectType source="#aat" key="300262572">writing tablet</objectType>
<supportDesc material="clay">
<material source="#aat" key="300010439">clay</material>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</supportDesc>
</objectDesc></egXML></p>
              <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | writing tablets (information artifacts) | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300262572">300262572</ref></p>
              <p>Object type = writing tablet → functional category.</p></cell>
          </row>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="supportDesc">
        <head><code>&lt;supportDesc&gt;</code> | support description</head>
        <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-supportDesc.html"><gi>supportDesc</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(support description) groups elements describing the physical support for the written part of a manuscript or other object.</hi></p>
        <p><gi>supportDesc</gi> within <gi>objectDesc</gi> should appear immediately after <gi>objectType</gi>, if present, or otherwise directly after its start tag. It is used to describe the material that forms the physical support of an item.</p>
        <p><gi>supportDesc</gi> should include <att>material</att> to record the principal support material of the item.</p>
        <p rend="attHead"><code>@material</code></p>
        <p><att>material</att> (material) a short project-defined name for the material composing the majority of the support.</p>
        <p>A corresponding description of the material should also be encoded using <gi>material</gi> within <gi>support</gi>. The value recorded in <att>material</att> may be repeated there and, where appropriate, further refined or described in greater detail.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="support">
        <head><code>&lt;support&gt;</code> | support</head>
        <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-support.html"><gi>support</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(support) contains a description of the materials etc. which make up the physical support for the written part of a manuscript or other object.</hi></p>
        <p><gi>support</gi> within <gi>supportDesc</gi> should be used to provide additional descriptive detail about the physical support. This may include not just the type of material, but also its appearance, condition, method of preparation, or other notable features.</p>
        <p>If the content within <gi>support</gi> consists of more than one sentence or requires a fuller narrative description, use one or more <gi>p</gi> to contain the text.</p>
        <p>The support material should be specified using <gi>material</gi>.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="material">
        <head><code>&lt;material&gt;</code> | material</head>
        <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-material.html"><gi>material</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(material) contains a word or phrase describing the material of which the object being described is composed.</hi></p>
        <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Material(s)</hi></p>
        <p>Although <gi>material</gi> is a phrase-level element and could theoretically be used wherever a material is referenced, such as within <gi>binding</gi> and <gi>seal</gi>, its use is restricted to <gi>support</gi>.</p>
        <p>In this context, <gi>material</gi> provides the textual form of the controlled value used in <att>material</att>. Both <att>material</att> and <gi>material</gi> should use standardised vocabulary wherever possible.</p>
        <p>The material of the physical support should be encoded using <gi>material</gi>. When applicable, it must include both <att>source</att> and <att>key</att>.</p>
        <p rend="attHead"><code>@source @key</code></p>
        <p><att>source</att> specifies the source from which some aspect of this element is drawn.</p>
        <p><att>key</att> provides a persistent, unique identifier for the named entity, supplied by that source.</p>
        <p><att>source</att> and <att>key</att> should together provide a unique identifier for the material from a recognised authority file. The preferred source is the Getty Art &amp; Architecture Thesaurus (AAT).</p>
        <table rend="rules">
          <row>
            <cell><p><val>aat</val></p></cell>
            <cell><p>Getty Art &amp; Architecture Thesaurus® (AAT)</p></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell cols="2"><p>The <ref target="https://www.getty.edu/research/tools/vocabularies/aat/">Getty Art &amp; Architecture Thesaurus® (AAT)</ref> is a structured vocabulary, including terms, descriptions, and other metadata for generic concepts related to art, architecture, conservation, archaeology, and other cultural heritage. Included are work types, styles, materials, techniques, and others.</p>
              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><taxonomy xml:id="aat">
<bibl><ref target="https://www.getty.edu/research/tools/vocabularies/aat">Getty Art &amp; Architecture Thesaurus® (AAT)</ref></bibl>
</taxonomy></egXML></p></cell>
            </row>
          </table>
          <p>When the value <code>#aat</code> is used for <code>@source,</code> it indicates that the identifier recorded in <att>key</att> is drawn from this authority file. The prefix <code>#</code> indicates a reference to an identifier defined elsewhere in <gi>msDesc</gi>. In this case, it refers to the <gi>taxonomy</gi> declared in the header with <att>xml:id</att>=<val>aat</val>. This value can be selected from a controlled dropdown list when entering the attribute and does not need to be typed manually.</p>
          <p><gi>material</gi> may include <att>type</att>, and <att>subtype</att> may also be used where further sub-classification is required.</p>
          <p rend="right"><att>type</att> | <att>subtype</att></p>
          <p><att>type</att> provides the primary classification of the material.</p>
          <p><att>subtype</att> provides a further sub-classification of that material.</p>
          <p>The following values should be used for <att>material</att> and <gi>material</gi>.</p>
          <table rend="rules">
            <row>
              <cell><p><att>material</att></p></cell>
              <cell><p><gi>material</gi> | <att>type</att> | <att>subtype</att></p></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><p><val>bamboo</val></p>
                <p rend="right">bamboo</p></cell>
              <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><material source="#aat" key="300011873">bamboo</material></egXML></p>
              <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | bamboo (material) | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300011873">300011873</ref></p></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><p><val>bark</val></p>
              <p rend="right">birch bark</p></cell>
            <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><material type="bark" subtype="birch" source="#aat" key="300379355">birch bark</material></egXML></p>
            <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | birch bark (plant material) | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300379355">300379355</ref></p></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><p><val>bone</val></p>
            <p rend="right">bone</p></cell>
          <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><material source="#aat" key="300011798">bone</material></egXML></p>
          <p rend="right">GETTY (AAT) | bone (material) | ID:<ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/aat/300011798">300011798</ref></p></cell>
      </row>
