<p>The distinction between Latin-script and non-Latin-script manuscripts used here is a technical one based on the writing system rather than on current geopolitical boundaries or cultural hierarchies. Scripts are grouped according to their palaeographical lineage and graphic form, so a manuscript is treated as non-Latin-script whenever it is written wholly or predominantly in a script other than the Latin alphabet.</p>
<p>A single hand (or scribe) is responsible for the entire text, written in a single script that remains uniform throughout.</p>
<table rend="rules">
  <row>
    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Script:</hi></p>
      <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Written in <hi rend="italic">textualis rotunda</hi> by a single hand.</p>
      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><handDesc hands="1">
<handNote scope="sole" script="textualisSouthern" medium="ink">
<p>Written in <term type="script">textualis rotunda</term> by a single hand.</p>
</handNote>
</handDesc></egXML></p>
      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Colonna Missal II</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00032-A/1">Latin MS 32a</ref></p></cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Script:</hi></p>
      <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Written in <hi rend="italic">kurrent</hi> (Kurrentschrift) by a single hand. Alchemical symbols are consistently rendered in red throughout.</p>
      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><handDesc hands="1">
<handNote scope="sole" script="kurrent" medium="ink">
<p>Written in <term type="script">kurrent</term> (Kurrentschrift) by a single hand. Alchemical symbols are consistently rendered in red throughout.</p>
</handNote>
</handDesc></egXML></p>
      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Sammlung Alchymistischer Schriften</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-GERMAN-00003/1">German MS 3</ref></p></cell>
  </row>
</table>
<p>More than one distinct hand has been identified, all using the same script. This can be encoded using <gi>summary</gi> within <gi>handDesc</gi>, followed by one <gi>handNote</gi> for each hand. Each <gi>handNote</gi> must include <att>xml:id</att> and one or more &lt;p&gt;. Where appropriate, <gi>locus</gi> may be used to indicate the folio range where the hand appears. <att>xml:id</att> should take values such as <val>hand1</val>, <val>hand2</val>, <val>hand3</val>, numbered in the order in which the hands appear.</p>
<table rend="rules">
  <row>
    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Script:</hi></p>
      <p>Written in <hi rend="italic">northern textualis</hi> script by two hands, the manuscript is punctuated throughout with punctus elevatus, punctus interrogativus, and punctus, the latter used to mark metrum, minor pauses, and the ends of verses.</p>
      <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> 4r–84v written in <hi rend="italic">textualis semi-quadrata</hi> by the first hand.
        <hi rend="bold">•</hi> 85r–168r written in <hi rend="italic">textualis semi-quadrata</hi> by the second hand.</p>
      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><handDesc hands="2">
<summary>Written in <hi rend="italic">northern textualis</hi> by two hands, the manuscript is punctuated throughout with punctus elevatus, punctus interrogativus, and punctus, the latter used to mark metrum, minor pauses, and the ends of verses.</summary>
<handNote xml:id="hand1" scope="major" script="textualisNorthern" medium="ink">
<p><locus from="4r" to="84v">4r–84v</locus> written in <term type="script">textualis semi-quadrata</term> by the first hand.</p>
</handNote>
<handNote xml:id="hand2" scope="major" script="textualisNorthern" medium="ink">
<p><locus from="85r" to="168r">85r–168r</locus> written in <term type="script">textualis semi-quadrata</term> by the second hand.</p>
</handNote>
</handDesc></egXML></p>
      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Psalter of Joan of Navarre</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00022/1">Latin MS 22</ref></p></cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Script:</hi></p>
      <p>Written in k<hi rend="italic">urrent</hi> (Kurrentschrift) by four hands.</p>
      <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> The first and largest section of the letter is written in the hand of Heinrich's father, Herrmann Simon.</p>
      <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> The second section is written in the hand of Heinrich's Heinrich's mother, Minna Simon.</p>
      <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> The third section is written in the hand of Heinrich's brother, Gustav Simon.</p>
      <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> The fourth section is written in the hand of Heinrich's sister, Julie Simon.</p>
      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><handDesc hands="4">
<summary>Written in <term type="script">kurrent</term> (Kurrentschrift) by four hands.</summary>
<handNote xml:id="hand1" scope="major" script="kurrent">
<p>The first and largest section of the letter is written in the hand of Heinrich's father, Herrmann Simon.</p>
</handNote>
<handNote xml:id="hand2" scope="minor" script="kurrent">
<p>The second section is written in the hand of Heinrich's Heinrich's mother, Minna Simon.</p>
</handNote>
<handNote xml:id="hand3" scope="minor" script="kurrent">
<p>The third section is written in the hand of Heinrich's brother, Gustav Simon.</p>
</handNote>
<handNote xml:id="hand4" scope="minor" script="kurrent">
<p>The fourth section is written in the hand of Heinrich's sister, Julie Simon. </p>
</handNote>
</handDesc></egXML></p>
      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Letter to Heinrich Simon from Herrmann, Minna, Gustav, and Julie Simon</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-SIM-00002-00142/1">SIM/2/142</ref></p></cell>
  </row>
</table>
<p>In the example above, the names are not encoded because this is a correspondence letter. The senders' names are already properly encoded as authors within <gi>correspDesc</gi> under <code>&lt;correspAction type="send"&gt;&lt;name role="aut"&gt;...&lt;/name&gt;</code>.</p>
<p>More than one distinct hand has been identified, with more than one script used across the manuscript.</p>
<table rend="rules">
  <row>
    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Script:</hi></p>
      <p>Written by three different hands. Headings are in red and black ink, sometimes omitted</p>
      <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> 1b-6b written in black ink in a neat <hi rend="italic">naskh</hi> script.
        <hi rend="bold">•</hi> 7a-118b written in black ink in <hi rend="italic">nasta‘līq</hi> script.</p>
      <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> 119a-309a written in black ink in a different, more legible <hi rend="italic">nasta‘līq</hi> script.</p>
      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><handDesc hands="3">
<summary>Written by three different hands. Headings are in red and black ink, sometimes omitted.</summary>
<handNote xml:id="hand1" scope="minor" script="naskh" medium="ink">
<p><locus from="1b" to="6b">1b-6b</locus> written in black ink in a neat <term type="script">naskh</term> script.</p>
</handNote>
<handNote xml:id="hand2" scope="minor" script="nastaliq" medium="ink">
<p><locus from="7a" to="118b">7a-118b</locus> written in black ink in <term type="script">nasta‘līq</term> script.</p>
</handNote>
<handNote xml:id="hand3" scope="major" script="nastaliq" medium="ink">
<p><locus from="119a" to="309a">119a-309a</locus> written in black ink in a different, more legible <term type="script">nasta‘līq</term> script.</p>
</handNote>
</handDesc></egXML></p>
      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Galen's On the Usefulness of the Parts of the Body</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-ARABIC-00780/1">Arabic MS 780</ref></p></cell>
  </row>
</table>
<p>Where the scribe is known, their name should be encoded using <code>&lt;name role="scr"&gt;&lt;persName/&gt;&lt;/name&gt;</code>. If the personal name is listed in VIAF, include both <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> on <gi>name</gi> to reference the appropriate VIAF authority record. Where an authority-controlled form is available, or where a distinction between display and indexed forms is required, include both <code>&lt;persName type="display"&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;persName type="standard"&gt;</code> within <gi>name</gi>. Otherwise, a single <gi>persName</gi> within <gi>name</gi> may be used.</p>
<table rend="rules">
  <row>
    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Scribe(s):</hi> Paolo</p>
      <p>—</p>
      <p><hi rend="bold">• Script:</hi></p>
      <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Written in <hi rend="italic">textualis rotunda</hi> by a single hand, identified in the colophon on 174r as the work of the scribe Paolo.</p>
      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><handDesc hands="1">
<handNote scope="sole" script="textualisSouthern" medium="ink">
<p>Written in <term type="script">textualis rotunda</term> by a single hand, identified in the colophon on <locus from="174r" to="174r">174r</locus> as the work of the scribe <name role="scr"><persName>Paolo</persName></name>.</p>
</handNote>
</handDesc></egXML></p>
      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Il Canzoniere di Petrarca e Le Rime di Dante</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-ITALIAN-00001/1">Italian MS 1</ref></p></cell>
  </row>
</table>
<p>Where it is not feasible to encode a scribe within <gi>handDesc</gi>, for example, when their name appears in multiple forms due to transliteration, translation, or script variation, the use of <gi>editor</gi> within <gi>msItem</gi> is acceptable. In such instances, <code>&lt;editor role="scr"&gt;</code> follows the same principles outlined in the section on <gi>author</gi> name variants &lt;!--insert hyperlink to that section --&gt;.</p>
<p>The following encoding is incorrect because it combines multiple scripts within a single <gi>handNote</gi>.</p>
<p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><handDesc>
<handNote scope="major" script="nastaliq naskh" medium="ink">Written in very clear, neat black nasta‘līq script, with Arabic passages in naskh, often in red, as well as other subheaders.
</handNote>
</handDesc></egXML></p>
<p>Each script should be described in its own <gi>handNote</gi>. The main text may be encoded in a <code>&lt;handNote scope="major"&gt;</code>, while the <hi rend="italic">naskh</hi> script used for Arabic passages, headings, or other subsidiary text should be described in a separate <code>&lt;handNote scope="minor"&gt;</code>.</p>
<p rend="attHead"><code>&lt;handNote&gt; @medium</code></p>
<p><att>medium</att> describes the type of ink or other writing medium.</p>
<p><att>medium</att> on <gi>handNote</gi> may be used to record the writing medium employed by a particular hand. Its values identify the substance used, most commonly <val>ink</val>, but may also refer to other writing materials such as <val>pencil</val>, where this was used for the main hand.</p>
<p>In most cases, it is <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> necessary to specify ink colour. Ink may be assumed unless there is a specific reason to identify the colour or type of ink. Where it is necessary to specify colour or type, and where this is known with certainty, <att>medium</att> value should be encoded in camelCase, without spaces, for example, <val>inkBlack</val> for colour or <val>inkIronGall</val> for ink type.</p>
<p>In addition to <att>medium</att>, <code>&lt;term type="medium"&gt;</code> may optionally be included within the prose content of <gi>handNote</gi>. This is useful for historically specific, culturally specific, or source-specific terminology, such as India ink, sumi ink. When available, <code>&lt;term type="medium"&gt;</code> may include <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> with the relevant AAT identifier.</p>
<table rend="rules">
  <row>
    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Script:</hi></p>
      <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Written in carbon black, India ink.</p>
      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><handDesc hands="1">
<handNote scope="sole" medium="inkCarbonBlack">
<p>Written in carbon black, <term type="medium" source="#aat" key="300015018">India ink</term>.</p>
</handNote>
</handDesc></egXML></p></cell>
    </row>
  </table>
  <p rend="right">Rubrication and ink colour</p>
  <p>Aspects of the item relating to the presentation or structuring of the text, such as rubrication, should <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> be encoded in <att>medium</att>. Rubrication refers to the use of coloured inks, not limited to red, to mark headings, structural divisions, or other paratextual elements. These should instead be described in <gi>decoDesc</gi> using <code>&lt;decoNote type="rubrication"&gt;</code>.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Script:</hi></p>
        <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Written in black ink in a neat naskh script.</p>
        <p>—</p>
        <p><hi rend="bold">• Decoration:</hi></p>
        <p>Subheadings and instructions written in red ink.</p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><handDesc hands="1">
<handNote scope="sole" script="naskh" medium="inkBlack">
<p>Written in <term type="medium" source="#aat" key="300015012">black ink</term> in a neat <term type="script">naskh</term> script.</p>
</handNote>
</handDesc>
<!-- additional metadata -->
<decoDesc>
<decoNote type="rubrication">
<p>Subheadings and instructions written in <term type="medium">red ink</term>.</p>
</decoNote>
</decoDesc></egXML></p></cell>
      </row>
    </table>
    <p>Non-ink media, such as pencil or crayon, may be recorded in <att>medium</att> where they are used by the hand being described. Later additions, annotations, corrections, or other interventions, where they are not part of the original scribal hand responsible for the main text, should normally be described in <gi>additions</gi> or elsewhere within <gi>physDesc</gi>, as appropriate.</p>
    <p>The following <att>medium</att> and <code>&lt;term</code> <code>type="medium"&gt;</code> values are recommended, together with AAT identifiers where an appropriate match is available.</p>
    <table rend="rules">
      <row>
        <cell><p><att>medium</att></p></cell>
        <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<term type="medium">]]></egXML></p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p><val>ink</val></p>
          <p rend="right">ink</p></cell>
        <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><term type="medium" source="#aat" key="300015012">ink</term></egXML></p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p><val>inkBlack</val></p>
          <p rend="right">black ink</p></cell>
        <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><term type="medium">black ink</term></egXML></p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p><val>inkIronGall</val></p>
          <p rend="right">iron gall ink</p></cell>
        <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><term type="medium" source="#aat" key="300015012">iron gall ink</term></egXML></p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p><val>inkCarbonBlack</val></p>
          <p rend="right">carbon black ink</p>
          <p rend="right">India ink</p>
          <p rend="right">Chinese ink</p>
          <p rend="right">sumi ink</p></cell>
        <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><term type="medium" source="#aat" key="300081180">carbon black ink</term>
<term type="medium" source="#aat" key="300015018">India ink</term>
<term type="medium" source="#aat" key="300015012">Chinese ink</term>
<term type="medium" source="#aat" key="300015012">sumi ink</term></egXML></p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p><val>inkSepia</val></p>
          <p rend="right">sepia ink</p></cell>
        <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><term type="medium" source="#aat" key="300015025">sepia ink</term></egXML></p></cell>
      </row>
    </table>
  </div>
  <div xml:id="typeDesc-typeNote">
    <head><code>&lt;typeDesc&gt;</code> | typeface description | <code>&lt;typeNote&gt;</code> | typographic note</head>
    <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release//doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-typeDesc.html"><gi>typeDesc</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(typeface description) contains a description of the typefaces or other aspects of the printing of an incunable or other printed source.</hi></p>
    <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release//doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-typeNote.html"><gi>typeNote</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(typographic note) describes a particular font or other significant typographic feature distinguished within the description of a printed resource.</hi></p>
    <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Typeface</hi></p>
    <p><gi>typeNote</gi> within <gi>typeDesc</gi> are used to describe the typographic features of a printed item, in a manner analogous to <gi>handDesc</gi> and <gi>handNote</gi>, which describe hands and scripts.</p>
    <p><gi>typeNote</gi> includes <att>scope</att>, and just as <gi>handNote</gi> may include <att>script</att> and <code>&lt;term type="script"&gt;</code>, in the context of printed items <gi>typeNote</gi> may include <att>typeface</att> and <code>&lt;term type="typeface"&gt;</code> to record the typeface.</p>
    <p rend="attHead"><code>@typeface</code></p>
    <p><att>typeface</att> characterises the particular typeface or letterform design used by the printer.</p>
    <p><att>typeface</att> is used for consistent, high-level typeface classification, following approved nomenclature. The following controlled values are suggested for <att>typeface</att>. Values may be further characterised using <code>&lt;term type="typeface"&gt;</code> within descriptive prose in <gi>p</gi>.</p>
    <table rend="rules">
      <row>
        <cell><p><att>typeface</att></p></cell>
        <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<term type="typeface">]]></egXML></p></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><p><val>blackletter</val></p>
          <p rend="right">blackletter type</p></cell>
        <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><term type="typeface">blackletter type</term></egXML></p>
        <p>Gothic-derived printing types.</p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><p><val>roman</val></p>
        <p rend="right">roman type</p></cell>
      <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><term type="typeface">roman type</term></egXML></p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><p><val>italic</val></p>
        <p rend="right">italic type</p></cell>
      <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><term type="typeface">italic type</term></egXML></p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><p><val>fraktur</val></p>
        <p rend="right">fraktur type</p></cell>
      <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><term type="typeface">fraktur type</term></egXML></p>
      <p>German blackletter type, distinct from generic blackletter.</p></cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell><p><val>civilite</val></p>
      <p rend="right">civilité type</p></cell>
    <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><term type="typeface">civilité type</term></egXML></p>
    <p>French cursive type, used mainly for French-language works, primers, proclamations</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p><val>financiere</val></p>
    <p rend="right">financière type</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><term type="typeface">financière type</term></egXML></p>
  <p>French cursive type associated with vernacular printing.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p><val>other</val></p></cell>
  <cell><p><code>N/A</code></p>
    <p>For clearly identifiable typefaces outside the current controlled vocabulary.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p><val>unknown</val></p></cell>
  <cell><p><code>N/A</code></p>
    <p>Used when the typeface cannot be securely identified.</p></cell>
</row>
</table>
<p>Printers are normally encoded using <code>&lt;editor role="prt"&gt;</code>, particularly in MARC-derived metadata and retroconversion workflows. Where a printer is directly relevant to the typographic description, their name may also be encoded within <gi>typeface</gi>, following the same convention as in <gi>handNote</gi>, using <code>&lt;name role="prt"&gt;&lt;persName&gt;&lt;/name&gt;</code>. Printers may also be recorded elsewhere, for example, within <gi>origin</gi> using <code>&lt;note type= "printersDevice"&gt;</code>, as printer's devices are generally treated as evidence for the book's printer, place of production, and origin.</p>
<table rend="rules">
  <row>
    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Printer(s):</hi> Caxton, William, approximately 1422-1491 or 1492</p>
      <p>—</p>
      <p><hi rend="bold">• Typeface:</hi></p>
      <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Printed by William Caxton (approximately 1422-1491 or 1492) using Type 6:120G, a <hi rend="italic">blackletter type</hi>.</p>
      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<typeDesc>
<typeNote scope="sole" typeface="blackletter">
<p>Printed by <name role="#viaf" key="68979076" role="prt"><persName type="display">William Caxton (approximately 1422-1491 or 1492)</persName><persName type="standard">Caxton, William, approximately 1422-1491 or 1492</persName></name> Type 6:120G, a <term type="typeface">blackletter type</term>.</p>
</typeNote>
</typeDesc>]]></egXML></p></cell>
    </row>
  </table>
  <p>Within <gi>typeDesc</gi>, each <gi>typeNote</gi> should describe a single printing feature. In its simplest form, where only a single typographical characteristic is known, <gi>typeDesc</gi> may consist of a single <gi>typeNote</gi> containing <gi>p</gi>.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Typeface:</hi></p>
        <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Printed in <hi rend="italic">roman type</hi>.</p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><typeDesc>
<typeNote scope="sole" typeface="roman">
<p>Printed in <term type="typeface">roman type</term>.</p>
</typeNote>
</typeDesc></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Le terze rime di Dante</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-ALDI-18873/1">18873</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
  </table>
  <p>A single <gi>typeNote</gi> is used when all the observations concern one typographical feature. In this case, the feature is the typeface, defined as the design of the type used in printing, such as roman or italic. All details, including where the italic type appears and how particular characters are set on specific leaves, relate directly to this single feature. Because the notes describe only the use and behaviour of the italic typeface, they belong together within one <gi>typeNote</gi>.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Typeface:</hi></p>
        <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Printed in <hi rend="italic">italic type</hi>. Line 3 of the title on [pi1r] ends <hi rend="italic">De-</hi>, and line 1 on [pi2r] ends <hi rend="italic">et</hi>.</p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<typeDesc>
<typeNote scope="sole" typeface="italic">
<p>Printed in <term type="typeface">italic type</term>. Line 3 of the title on
<locus from="[pi1r]" to="[pi1r]">[pi1r]</locus> ends <hi rend="italic">De=</locus>, and line 2 on <locus from="[pi2r]" to="[pi2r]">pi2r</locus> begins <hi rend="italic">et</locus>.</p>
</typeNote>
</typeDesc>]]></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Dante col sito, et forma dell'inferno tratta dalla istessa descrittione del poeta</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-ALDI-R-00002-13743/1">R213743</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
  </table>
  <p>A single <gi>typeNote</gi> may record both the typeface, defined as the design of the type used in printing, such as roman or italic, and any variant states arising during printing, such as omissions, stop-press corrections, or substitutions in the typesetting. Combining these observations keeps the typographical information for a given impression together within <gi>typeDesc</gi>.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Typeface:</hi></p>
        <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Printed in <hi rend="italic">italic type</hi>.</p>
        <p>Variant A: three lines in Purgatorio II, 64-66 on V7r have been omitted.</p>
        <p>Variant B: the missing lines in Purgatorio II, 64-66 on V7r have been added by hand-printing.</p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><typeDesc>
<typeNote scope="sole" typeface="italic">
<p>Printed in <term type="typeface">italic type</term>.</p>
<p>Variant A: three lines in Purgatorio II, 64-66 on <locus from="v7r" to="V7r">V7r</locus> have been omitted.</p>
<p>Variant B: the missing lines in Purgatorio II, 64-66 on <locus from="v7r" to="V7r">V7r</locus> have been added by hand-printing.</p>
</typeNote>
</typeDesc></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">La Comedia di Dante Aligieri [sic] con la noua espositione di Alessandro Vellutello</hi> : <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-SPCC-R-52857/1">R52857</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
  </table>
  <p><gi>typeDesc</gi> may include <gi>summary</gi> with one or more <gi>p</gi> giving a general account of the typography, such as noting a mixture of roman or italic types, followed by separate <gi>typeNote</gi> for each typographical feature. Where appropriate, <gi>locus</gi> may be used to indicate where each typeface occurs. Where this level of detail is unavailable, as is often the case with MARC-derived metadata, it is acceptable to use a single <gi>typeNote</gi> to record the typographical information supplied by the source record.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Typeface:</hi></p>
        <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Printed in <hi rend="italic">italic type</hi>, <hi rend="italic">italic type</hi> and <hi rend="italic">roman type</hi>.</p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><typeDesc>
<typeNote>
<p>Printed <term type="typeface">roman type</term> and <term type="typeface">italic type</term>.</p>
</typeNote>
</typeDesc></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Dante con nuoue, et utili ispositioni. Aggiuntoui di più una ...</hi> : <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-BULL-00611/1">611</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
  </table>
  <p>Unless stated in the MARC, record only the typeface of the main text and ignore brief or peripheral sections set in a different typeface. If the core text is set in one typeface, such as italic, and smaller sections not integral to the main text, such as headings, title-page words, privileges, colophons, or similar paratexts, appear in another typeface, only the typeface of the main text is recorded. These minor sections do not constitute separate typographical features.</p>
  <p>Where information is required about both typography and written script, <gi>handDesc</gi> and <gi>typeDesc</gi> should be supplied. The same applies when the source is a typescript that includes significant handwritten content.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Typeface:</hi></p>
        <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Written in <hi rend="italic">kurrent</hi> (Kurrentschrift), in the hand of an unidentified school teacher.</p>
        <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Signature in the hand of Herrmann Simon.</p>
        <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Printed in <hi rend="italic">fraktur</hi> (Frakturschrift).</p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<handDesc hands="2">
<handNote xml:id="hand1" scope="major" script="kurrent">
<p>Written in <term type="script">kurrent</term> (Kurrentschrift), in the hand of an unidentified school teacher.</p>
</handNote>
<handNote xml:id="hand2" scope="minor" script="kurrent>
<p>Signature in the hand of Herrmann Simon.</p>
</handNote>
<typeDesc>
<typeNote>
<p>Printed <term type="typeface">fraktur</term> (Frakturschrift).</p>
</typeNote>
</typeDesc>]]></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right">Weekly school report for Heinrich Simon from the Königliches Friedrichs-Gymnasium zu Breslau: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-SIM-00001-00001-A/1">SIM/1/1a</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
  </table>
</div>
<div xml:id="musicNotation">
  <head><code>&lt;musicNotation&gt;</code> | music notation</head>
  <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release//doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-musicNotation.html"><gi>musicNotation</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(music notation) contains description of type of musical notation.</hi></p>
  <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Music notation</hi></p>
  <p><gi>musicNotation</gi> is used to record any musical notation found in an item. It may describe the type of notation, such as neumatic, mensural, modern, or staffless notation, its appearance or layout, such as a four-line staff, red lines, or square notation, or its function within the item.</p>
  <p>Music notation should be described in <gi>p</gi>, using <gi>locus</gi> where relevant. Where more than one type of notation is present, use a separate <gi>p</gi> for each type.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Music notation:</hi></p>
        <p>Black square notation on 3- and 4-line red staves on 4r, 8v-12r, 19v, 26r-29r, 44v, 55r, 65r-68v, 80v-83v, 85v-86r.</p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><musicNotation>
<p>Black square notation on 3- and 4-line red staves on <locus from="4r" to="4r">4r</locus>, <locus from="8v" to="12r">8v-12r</locus>, <locus from="19v" to="19v">19v</locus>, <locus from="26r" to="29r">26r-29r</locus>, <locus from="44v" to="44v">44v</locus>, <locus from="55r" to="55r">55r</locus>, <locus from="65r" to="68v">65r-68v</locus>, <locus from="80v" to="83v">80v-83v</locus>, <locus from="85v" to="86r">85v-86r</locus>.</p>
</musicNotation></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right">Colonna Missal II: <ref target="https://https:/www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00032-A/1">Latin MS 32a</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
  </table>
</div>
<div xml:id="decoDesc">
  <head><code>&lt;decoDesc&gt;</code> | decoration description</head>
  <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-decoDesc.html"><gi>decoDesc</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(decoration description) contains a description of the decoration of a manuscript or other object, either as in paragraphs, or as one or more</hi> <gi>decoNote</gi> <hi rend="italic">elements.</hi></p>
  <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Decoration</hi></p>
  <p><gi>decoDesc</gi> is used to record the decorative features of an item, including visual and textual components such as illustrations, initials, borders, and rubrication.</p>
  <p><gi>decoDesc</gi> may contain <gi>summary</gi> with one or more <gi>p</gi> providing a general overview of the decorative programme, followed by a series of <gi>decoNote</gi>, each describing a particular aspect or class of decoration.</p>
</div>
<div xml:id="decoNote">
  <head><code>&lt;decoNote&gt;</code> | note on decoration</head>
  <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-decoNote.html"><gi>decoNote</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(note on decoration) contains a note describing either a decorative component of a manuscript or other object, or a fairly homogenous class of such components.</hi></p>
  <p>Within <gi>decoDesc</gi>, one or more <gi>decoNote</gi> should be used to organise the decoration into discrete categories, each treated as an independent unit of description. These should be arranged in a consistent, hierarchical order, beginning with illustrations (including miniatures), followed by initials (historiated or otherwise), then borders, and concluding with rubrication and other forms of textual decoration. Where decorative features are closely integrated, this order may be adapted to reflect the structure of the decorative programme, provided that clear categorisation is maintained.</p>
  <p>Where the decorative programme is closely integrated, however, this sequence may be adapted to reflect the structure of the material, for example, where borders are directly associated with specific initials. In such cases, the order of description should follow the most logical and coherent presentation of the decoration while maintaining clear categorisation.</p>
  <p>Each <gi>decoNote</gi> should include <att>type</att>, and <att>subtype</att> should also be used where further sub-classification is required.</p>
  <p rend="right"><att>type</att> | <att>subtype</att></p>
  <p><att>type</att> provides the primary classification of the decorative feature.</p>
  <p><att>subtype</att> provides a further sub-classification of that feature.</p>
  <p>When describing decoration, the following <att>type</att> and <att>subtype</att> values are recommended. All values should be encoded in the singular form, as they denote conceptual categories rather than multiple instances.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell cols="2"><p><gi>decoNote</gi> | <att>type</att> | <att>subtype</att></p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><p>illustrations</p></cell>
      <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<decoNote type="illustration">]]></egXML></p>
      <p>Any pictorial or graphic representations functioning as illustrations, applicable across different materials and disciplines. The use of <att>type</att>=<val>illustration</val> covers:</p>
      <list rend="bulleted">
        <item>Figural and non-figural illustrations.</item>
        <item>Ornamental full-page or marginal visual compositions.</item>
        <item>Diagrammatic representations.</item>
        <item>Tabular visual material described for its visual presentation rather than textual structure.</item>
        <item>May be used alone or refined with a <att>subtype</att>.</item>
      </list>
      <p>Extent may be described in prose: full-page | half-page | quarter-page.</p>
      <p>Placement, such as <hi rend="italic">marginal</hi> or <hi rend="italic">bas-de-page</hi>, should also be described in prose rather than encoded as <att>subtype</att> values, since they indicate spatial position or layout role rather than illustration class.</p></cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell><p>figurative illustrations</p></cell>
    <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<decoNote type="illustration" subtype="figurative">]]></egXML></p>
    <p>Pictorial illustrations treated as miniatures within manuscript traditions, typically an independent composition not incorporated into another decorative element such as a border or initial.</p>
    <p>The use of <att>subtype</att>=<val>figurative</val> covers:</p>
    <list rend="bulleted">
      <item>Figural or narrative illustrations depicting a scene or identifiable subject, particularly in medieval and Renaissance manuscripts.</item>
      <item>Standalone pictorial compositions, including full-page and smaller illustrations.</item>
      <item>Illustrations described in manuscript studies as miniatures, including medallions or roundels.</item>
    </list>
    <p>Extent may be described in prose: full-page | half-page | quarter-page.</p>
    <p>Placement such as marginal or bas-de-page should also be described in prose.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>ornamental illustrations</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<decoNote type="illustration" subtype="ornamental">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Non-figurative decorative illustrations treated as independent ornamental compositions rather than narrative or diagrammatic representations.</p>
  <p>The use of <att>subtype</att>=<val>ornamental</val> covers:</p>
  <list rend="bulleted">
    <item>Non-figural decorative compositions composed primarily of foliate, geometric, interlace, or abstract ornament.</item>
    <item>Carpet pages and similar full-page ornamental designs.</item>
    <item>Decorative frontispieces and ornamental title pages.</item>
    <item>Ornamental medallions, frames, or decorative visual programmes functioning primarily as embellishment.</item>
    <item>Headpieces, consisting of decorative illustrations or ornaments placed at the beginning of a chapter, section, or major textual division, including Islamic <hi rend="italic">‘unwān</hi> or <hi rend="italic">sarlawḥ</hi> headpieces.</item>
    <item>Tailpieces, consisting of decorative illustrations or ornaments positioned at the end of a chapter, section, or major textual division.</item>
  </list>
  <p>Extent may be described in prose: full-page | half-page | quarter-page</p>
  <p>Placement such as marginal or bas-de-page should also be described in prose.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>diagrammatic illustrations</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<decoNote type="illustration" subtype="diagrammatic">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Graphic representation used to explain or organise information visually.</p>
  <p>The use of <att>subtype</att>=<val>diagrammatic</val> covers:</p>
  <list rend="bulleted">
    <item>Cosmological, genealogical, and astronomical diagrams, and other structured visual forms.</item>
  </list>
  <p><gi>layoutDesc</gi> may supplement the description where page design or spatial arrangement is significant, for example, in complex layouts such as the tree-structured diagram in <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00018/1">Latin MS 18</ref>.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>tabular</p>
    <p>illustrations</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<decoNote type="illustration" subtype="tabular">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Decorative concordance tables used in Gospel manuscripts, typically arranged in architectural frames to show parallel passages.</p>
  <p>The use of <att>subtype</att>=<val>tabular</val> covers:</p>
  <list rend="bulleted">
    <item>Canon tables and other concordance tables.</item>
    <item>Tables organised primarily for comparison, reference, or systematic arrangement of information.</item>
    <item>Tabular visual compositions structured through grids, columns, arcades, or compartmentalised frameworks.</item>
    <item>Genealogical, calendrical, computistical, or schematic tables when described for their visual presentation rather than their textual content.</item>
  </list></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>heraldic</p>
    <p>illustrations</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<decoNote type="illustration" subtype="heraldic">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Illustrations of a coat of arms or heraldic devices functioning as the primary illustrations, such as standalone heraldic devices or armorial manuscripts, for example, <hi rend="italic">Armorial</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00028/1">Latin MS 28</ref>. Where appropriate, heraldic content may also be encoded using <gi>heraldry</gi>. Heraldry indicating ownership or patronage should normally be recorded in <gi>provenance</gi>.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>historiated initials</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<decoNote type="initial" subtype="historiated">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Initials in which figures participate in identifiable actions or episodes, often related to the text. The use of <att>subtype</att>=<val>historiated</val> covers:</p>
  <list rend="bulleted">
    <item>Figural and narrative initials with recognisable scenes or subjects, including biblical, hagiographic, or allegorical themes.</item>
  </list>
  <p>Extent may be described in prose: 1-line | 2-line | 3-line etc.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>inhabited initials</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<decoNote type="initial" subtype="inhabited">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Initials in which figures of humans, animals, or hybrids occupy or embellish the letter without forming a narrative scene. The use of <att>subtype</att>=<val>inhabited</val> covers:</p>
  <list rend="bulleted">
    <item>Zoomorphic, anthropomorphic, or grotesque initials.</item>
  </list>
  <p>Extent may be described in prose: 1-line | 2-line | 3-line etc.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>decorated initials</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<decoNote type="initial" subtype="decorated">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Initials that incorporate ornament or decorative elaboration, without narrative or integrated figural subjects. The use of <att>subtype</att>=<val>decorated</val> covers:</p>
  <list rend="bulleted">
    <item>Foliate, floriated, interlaced, puzzle, pen-flourished, penwork, geometric, or epigraphic forms. Use for decorative initials that are not narrative and not inhabited by figures.</item>
    <item>Versals may also be classified as decorated where they incorporate ornamental features such as pen-flourishing or other forms of elaboration.</item>
    <item>Cadels are treated as decorated initials, specifically elaborate penwork initials formed of looping calligraphic flourishes, often extending into margins.</item>
  </list>
  <p>Extent may be described in prose: 1-line | 2-line | 3-line etc.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>plain initials</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[  <decoNote type="initial" subtype="plain">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Initials with minimal or no ornamental features, typically executed in a single colour or with minimal enhancement. The use of <att>subtype</att>=<val>plain</val> covers:</p>
  <list rend="bulleted">
    <item>Coloured initials, including rubricated and colour-stroked forms, as well as Lombards and versals.</item>
    <item>Versals and Lombards are typological forms that can sometimes be decorative.</item>
  </list>
  <p>Extent may be described in prose: 1-line | 2-line | 3-line etc.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>historiated borders</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[  <decoNote type="border" subtype="historiated">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Borders in which figures participate in identifiable actions or episodes, often related to the text. The use of <att>subtype</att>=<val>historiated</val> covers:</p>
  <list rend="bulleted">
    <item>Figural and narrative borders with recognisable scenes or subjects, including biblical, hagiographic, or allegorical themes.</item>
  </list>
  <p>Extent may be described in prose: 4-sided | 3-sided | 2-sided | 1-sided | intercolumnar.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>inhabited borders</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[  <decoNote type="border" subtype="inhabited">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Borders in which figures of humans, animals, or hybrids occupy or embellish the border without forming a narrative scene. The use of <att>subtype</att>=<val>inhabited</val> covers:</p>
  <list rend="bulleted">
    <item>Zoomorphic, anthropomorphic, or grotesque borders.</item>
  </list>
  <p>Extent may be described in prose: 4-sided | 3-sided | 2-sided | 1-sided | intercolumnar.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>decorated borders</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[  <decoNote type="border" subtype="decorated">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Borders with ornamental features and no narrative or integrated figural subjects. The use of <att>subtype</att>=<val>decorated</val> covers:</p>
  <list rend="bulleted">
    <item>Bar borders consisting of painted vertical or horizontal bands with sprouting foliage or tendrils</item>
    <item>Foliate or floral borders composed of stylised or naturalistic vines, leaves, flowers, and gold bezants, including spray borders and white vine-stem borders.</item>
    <item>Strewn, scatter, or trompe l'oeil borders with naturalistic flora, fruit, insects, or small animals arranged decoratively across the margins.</item>
    <item>Heraldic borders featuring coats of arms, badges, or dynastic symbols used ornamentally.</item>
    <item>Friezes treated as borders, consisting of horizontal ornamental bands running along one or more margins.</item>
  </list>
  <p>Extent may be described in prose: 4-sided | 3-sided | 2-sided | 1-sided | intercolumnar.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>plain borders</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[  <decoNote type="border" subtype="plain">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Borders with minimal or no ornamental features. The use of <att>subtype</att>=<val>plain</val> covers:</p>
  <list rend="bulleted">
    <item>Simple bar borders consisting of painted vertical or horizontal bands without additional ornament.</item>
    <item>Borders in panelled form functioning as simple frames with minimal or no decorative extension.</item>
    <item>Framing borders in printed books, including woodcut or engraved surrounds, where these remain structurally simple.</item>
  </list>
  <p>Extent may be described in prose: 4-sided | 3-sided | 2-sided | 1-sided | intercolumnar.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>rubrication</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[  <decoNote type="rubrication">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Rubrication is the use of coloured ink, most commonly red but also other colours, to highlight headings, instructions, or structural elements within a text. The use of <att>type</att>=<val>rubrication</val> covers:</p>
  <p>Rubrication in red ink as well as other colours such as blue, green, and purple.</p>
  <list rend="bulleted">
    <item>Chrysography (writing in gold).</item>
    <item>Headings or section titles.</item>
    <item>Running titles or marginal indicators.</item>
    <item>Paraph marks (¶ - pilcrows) indicating textual divisions.</item>
    <item>Verse or section markers.</item>
  </list>
  <p>The medium and colour of execution may be described in prose using <code>&lt;term type="medium"&gt;</code>. Common <att>type</att>=<val>medium</val> values include:</p>
  <p><val>inkRed</val>    standard rubrication in red ink</p>
  <p><val>inkBlue</val>   rubrication in blue ink</p>
  <p><val>inkGreen</val>  rubrication in green ink</p>
  <p><val>inkPurple</val> rubrication in purple ink</p>
  <p><val>inkGold</val>      rubrication in gold ink (chrysography)</p>
  <p><val>inkSilver</val> rubrication in silver ink</p>
  <p>Rubricated initials are not classified here but are encoded under plain initials, with rubrication noted in the description.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>line fillers</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<decoNote type="lineFiller">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Decorative devices used to fill unused space at the end of a line of text.</p>
  <p>The use of <att>type</att>=<val>lineFiller</val> covers:</p>
  <list rend="bulleted">
    <item>Penwork, geometric, floral, zoomorphic, anthropomorphic, or grotesque motifs.</item>
  </list></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>manicules</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<decoNote type="manicule">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Hand-shaped pointing symbols used to draw attention to a passage. Manicules (manicula) are primarily functional rather than decorative. They should be recorded in <gi>decoNote</gi> only when they form part of the manuscript’s original execution and are integrated into its visual or decorative programme, for example, Sammlung Alchymistischer Schriften: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-GERMAN-00003/1">German MS 3</ref>.</p>
  <p>Manicules added by later readers should normally be recorded in <gi>additions</gi>, unless they take the form of elaborate or ornamental drawings that function as decorative elements.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>missing</p></cell>
  <cell><p><att>subtype</att>=<val>missing</val></p>
    <p>A decoration that was originally executed but is no longer present, as indicated by physical traces such as cutting, erasure, abrasion, or other forms of loss.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>unfilled</p></cell>
  <cell><p><att>subtype</att>=<val>unfilled</val></p>
    <p>A decoration that was planned but never executed, as indicated by reserved space, guide letters, or layout preparation, without evidence of completion.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p>other</p></cell>
  <cell><p><att>subtype</att>=<val>other</val></p>
    <p>Any decorative feature not covered by the controlled categories above. This value should be used sparingly and only where no existing controlled subtype is appropriate.</p></cell>
</row>
</table>
<p><gi>decoNote</gi> may begin with one or more <gi>p</gi> summarising the features of the decoration within that category. These paragraphs may include information such as the total number of components, their scale, illumination or colour, and any attribution to an artist, workshop, or school.</p>
<p>Numbers should be written in words when they express narrative or descriptive quantities within prose. This distinction reflects the difference between discursive description and standardised descriptive notation: counts such as five miniatures, thirty-two leaves, or one hundred and seventy-nine initials are treated as part of the narrative and written in words, whereas fixed descriptive forms relating to line-height, such as 3-line, 5-line, and 7-line initials, are expressed using numerals for clarity and consistency.</p>
<p>Any name associated with the production or execution of the decoration should be encoded using <gi>name</gi>, containing either <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> as appropriate, and must include <att>role</att> indicating the nature of the relationship to the decoration. If the name is listed in VIAF, include both <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> on <gi>name</gi> to reference the relevant VIAF authority record. Where both display and standard forms are required, include two <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> within <gi>name</gi>, one with <att>type</att>=<val>display</val> and one with <att>type</att>=<val>standard</val>. Otherwise, a single <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> within <gi>name</gi> may be used.</p>
<p>When the value <val>#viaf</val> is used for <att>source</att>, it indicates that the identifier recorded in <att>key</att> is drawn from this authority file. The prefix <code>#</code> indicates a reference to an identifier defined elsewhere in <gi>msDesc</gi>. In this case, it refers to the <gi>taxonomy</gi> declared in the header with <att>xml:id</att>=<val>viaf</val>. This value can be selected from a controlled dropdown list when entering the attribute and does not need to be typed manually.</p>
<p><att>role</att> specifies the relationship of a person or organisation to the decoration. In most cases, this value will be <val>art</val>, used for artists. Other MARC relator codes, such as <val>ilu</val> for illuminators, <val>ill</val> for illustrators, or <val>egr</val> for engravers, may be used where appropriate, and additional values may also be applied as required.</p>
<p><gi>list</gi> may be used within <gi>decoNote</gi> to record several decorative features of the same category. This is appropriate when, for example, a series of miniatures or historiated initials appears throughout the item. Each feature should be encoded as an <gi>item</gi>, and each <gi>item</gi> should contain <gi>locus</gi> with <att>from</att> and <att>to</att> indicating the folio or page on which the feature appears.</p>
<p><gi>locus</gi> should contain only the foliation or pagination value, without additional descriptive text or punctuation. Terms such as Folio, fol., f., page, or p., and punctuation such as a trailing colon (:), should not be encoded either within <gi>locus</gi> or immediately adjacent to it within <gi>item</gi>.</p>
<p><gi>list</gi> should not be enclosed within an introductory <gi>p</gi>. Instead, it should appear as a separate element, maintaining a clear distinction between continuous prose and the list structure. Within <gi>item</gi>, one or more <gi>p</gi> may be used where the content contains meaningful internal divisions.</p>
<p>The use of <gi>head</gi> within <gi>list</gi> is optional. Where a visible category label or heading is required, it may instead be supplied in a preceding <gi>p</gi> using <code>&lt;hi rend="bold"&gt;</code>. <gi>head</gi> should be used only where it adds genuine structural value.</p>
<p><gi>head</gi> may be used within <gi>list</gi> to provide a heading for the list. Where a heading is required but no <gi>list</gi> is being used, a preceding <gi>p</gi> containing <code>&lt;hi rend="bold"&gt;</code> may be used instead.</p>
<p>Where <gi>decoNote</gi> contains multiple comparable entries, <gi>list</gi> is normally preferred. Where only a single entry is required, or where the description is better expressed in continuous prose, one or more <gi>p</gi> may be used instead.</p>
<table rend="rules">
  <row>
    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Illuminator(s):</hi> Simone Camaldolese, Don, active 1378-1405</p>
      <p>—</p>
      <p><hi rend="bold">• Decoration:</hi></p>
      <p>The illuminated decoration on 3r, 105r, and 149r is attributed to Don Simone Camaldolese (active 1378-1405), also known as Simone da Siena. A monk of the Camaldolite Order at the Monastery of Santa Maria degli Angeli in Florence, Don Simone was a prominent miniaturist and illuminator of the late fourteenth century, primarily active in Florence and Tuscany. His distinctive style has led art historian Ada Labriola (2012) to attribute these specific folios to him, noting strong stylistic connections with other manuscripts he is known to have illuminated, including the following works:</p>
      <p>Divina commedia (Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library: Beinecke MS 458)
        Divina commedia (Biblioteca Apostolica Vaticana: Vat.lat. 4776)
        Canzoniere (Biblioteca Nazionale Centrale di Firenze: MS Pal. 184)
        Genealogia deorum gentilium (The Hanna Holborn Gray Special Collections Research Center: Codex MS 100)</p>
      <p>At the beginning of each major section, three historiated initials depicting the poets are accompanied by full border decorations portraying their <hi rend="italic">inamoratas</hi>. The arms of the Florentine Strozzi family are emblazoned in the lower borders of the first two.</p>
      <p>Historiated initials</p>
      <p><hi rend="italic">In vita di madonna Laura</hi></p>
      <p>3r 9-line <hi rend="bold">U</hi> | <hi rend="bold">V</hi>[oi chascoltate] | Petrarch, hooded and in blue, green, and red robes, is sitting at a desk, holding a quill or stylus in his right hand and writing in an open book. He is pierced by an arrow, symbolically shot by Cupid or Eros.</p>
      <p><hi rend="italic">In morte di madonna Laura</hi></p>
      <p>105r 6-line <hi rend="bold">I</hi>[vo pensando] | Petrarch, hooded and in blue, green, and red robes, is standing with his hands gently clasped.</p>
      <p><hi rend="italic">In lode di Beatrice</hi></p>
      <p>149r 5-line <hi rend="bold">C</hi>[osi nel mio] | Dante, hooded and in pink, blue, and red robes, is sitting at a desk, holding a quill or stylus in his right hand and writing in an open book.</p>
      <p>Historiated borders</p>
      <p><hi rend="italic">In vita di madonna Laura</hi></p>
      <p>3r 4-sided border filled with vibrant floral and foliate motifs in blue, red, green, and gold. In the upper border, the winged god of Love, Cupid or Eros, is holding a bow and aiming an arrow at Petrarch. In the outer border, Laura, crowned with laurel and in a flowing pink or violet gown, is standing, pierced by an arrow shot by Cupid or Eros. In the lower border, a heraldic shield contains the coat of arms of the House of Strozzi.</p>
      <p><hi rend="italic">In morte di madonna Laura</hi></p>
      <p>105r 4-sided border filled with vibrant floral and foliate motifs in blue, red, green, and gold. In the outer border, Laura, crowned with laurel and in a flowing blue gown, is lying on her deathbed with her head resting on a pillow and her arms crossed. In the upper border, the skeletal figure of Death, with bat-like wings and in a dark grey garment, is holding a raised scythe in his right hand and a spear in his left. In the lower border, a radiant golden sun contains the coat of arms of the House of Strozzi.</p>
      <p><hi rend="italic">In lode di Beatrice</hi></p>
      <p>149r 4-sided border filled with vibrant floral and foliate motifs in blue, red, green, and gold. In the outer border, Beatrice, in a flowing blue gown, is standing with her right arm bent across her chest, facing left towards Dante. In the upper border, a blue-winged figure is hovering and holding a flaming torch.</p>
      <p>Pen-flourished initials</p>
      <p>Each poem opens with a 2- to 3-line pen-flourished initial, alternating red and blue. Examples on 28r, 123r, and 160r.</p>
      <p>Plain initials</p>
      <p>Each verse begins with a 1-line plain initial highlighted with strokes of pale-yellow wash.</p>
      <p>Rubrication</p>
      <p>Each stanza begins with a paraph mark (pilcrow), alternating red and blue.
        Headings are rubricated in red ink throughout.</p>
      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><decoDesc>
<summary>
<p>The illuminated decoration on <locus from="3r" to="3r">3r</locus>, <locus from="105r" to="105r">105r</locus>, and <locus from="149r" to="149r">149r</locus> is attributed to <name source="#viaf" key="313279739" role="ilu"><persName type="display">Don Simone Camaldolese (active 1378-1405), also known as Simone da Siena</persName><persName type="standard">Simone Camaldolese, Don, active 1378-1405</persName></name>. A monk of the Camaldolite Order at the Monastery of Santa Maria degli Angeli in Florence, Don Simone was a prominent miniaturist and illuminator of the late fourteenth century, primarily active in Florence and Tuscany. His distinctive style has led art historian Ada Labriola (2012) to attribute these specific folios to him, noting strong stylistic connections with other manuscripts he is known to have illuminated, including the following works:</p>
<list>
<item>Divina commedia (<ref target="https://collections.library.yale.edu/catalog/2052913">Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library: Beinecke MS 458</ref>)</item>
<item>Divina commedia (<ref target="https://spotlight.vatlib.it/dante/catalog/Vat_lat_4776">Biblioteca Apostolica Vaticana: Vat.lat. 4776 </ref>)</item>
<item>Canzoniere (Biblioteca Nazionale Centrale di Firenze: MS Pal. 184)</item>
<item>Genealogia deorum gentilium (<ref target="https://www.lib.uchicago.edu/e/scrc/findingaids/view.php?eadid=ICU.SPCL.MS100#idp150024776">The Hanna Holborn Gray Special Collections 458 Research Center: Codex MS 100</ref>)</item>
</list>
<p>At the beginning of each major section, three historiated initials depicting the poets are accompanied by full border decorations portraying their <hi rend="italic">inamoratas</hi>. The arms of the Florentine Strozzi family are emblazoned in the lower borders of the first two. </p>
</summary>
<decoNote type="initial" subtype="historiated">
<list>
<head>Historiated initials</head>
<item>
<p><hi rend="italic">In vita di madonna Laura</hi></p>
<p><locus from="3r" to="3r">3r</locus> 9-line <hi rend="bold">U | V</hi>[oi chascoltate] | Petrarch, hooded and in blue, green, and red robes, is sitting at a desk, holding a quill or stylus in his right hand and writing in an open book. He is pierced by an arrow, symbolically shot by Cupid or Eros.</p></item>
<item>
<p><hi rend="italic">In morte di madonna Laura</hi></p>
<p><locus from="105r" to="105r">105r</locus> 6-line <hi rend="bold">I</hi>[vo pensando] | Petrarch, hooded and in blue, green, and red robes, is standing with his hands gently clasped. </p></item>
<item>
<p><hi rend="italic">In lode di Beatrice</hi></p>
<p><locus from="149r" to="149r">149r</locus> 5-line <hi rend="bold">C</hi>[osi nel mio] | Dante, hooded and in pink, blue, and red robes, is sitting at a desk, holding a quill or stylus in his right hand and writing in an open book.</p></item>
</list>
</decoNote>
<decoNote type="border" subtype="historiated">
<list>
<head>Historiated borders</head>
<item>
<p><hi rend="italic">In vita di madonna Laura</hi></p>
<p><locus from="3r" to="3r">3r</locus> 4-sided border filled with vibrant floral and foliate motifs in blue, red, green, and gold. In the upper border, the winged god of Love, Cupid or Eros, is holding a bow and aiming an arrow at Petrarch. In the outer border, Laura, crowned with laurel and in a flowing pink or violet gown, is standing, pierced by an arrow shot by Cupid or Eros. In the lower border, a heraldic shield contains the coat of arms of the House of Strozzi.</p></item>
<item>
<p><hi rend="italic">In morte di madonna Laura</hi></p>
<p><locus from="105r" to="105r">105r</locus> 4-sided border filled with vibrant floral and foliate motifs in blue, red, green, and gold. In the outer border, Laura, crowned with laurel and in a flowing blue gown, is lying on her deathbed with her head resting on a pillow and her arms crossed. In the upper border, the skeletal figure of Death, with bat-like wings and in a dark grey garment, is holding a raised scythe in his right hand and a spear in his left. In the lower border, a radiant golden sun contains the coat of arms of the House of Strozzi.</p></item>
<item>
<p><hi rend="italic">In lode di Beatrice</hi></p>
<p><locus from="149r" to="149r">149r</locus> 4-sided border filled with vibrant floral and foliate motifs in blue, red, green, and gold. In the outer border, Beatrice, in a flowing blue gown, is standing with her right arm bent across her chest, facing left towards Dante. In the upper border, a blue-winged figure is hovering and holding a flaming torch.</p></item>
</list>
</decoNote>
<decoNote type="initial" subtype="decorated">
<p><hi rend="bold">Pen-flourished initials</hi></p>
<p>Each poem opens with a 2- to 3-line pen-flourished initial, alternating red and blue. Examples on <locus from="28r" to="28r">28r</locus>, <locus from="123r" to="123r">123r</locus>, and <locus from="160r" to="160r">160r</locus>.</p>
</decoNote>
<decoNote type="initial" subtype="plain">
<p><hi rend="bold">Plain initials</hi></p>
<p>Each verse begins with a 1-line plain initial highlighted with strokes of pale-yellow wash.</p>
</decoNote>
<decoNote type="rubrication">
<p><hi rend="bold">Rubrication</hi></p>
<p>Each stanza begins with a paraph mark (pilcrow), alternating red and blue.</p>
<p>Headings are rubricated in red ink throughout.</p>
</decoNote>
</decoDesc></egXML></p>
      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Il Canzoniere di Petrarca e Le Rime di Dant</hi>e: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-ITALIAN-00001/1">Italian MS 1</ref></p></cell>
  </row>
</table>
<p>The following partial example comes from a retroconversion of James’s catalogue, with only minimal subsequent editorial refinement. The wording within &lt;p&gt; was only lightly revised at a later stage and otherwise reflects the language and terminology of that period, which is not recommended. The example also demonstrates a straightforward approach without the use of headings or labels.</p>
<table rend="rules">
  <row>
    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Decoration:</hi></p>
      <p>The principal decoration consists of full-page illustrations and borders of fluid gold, incorporating birds, notably peacocks, together with naturalistic flowers and fruit. The borders, as in the first instance, are divided into panels by gold frames, with each panel set against a ground of blue or purple-red. The style is Flemish. The illustrations are full-page except where otherwise specified.</p>
      <p>13v Salue sanctafacies. Blue ground. Bust of Christ in purple robe holding a crystal orb with gold cross, and fleury. His head is rayed with flourished gold rays. The opposite page has full border, as in nearly all cases.</p>
      <p>16v Hours of the Cross. The Crucifixion. The Virgin, John, and woman on left: two Jews on right. Peacocks in the border.</p>
      <p>23v Hours of the Holy Ghost. Pentecost. The Virgin kneels at a desk in centre facing right. Apostles kneel on either side looking up at the dove.</p>
      <p>30v Mass of the Virgin. Ground is mainly pink. The Virgin and Child, rayed, rather more than half-length, surrounded by clouds.</p>
      <p>43v Matins of the Virgin. Annunciation. The Virgin kneels inside a building. Gabriel (outside) enters on left. The Dove on a ray.</p>
      <p>63v Lauds. The Visitation, on a grass plot in front of a brick house with stone dressings.</p>
      <p>77v Prime. The Virgin (left) and Joseph adore the Child. Ox and ass behind. Rays descend vertically.</p>
      <p>83v Tierce. Two shepherds in a field with a gate. Angel in pink, and star, in the sky.</p>
      <p>—</p>
      <p>245r Missus est. In text. Left, against a pink ground, the Virgin and Child. Right, against a blue ground, with gold leaves, a beardless man in dark habit, in prayer.</p>
      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><decoDesc>
<decoNote type="illustration">
<p>The principal decoration consists of full-page illustrations and borders of fluid gold, incorporating birds, notably peacocks, together with naturalistic flowers and fruit. The borders, as in the first instance, are divided into panels by gold frames, with each panel set against a ground of blue or purple-red. The style is Flemish. The illustrations are full-page except where otherwise specified.</p>
<list>
<item><locus from="13v" to="13v">13v</locus> Salue sanctafacies. Blue ground. Bust of Christ in purple robe holding a crystal orb with gold cross, and fleury. His head is rayed with flourished gold rays. The opposite page has full border, as in nearly all cases.</item>
<item><locus from="16v" to="16v">16v</locus> Hours of the Cross. The Crucifixion. The Virgin, John, and woman on left: two Jews on right. Peacocks in the border.</item>
<item><locus from="23v" to="23v">23v</locus> Hours of the Holy Ghost. Pentecost. The Virgin kneels at a desk in centre facing right. Apostles kneel on either side looking up at the dove.  </item>
<item><locus from="30v" to="30v">30v</locus> Mass of the Virgin. Ground mainly pink. The Virgin and Child, rayed, rather more than half-length, surrounded by clouds.</item>
<item><locus from="43v" to="43v">43v</locus> Matins of the Virgin. Annunciation. The Virgin kneels inside a building. Gabriel (outside) enters on left. The Dove on a ray.</item>
<item><locus from="63v" to="63v">63v</locus> Lauds. The Visitation, on a grass plot in front of a brick house with stone dressings.</item>
<item><locus from="77v" to="77v">77v</locus> Prime. The Virgin (left) and Joseph adore the Child. Ox and ass behind. Rays descend vertically.</item>
<item><locus from="83v" to="83v">83v</locus> Tierce. Two shepherds in a field with a gate. Angel in pink, and star, in the sky.</item>
<!-- additional metadata -->
<item><locus from="245r" to="245r">245r</locus> Missus est. In text. Left, against a pink ground, the Virgin and Child. Right, against a blue ground, with gold leaves, a beardless man in dark habit, in prayer.</item>
</list>
</decoNote>
</decoDesc></egXML></p>
      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Horae (Mary, Queen of Scots)</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00021/1">Latin MS 21</ref></p></cell>
  </row>
</table>
<p>An additional level of encoding may be applied where iconographic detail is relevant. In such cases, the iconographic subjects of illustrations may be classified and encoded using <code>&lt;term type="iconography"&gt;</code>. <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> may be used to reference a controlled vocabulary or thesaurus, such as Iconclass, which provides a universal classification system for the subject matter of works of art.</p>
<table rend="rules">
  <row>
    <cell><p><val>iconclass</val></p></cell>
    <cell><p>Iconclass</p></cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell cols="2"><p><ref target="https://iconclass.org">Iconclass</ref> is a specialised classification system used to describe and organise the subject matter of images in art and visual culture. Developed by the Dutch art historian Henri van de Waal, it is one of the largest and most widely used systems for iconography, containing over 28,000 concepts arranged in a hierarchical structure. Each subject is represented by an alphanumeric code, allowing images to be indexed and retrieved by their content. The system is divided into ten main categories, such as Religion, Nature, History, and the Bible, and is widely used by museums, libraries, and researchers to standardise the description and analysis of visual materials</p>
      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><classDecl>
<taxonomy xml:id="iconclass">
<bibl><ref target="https://iconclass.org">Iconclass</ref></bibl>
</taxonomy>
</classDecl></egXML></p></cell>
    </row>
  </table>
  <p>For example, folio 63v of Latin MS 21 contains an illustration of the Visitation, which may be encoded as follows.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Decoration:</hi></p>
        <p>—</p>
        <p>63v Lauds. The <hi rend="italic">Visitation</hi>, on a grass plot in front of a brick house with stone dressings.</p>
        <p>—</p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><decoDesc>
<decoNote type="illustration">
<!-- additional metadata -->
<list>
<!-- additional metadata -->
<item><locus from="63v" to="63v">63v</locus> Lauds. The <term type="iconography" source="#iconclass" key="73A6">Visitation</term>, on a grass plot in front of a brick house with stone dressings.</item>
<!-- additional metadata -->
</list>
</decoNote>
</decoDesc></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Horae (Mary, Queen of Scots)</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00021/1">Latin MS 21</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
  </table>
  <p>When the value <val>#iconclass</val> is used for <att>source</att>, it indicates that the identifier recorded in <att>key</att> is drawn from this authority. The prefix <code>#</code> signals a reference to an identifier defined elsewhere in the same TEI file. In this case, it points to <gi>taxonomy</gi> declared in the header with <att>xml:id</att>=<val>iconclass</val>. This value can be selected from a controlled dropdown list when entering the attribute and does not need to be typed manually.</p>
  <div xml:id="general-remarks-encoding-principles-and-convention">
    <head>General remarks: encoding principles and conventions</head>
    <p>Miniature is a specialist art-historical term referring to a particular type of painted image and should <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> be used as a controlled classification value. Not all illustrations are miniatures, and the term is only applicable in specific descriptive contexts. Where a decorative feature is identified as a miniature, this should be described in the prose of <gi>decoNote</gi>, while <att>type</att>=<val>illustration</val> should continue to be used for classification.</p>
    <p><att>subtype</att> for initials and borders is restricted to four controlled values: <val>historiated</val>, <val>decorated</val>, <val>inhabited</val>, and <val>plain</val>. These provide a stable top‑level typology, ensuring that each initial is assigned to a single conceptual category. Further variation, such as puzzle, zoomorphic, anthropomorphic, pen-flourished, or Lombard forms, should be described in the prose of <gi>decoNote</gi> and should not be encoded as additional <att>subtype</att> values.</p>
    <p>Motifs and detailed decorative features may also be encoded in <gi>decoNote</gi> using <att>type</att>, <att>subtype</att>, and <att>style</att>, and may additionally be encoded with <code>&lt;term type="motif"&gt;</code> where appropriate. More generally, <gi>term</gi> may be used to supply controlled terminology for decorative forms, motifs, materials, or techniques when greater specificity is required.</p>
    <p>Terms referring to techniques, such as drawing, sketch, illumination, woodcut, and similar production methods, should <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> be encoded as attribute values. These describe how a decoration was executed, not what category it belongs to. Such information may be described in prose and encoded using <code>&lt;note type="technique"&gt;</code> or <code>&lt;term type="technique"&gt;</code> where appropriate.</p>
    <p>Micrography is a scribal technique and should not be treated as a decorative category.</p>
    <p>Values such as <val>none</val>, <val>unknown</val>, and similar placeholders must <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> be used in the controlled vocabulary. The values <val>mixed</val> and <val>unspecified</val> must <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> be used in <gi>decoNote</gi>. These do not represent valid decorative categories and introduce ambiguity.</p>
    <p><att>rend</att> and <att>rendition</att> must <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> be used within <gi>decoDesc</gi> or elsewhere in <gi>teiHeader</gi>. Decorative and visual features described in the header should instead be encoded through the appropriate descriptive elements and attributes. <att>rend</att> and <att>rendition</att> should be used only for transcription within <gi>text</gi>, <gi>body</gi>, and related elements.</p>
    <p><gi>decoNote</gi> within <gi>decoDesc</gi> is reserved for describing decorative features. Where decoration is specific to binding, seals, provenance, or other aspects of the item, it should be encoded using the appropriate TEI elements. For example, decoration associated with bindings should be encoded within <gi>bindingDesc</gi>, where <gi>decoNote</gi> may optionally be used within <gi>binding</gi>. Decoration associated with seals should be encoded within <gi>sealDesc</gi>, where <gi>decoNote</gi> may optionally be used within <gi>seal</gi>. Paratextual features such as the printer's device should be encoded within <gi>origin</gi> using <code>&lt;note type="printersDevice"&gt;</code>.</p>
    <p><hi rend="bold">For descriptive terminology, the following resources may be consulted:</hi></p>
    <p>Brown, Michelle P, et al. <ref target="https://muse.jhu.edu/book/77994">Understanding Illuminated Manuscripts</ref> : A Guide to Technical Terms, Revised Edition. Getty Trust Publications, 2018.</p>
    <p>Beal, Peter. <ref target="https://ebookcentral-proquest-com.manchester.idm.oclc.org/lib/manchester/detail.action?docID=415037">A Dictionary of English Manuscript Terminology, 1450 to 2000</ref>. Oxford University Press, 2008.</p>
    <p>Hall, James. Dictionary of Subjects and Symbols in Art. Rev. ed., John Murray, 1997.</p>
    <p>Hill Museum &amp; Manuscript Library | HMML School <ref target="https://hmmlschool.org/lexicon/">Lexicon</ref>. Terms used in manuscript studies.</p>
    <p>Getty Research Institute. <ref target="https://www.getty.edu/research/tools/vocabularies/aat/index.html">Getty Art &amp; Architecture Thesaurus®</ref> (AAT)</p>
  </div>
</div>
<div xml:id="additions">
  <head><code>&lt;additions&gt;</code> | additions</head>
  <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release//doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-additions.html"><gi>additions</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(additions) contains a description of any significant additions found within a manuscript or other object, such as marginalia or other annotations.</hi></p>
  <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Additions</hi></p>
  <p><gi>additions</gi> is used to record any additions introduced into or around the main text, whether during production or at later points in its history. These may be scribal, such as corrections by the original scribe or a corrector, or non-scribal, such as later annotations, informal markings, or censorship.</p>
  <p>The following terms may be used to describe common forms of addition, correction, or textual intervention:</p>
  <p><hi rend="bold">marginal insertion</hi> text added in the margin</p>
  <p><hi rend="bold">interlinear insertion</hi> text added between existing lines</p>
  <p><hi rend="bold">erasure</hi> text scraped, rubbed away, washed, or otherwise removed</p>
  <p><hi rend="bold">cancellation or strikethrough</hi> text marked for deletion by being crossed out</p>
  <p>expunctuation dots placed beneath letters or words to mark deletion</p>
  <p><hi rend="bold">overwriting</hi> new writing added over existing writing</p>
  <p><hi rend="bold">transformation</hi> letters or words altered into another form</p>
  <p><hi rend="bold">superimposition</hi> new writing placed over earlier writing</p>
  <p>Other additions and marks may include marginalia, annotations, scribblings, doodles, manicules, drawings, pen-trials, underlining, ink stamps, censorial marks, and other evidence of use. Censorial interventions may include text deliberately obscured with ink or otherwise made difficult to read. Guiding marks, such as caret signs or signes-de-renvoi, may also be recorded where they indicate the placement of supplementary text.</p>
  <p>These categories may overlap. For example, marginal additions, erasures, underlining, or annotations may be contemporary with the main text or added later by a reader, owner, or annotator. Where possible, describe the nature of the intervention and its relationship to the main text, including date, hand, or function when this can be determined.</p>
  <p>Identifiable ownership inscriptions, stamps, or other provenance marks should be recorded in <gi>provenance</gi> within <gi>history</gi>, with only unattributable marks remaining in <gi>additions</gi>. Non-contemporaneous additional material that accompanies the item but is not part of its physical structure should be described in <gi>accMat</gi>, <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> in <gi>additions</gi>.</p>
  <p>Any additions made to the item itself should be recorded in <gi>additions</gi>, with each type described in a separate <gi>p</gi> and <gi>locus</gi> where relevant.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Additions:</hi></p>
        <p>Omission of text by means of strikethrough and superscription on 75v, 81v.</p>
        <p>Erasure of text and overwriting on 24r, 26r, 28r, 34r, 75r, and 84v.</p>
        <p>Caret marks (˄) and interlineations or marginal additions on 44r, 47r, 61v, and 84r.</p>
        <p>Erasures indicating post-Reformation political and religious censorship. The text has been scraped or rubbed off or crossed (blacked) out with ink on 4r-7v and 168v.</p>
        <p>Marginal annotation on 85r, mainly extracting keywords, possibly in a fifteenth-century English hand.</p>
        <p>The marginal numbering of the Psalms appears to correspond consistently with the numbering system found in the Hebrew Masoretic text (MT). It remains challenging to ascertain whether these numbers were added during the original production process of the manuscript or introduced by subsequent owners.</p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><additions>
<p>Omission of text by means of strikethrough and superscription on <locus from="75v" to="75v">75v</locus> and <locus from="81v" to="81v">81v</locus>.</p>
<p>Erasure of text and overwriting on <locus from="24r" to="24r">24r</locus>, <locus from="26r" to="26r">26r</locus>, <locus from="28r" to="28r">28r</locus>, <locus from="34r" to="34r">34r</locus>, <locus from="75r" to="75r">75r</locus>, and <locus from="84v" to="84v">84v</locus>.</p>
<p>Caret marks (˄) and interlineations or marginal additions on <locus from="44r" to="44r">44r</locus>, <locus from="47r" to="47r">47r</locus>, <locus from="61v" to="61v">61v</locus>, and <locus from="84r" to="84r">84r</locus>.</p>
<p>Erasures indicating post-Reformation political and religious censorship. The text has been scraped or rubbed off or crossed (blacked) out with ink on <locus from="4r" to="7v">4r-7v</locus> and <locus from="168v" to="168v">168v</locus>.</p>
<p>Marginal annotation on <locus from="85r" to="85r">85r</locus>, mainly extracting keywords, possibly in a fifteenth-century English hand.</p>
<p>The marginal numbering of the Psalms appears to correspond consistently with the numbering system found in the Hebrew Masoretic text (MT). It remains challenging to ascertain whether these numbers were added during the original production process of the manuscript or introduced by subsequent owners.</p>
</additions></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Psalter of Joan of Navarre</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00022/1">Latin MS 22</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Additions:</hi></p>
        <p>A notable instance of 'indulgence inflation' can be observed on 95r, where a small paper slip has been pasted over one word in the prayer (line 4) to increase the indulgence from seven to ten years: ...<hi rend="italic">omnibus hic presentibus</hi> <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">decem</hi></hi> <hi rend="italic">annos ...</hi>.</p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><additions>
<p>A notable instance of 'indulgence inflation' can be observed on <locus from="95r" to="95r">95r</locus>, where a small paper slip has been pasted over one word in the prayer (line 4) to increase the indulgence from seven to ten years: <hi rend="italic">...omnibus hic presentibus <hi rend="italic">decem</hi> annos ...</hi></p>
</additions></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right">Colonna Missal II: <ref target="https://https:/www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00032-A/1">Latin MS 32a</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
  </table>
  <p>In printed materials, <gi>additions</gi> is used to record manuscript notes, inscriptions, markings, and other handwritten additions found on the item that cannot be confidently attributed to <gi>provenance</gi>.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Additions:</hi></p>
        <p>Manuscript pencil note on Flyleaf 1v: <hi rend="italic">Character of G. Huyon A | 1520?.</hi></p>
        <p>Various manuscript pencil prices[?] on Flyleaf 1v: <hi rend="italic">£2.2.0 | 0 | 3/[?] | 1/4/2[?].</hi></p>
        <p>Manuscript pencil note on a1r: <hi rend="italic">[?]De[?]dras[?].</hi></p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><additions>
<p>Manuscript pencil note on <locus from="Flyleaf_1v" to="Flyleaf_1v">Flyleaf 1v</locus>: <hi rend="italic">Character of G. Huyon A | 1520?</hi>.</p>
<p>Various manuscript pencil prices[?] on <locus from="Flyleaf_1v" to="Flyleaf_1v">Flyleaf 1v</locus>: <hi rend="italic">£2.2.0 | 0 | 3/[?] | 1/4/2[?]</hi>.</p>
<p>Manuscript inscription, mostly illegible, on the lower margin of <locus from="a1r" to="a1r">a1r</locus>: <hi rend="italic">[?]De[?]dras[?]</hi>.</p>
</additions></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Le terze rime di Dante</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-ALDI-18873/1">18873</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
  </table>
</div>
<div xml:id="bindingDesc">
  <head><code>&lt;bindingDesc&gt;</code> | binding description</head>
  <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release//doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-bindingDesc.html"><gi>bindingDesc</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(binding description) describes the present and former bindings of a manuscript or other object, either as a series of paragraphs or as a series of distinct</hi> <gi>binding</gi> <hi rend="italic">elements, one for each binding of the manuscript.</hi></p>
  <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Binding</hi></p>
  <p><gi>bindingDesc</gi> contains information about the binding of a manuscript, printed book, or other codex-form item. This may include a description of a single binding or a sequence of bindings the item has received over time. It typically contains at least one <gi>binding</gi> describing a specific binding at a given point in time, and may record details such as the type of covering, the boards, structural features, decoration, condition, and physical dimensions.</p>
</div>
<div xml:id="binding">
  <head><code>&lt;binding&gt;</code> | binding</head>
  <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release//doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-binding.html"><gi>binding</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(binding) contains a description of one binding, i.e. type of covering, boards, etc. applied to a manuscript or other object.</hi></p>
  <p><gi>binding</gi> within <gi>bindingDesc</gi> should describe a single physical binding, normally using one or more <gi>p</gi>. TEI does not prescribe an internal sequence for this prose, so projects should adopt a consistent order to keep binding descriptions readable and comparable across files. The following order is recommended, moving from identification through materials, structure, and decoration, and concluding with condition (including any repairs or alterations) and the physical dimensions of the binding.</p>
  <p><gi>binding</gi> should include <att>contemporary</att> and at least one dating attribute, such as <att>when</att>, <att>notBefore</att>, <att>notAfter</att>, or <att>from</att>, <att>to</att>, to indicate the date the binding was created.</p>
  <p rend="attHead"><code>@contemporary</code></p>
  <p><att>contemporary</att> (contemporary) specifies whether or not the binding is contemporary with its contents.</p>
  <p>The following values should be used:</p>
  <p><val>true</val> the binding is contemporary with its contents.</p>
  <p><val>false</val> the binding is not contemporary with its contents.</p>
  <p><val>unknown</val> it is not known whether the binding is contemporary with its contents.</p>
  <p> When using <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att>, ensure that the values reflect the correct start and end boundaries of the period being described, following the same dating conventions used for <gi>origDate</gi>. For example, a nineteenth-century binding that is not contemporary with its contents should be encoded as <code>&lt;binding @contemporary= "false" notBefore="1801" and notAfter="1900"&gt;</code>, <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> as <hi rend="italic">1800–1899</hi> or <hi rend="italic">1800–1900</hi>.</p>
  <p>Where the binder is known, their name should be encoded using <code>&lt;name role="bnd"&gt;</code>, containing either <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> as appropriate. If the name is listed in VIAF, include both <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> on <gi>name</gi> to reference the appropriate VIAF authority record. Where both display and standard forms are required, include two <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> within <gi>name</gi>, one with <att>type</att>=<val>display</val> and one with <att>type</att>=<val>standard</val>. Otherwise, a single <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> within <gi>name</gi> may be used.</p>
  <p>The physical dimensions of the binding should be encoded within <code>&lt;dimensions type="binding" unit="mm"&gt;</code> using <gi>height</gi>, <gi>width</gi> and optionally <gi>depth</gi>, each with <att>quantity</att>.</p>
  <p>The following examples illustrate typical patterns of binding descriptions.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Binding:</hi></p>
        <p>Nineteenth-century binding in full black morocco over boards.</p>
        <p>Binding height: 270 mm, width: 170 mm<hi rend="italic">.</hi></p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<bindingDesc>
<binding contemporary="false" notBefore="1801" notAfter="1900">
<p>Nineteenth-century binding in full black morocco over boards.</p>
<p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
<height quantity="270">270</height>
<width quantity="170">170</width></p>
</binding>
</bindingDesc>]]></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Armorial</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00028/1">Latin MS 28</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Binding:</hi></p>
        <p>Mid-sixteenth-century binding in full red morocco over boards, crafted by Maestro Luigi de Gava (or de Gradi), a binder to several popes and other important patrons. Active from 1542 to at least 1565, he produced bindings for the Sistine Chapel and the Capella Segreta (Hobson 1975).</p>
        <p>The front and back covers are blind-tooled in a rectilinear scheme, with a central rectangular panel formed by concentric rectangular frames. Double blind fillets frame the perimeter of the covers, with triple blind fillets dividing the surface into subsidiary panels. The principal panel consists of a repeated interlaced strapwork motif arranged in small rectangular compartments. The motif is formed by crossed C-shaped straps, each with a diaper-patterned infill of small square tooling.</p>
        <p>The decoration expands outwards through successive frames of gilt fillets and foliate rolls. Just inside the outermost border is a slim band carrying a small gilt Colonna device on each of the left and right sides. The outermost frame is heavier, with a dense foliate roll and gilt cornerpieces containing double-headed eagles.</p>
        <p>The spine is divided into five compartments by four raised bands, each outlined with a gilt fillet. The compartments are blind-tooled with a repeating foliate ground and centred with gold-tooled arabesque motifs.</p>
        <p>All edges are gilt.</p>
        <p>Binding height: 270 mm, width: 170 mm, depth: 49 mm<hi rend="italic">.</hi></p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<bindingDesc>
<binding contemporary="true" notBefore="1542" notAfter="1565">
<p>Mid-sixteenth-century binding in full red morocco over boards, crafted by <name role="bnd"><persName>Maestro Luigi de Gava (or de Gradi)</persName>, a binder to several popes and other important patrons. Active from 1542 to at least 1565, he produced bindings for the Sistine Chapel and the Capella Segreta (Hobson 1975).</p>
<p>The <locus from="Front_cover" to="Front_cover">front</locus> and <locus from="Back_cover" to="Back_cover">back</locus> covers are gold-tooled symmetrically with nested rectangular frames incorporating gilt arabesque cornerpieces and side panels. At the centre is the coat of arms of the House of Colonna: <heraldry> Gules, a column Argent, the base and capital Or, crowned antiquely of the last</heraldry>. The arms are set within a gilt oval frame and a lobed cartouche of scrolling foliage, with small flourishes above and below.</p>
<p>The decoration expands outwards through successive frames of gilt fillets and foliate rolls. Just inside the outermost border is a slim band carrying a small gilt Colonna device on each of the left and right sides. The outermost frame is heavier, with a dense foliate roll and gilt cornerpieces containing double-headed eagles.</p>
<p>The <locus from="Spine" to="Spine">spine</locus> is divided into five compartments by four raised bands, each outlined with a gilt fillet. The compartments are blind-tooled with a
repeating foliate ground and centred with gold-tooled arabesque motifs.</p>
<p>All edges are gilt.</p>
<p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
<height quantity="387">387</height>
<width quantity="273">273</width></p>
<depth quantity="49">49</depth></p>
</binding>
</bindingDesc>]]></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Colonna Missal II</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00032-A/1">Latin MS 32a</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Binding:</hi></p>
        <p>Fifteenth-century binding in full brown leather over wooden boards.</p>
        <p>The front and back covers are blind-tooled in a rectilinear scheme, with a central rectangular panel formed by concentric rectangular frames. Double blind fillets frame the perimeter of the covers, with triple blind fillets dividing the surface into subsidiary panels. The principal panel consists of a repeated interlaced strapwork motif arranged in small rectangular compartments. The motif is formed by crossed C-shaped straps, each with a diaper-patterned infill of small square tooling.</p>
        <p>The spine is divided into ten compartments by nine raised bands. The third, fourth, and fifth compartments are gilt-lettered: <hi rend="italic">Psalterium | Anglo-Norman | Saec. XIII.</hi></p>
        <p>Binding height: 273 mm, width: 190 mm<hi rend="italic">.</hi></p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<bindingDesc>
<binding contemporary="false" notBefore="1860" notAfter="1975">
<p>Fifteenth-century binding in full brown leather over wooden boards.</p>
<p>The <locus from="Front_cover" to="Front_cover">front</locus> and <locus from="Back_cover" to="Back_cover">back</locus> covers are blind-tooled in a rectilinear scheme, with a central rectangular panel formed by concentric rectangular frames. Double blind fillets frame the perimeter of the covers, with triple blind fillets dividing the surface into subsidiary panels. The principal panel consists of a repeated interlaced strapwork motif arranged in small rectangular compartments. The motif is formed by crossed C-shaped straps, each with a diaper-patterned infill of small square tooling.</p>
<p>The <locus from="Spine" to="Spine">spine</locus> is divided into ten compartments by nine raised bands. The third, fourth, and fifth compartments are gilt-lettered: <hi rend="italic">Psalterium | Anglo-Norman | Saec. XIII.</hi></p>
<p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
<height quantity="273">273</height>
<width quantity="190">190</width></p>
</binding>
</bindingDesc>]]></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Psalter of Joan of Navarre</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00022/1">Latin MS 22</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Binding:</hi></p>
        <p>Late nineteenth- or twentieth-century binding in full dark green coated cloth over boards.</p>
        <p>The spine is smooth, gold-blocked, with two horizontal foliate scroll motifs forming a single panel, and lettered: <hi rend="italic">Erlebtes.| Band I. | 1817-1824.</hi></p>
        <p>Binding height: 370 mm, width: 240 mm<hi rend="italic">.</hi></p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<bindingDesc>
<binding contemporary="false" notBefore="1860" notAfter="1975">
<p>Late nineteenth- or twentieth-century binding in full dark green coated cloth over boards</p>
<p>The <locus from="Spine" to="Spine">spine</locus> is smooth, gold-blocked, with two horizontal foliate scroll motifs forming a single panel, and lettered: <hi rend="italic">Erlebtes.| Band I. | 1817-1824.</hi></p>
<p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
<height quantity="370">370</height>
<width quantity="240">240</width></p>
</binding>
</bindingDesc>]]></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">The Heinrich Simon Papers: The Pupil</hi>: <ref target="https://https:/www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-SIM-00001/1">SIM/1</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
  </table>
  <p>Write centuries in words and lowercase, such as fifteenth century, rather than using numeric forms such as 15th century or 15th-century. Insert a hyphen when the term is used adjectivally, for example, fifteenth-century binding, and when expressing an uncertain or alternative range, connect the terms with a hyphen, for instance, fifteenth- or sixteenth-century binding.</p>
  <p><gi>binding</gi> is repeatable and may be used multiple times within a single <gi>bindingDesc</gi>. Additional <gi>binding</gi> may typically be used to record successive historical bindings, for example, when details of earlier bindings are known from documentary evidence, when a codex has been rebound, or when physical traces or surviving artefacts attest to the presence of an earlier binding.</p>
  <p>Where heraldry associated with ownership appears as decoration on the binding, encode the description in detail within <gi>binding</gi> using <gi>heraldry</gi>. For guidance and examples, see the <gi>heraldry</gi> section in The John Rylands Library foundation collections.&lt;! -- Insert hyperlink--&gt;</p>
  <p>Protective enclosures associated with a binding should be described within the same <gi>binding</gi>. Any enclosure dimensions should be recorded in an additional <gi>dimensions</gi> and distinguished by <att>type</att>, using values such as <val>chemise</val>, <val>slipcase</val>, <val>satchel</val>, <val>case</val>, or <val>box</val>.</p>
  <p><gi>binding</gi> may optionally include more granular encoding to distinguish decorative, material, and condition-related aspects. Within a binding description, <code>&lt;decoNote type="binding"&gt;</code> and <gi>condition</gi> are available, as alternatives to <gi>p</gi>, dealing exclusively with information about decorative features of a binding, or about its condition, respectively. Materials used in the binding may be encoded using <code>&lt;term type="material"&gt;</code>. Other key features may also be encoded using <gi>term</gi> with a relevant <att>type</att>. For example, a bookmark or register, any movable or fixed device used to mark particular leaves or passages, may be encoded with <code>&lt;term type="bookmark"&gt;</code>. When applicable, and in all cases where controlled vocabulary is used, <gi>term</gi> should include both <att>source</att> and <att>key</att>, with the appropriate AAT identifier.</p>
  <p><hi rend="bold">General remarks: binding terminology and usage</hi></p>
  <p><hi rend="bold">Board(s)</hi> the rigid structural substrate of a binding, such as pasteboard, millboard, or another stiff support. Boards may survive even where no covering material remains.</p>
  <p><hi rend="bold">Cover(s</hi>) the outer material applied over the boards, such as leather, parchment, cloth, or paper. Covers may be absent, partial, replaced, or later than the boards.</p>
  <p>Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> use margin to describe areas of covers or boards. Margin applies to the area surrounding the text or image on a leaf or page. When describing areas of a cover or board, use cover-surface terms such as central area, upper outer area, or lower inner area.</p>
  <p><hi rend="bold">Pastedown(s)</hi> an endleaf adhered to the inner cover. Free endleaf: an endleaf that is not adhered. Endleaves should be described in <gi>binding</gi> only where they are decorated or materially distinctive.</p>
  <p><hi rend="bold">Turn-ins</hi> the portions of covering material folded over the edges of the boards and adhered to the inside surface.</p>
  <p><hi rend="bold">Edge</hi> the physical outer boundaries of a bound volume. Use head, tail, fore edge, and spine for the physical edges of the bound volume or textblock. Fore edge should be treated as singular.</p>
  <p>When describing decoration of the cut edges of leaves, use established edge-treatment terms, such as gilt, sprinkled, speckled, marbled, or painted. Use gauffered only where gilt edges are additionally impressed with decorative patterns. <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">Avoid</hi></hi> using tooled for leaf edges, to prevent confusion with tooling applied to binding surfaces.</p>
  <p><hi rend="bold">Tooling</hi> is usually the appropriate general term unless there is clear evidence for a more specific technique, such as stamping or rolling. Where applicable, use the hyphenated forms blind-tooled and gold-tooled.</p>
  <p>Any aspects of the binding that carry provenance significance should be mentioned briefly in <gi>binding</gi> to indicate their presence, but described in full in <gi>provenance</gi>, where their significance, context, and any associated evidence can be set out in detail.</p>
</div>
<div xml:id="sealDesc">
  <head><code>&lt;sealDesc&gt;</code> | seal description</head>
  <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-sealDesc.html"><gi>sealDesc</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(seal description) describes the seals or similar items related to the object described, either as a series of paragraphs or as a series of</hi> <gi>seal</gi> <hi rend="italic">elements.</hi></p>
  <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Seal(s)</hi></p>
  <p><gi>sealDesc</gi> contains information about seals or seal-like features present on an item. It commonly includes one or more <gi>seal</gi>, each instance describing a single seal. It may record details such as the number of seals present, whether they are original or later additions (where this can be determined), their location on the item, and their method of attachment or application. It may also describe physical characteristics such as material, shape, size, and colour, together with iconography or legend, any associated name or identifying information (including a person or organisation where this can be determined), associated inscriptions and their language, and condition, including whether a seal is intact or broken, or missing.</p>
</div>
<div xml:id="seal">
  <head><code>&lt;seal&gt;</code> | seal</head>
  <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-seal.html"><gi>seal</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(seal) contains a description of one seal or similar applied to the object described.</hi></p>
  <p><gi>seal</gi> within <gi>sealDesc</gi> should describe a single seal, normally using one or more <gi>p</gi>. Although the term seal is sometimes used to refer to the negative matrix of metal used to create an impression, it is also intended here to describe the resulting impression itself.</p>
  <p><gi>seal</gi> is repeatable and may be used multiple times within a single <gi>sealDesc</gi> to record each seal individually when more than one is present on a given item. Where appropriate, <gi>summary</gi> may be used within <gi>sealDesc</gi>, to provide context before listing each <gi>seal</gi>. Each <gi>seal</gi> must include <att>n</att> and one or more &lt;p&gt;. If the location of the seal is known, <gi>locus</gi> may be used within the description to indicate where it appears on the item. <att>n</att> should take values such as <val>1</val>, <val>2</val>, <val>3</val>, numbered in the order in which the seals appear.</p>
  <p>Each <gi>seal</gi> should include <att>type</att>, and <att>subtype</att> should also be used where further sub-classification is required.</p>
  <p rend="right"><att>type</att> | <att>subtype</att></p>
  <p><att>type</att> provides the primary classification of the seal.</p>
  <p><att>subtype</att> provides a further sub-classification of that seal.</p>
  <p>When describing decoration, the following <att>type</att> and <att>subtype</att> values are recommended. All values should be encoded in the singular form, as they denote conceptual categories rather than multiple instances.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell cols="2"><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<seal> @type]]></egXML></p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><p><val>pendent</val></p></cell>
      <cell><p>Seal attached to the item and suspended from it by a joining mechanism such as cord, tag, tongue, ribbon, or similar.</p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><p><val>applied</val></p></cell>
      <cell><p>Seal impressed or marked directly onto the surface of the item and is not suspended from it.</p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell cols="2"><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<seal> @subtype]]></egXML></p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><p><val>leadSeal</val></p>
        <p rend="right">lead seal</p></cell>
      <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<seal type="pendent" subtype="leadSeal">]]></egXML></p>
      <p>Seal made of lead, of any shape, typically circular and double-sided. Most often pendent.</p></cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell><p><val>goldSeal</val></p>
      <p rend="right">gold seal</p></cell>
    <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<seal type="pendent" subtype="goldSeal">]]></egXML></p>
    <p>Seal made of gold, of any shape, typically circular and double-sided. Most often pendent.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p><val>silverSeal</val></p>
    <p rend="right">silver seal</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<seal type="pendent" subtype="silverSeal">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Seal made of silver, of any shape, typically circular and double-sided. Most often pendent.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p><val>metalSeal</val></p>
    <p rend="right">metal seal</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<seal type="pendent" subtype="metalSeal">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Seal made of metal where the specific metal cannot be confidently identified, or where the seal is mixed metal or alloy. Use <val>leadSeal</val>, <val>goldSeal</val>, or <val>silverSeal</val> when identified.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p><val>claySeal</val></p>
    <p rend="right">clay seal</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<seal type="pendent" subtype="claySeal">
<seal type="applied" subtype="claySeal">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Seal impression made in clay, of any shape. Can be pendent or applied.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p><val>waxSeal</val></p>
    <p rend="right">wax seal</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<seal type="pendent" subtype="waxSeal">
<seal type="applied" subtype="waxSeal">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Seal impression made by pressing a seal matrix into softened or melted wax. Can be pendent or applied.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p><val>waferSeal</val></p>
    <p rend="right">wafer seal</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<seal type="pendent" subtype="waferSeal">
<seal type="applied" subtype="waferSeal">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Seal impression made by pressing a matrix into an adhesive wafer. Can be pendent or applied.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p><val>embossedSeal</val></p>
    <p rend="right">embossed seal</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<seal type="pendent" subtype="embossedSeal">
<seal type="applied" subtype="embossedSeal">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>A raised seal impression made by pressing a seal matrix or equivalent tool into the surface of an item using dry pressure. Most commonly applied directly to the item, but may also occur on a pendent paper or card tag.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p><val>paperedSeal</val></p>
    <p rend="right">papered seal</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<seal type="pendent" subtype="paperedSeal">
<seal type="applied" subtype="paperedSeal">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Seal impression created through paper laid over wax or other medium applied to the surface, producing a relief effect. Can be pendent or applied.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p><val>inkSeal</val></p>
    <p rend="right">ink seal</p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<seal type="applied" subtype="inkSeal">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Seal impression made by applying ink to a seal matrix or equivalent tool and pressing it onto the surface of an item.  Most often applied.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p><val>other</val></p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<seal type="pendent" subtype="other">
<seal type="applied" subtype="other">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Seal impression whose form does not match the categories above. Specify the form and material in the description.</p></cell>
</row>
<row>
  <cell><p><val>uncertain</val></p></cell>
  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<seal type="pendent" subtype="uncertain">
<seal type="applied" subtype="uncertain">]]></egXML></p>
  <p>Seal impression is present, and the attachment mode is known, but the seal manifestation cannot be confidently identified. Use only when necessary and provide a brief explanation in the description.</p></cell>
</row>
</table>
<p>This typology is restricted to physical attachment and manifestation only. The shape of a seal should <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> be encoded as <att>subtype</att>. It should be described in prose using consistent terminology: circular, diamond, irregular, oval, pentagonal, polygonal, rectangular, square, and triangular. Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> use round or circle for circular, lozenge for diamond, oblong for oval, or rectangle for rectangular.</p>
<p>For pendent seals that display designs on both sides, the terms <hi rend="italic">obverse</hi> and <hi rend="italic">reverse</hi> may be used in descriptive prose. The obverse typically carries the principal or identifying design, such as a portrait, emblem, or insignia. The reverse often contains supplementary imagery or inscriptions. These terms are appropriate for double-sided seals, especially in formal or official contexts where both sides were intended to convey meaning.</p>
<p>A single-sided seal is created using a matrix engraved on one face only, producing an impression on a single surface of the sealing material. In contrast, a double-sided seal is made using a pair of matrices engraved on both sides.</p>
<p><gi>seal</gi> may include <att>contemporary</att> to indicate whether a seal is original to the item or was added later.</p>
<p rend="attHead"><code>@contemporary</code></p>
<p><att>contemporary</att> (contemporary) specifies whether a seal is contemporary with the item to which it is affixed</p>
<p>The following values should be used:</p>
<p><val>true</val> the seal is contemporary with the item.</p>
<p><val>false</val> the seal is not contemporary with the item.</p>
<p><val>unknown</val> it is unknown whether the seal is contemporary with the item.</p>
<p>This helps distinguish seals associated with the item's original production or authentication from those reflecting later ownership, custody, or administrative handling. It is particularly useful where multiple seals are present, as individual seals on the same item may belong to different periods.</p>
<p>Dating attributes such as <att>when</att>, <att>notBefore</att>, <att>notAfter</att>, <att>from</att>, and <att>to</att> are <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> recommended for <gi>seal</gi> as standard practice because the date associated with a seal is often ambiguous. A seal may bear a date in its legend, but this does not necessarily indicate when it was applied to the item, and seals can be reused over long periods. Applying dating attributes at the level of <gi>seal</gi> can therefore introduce false precision or be misinterpreted as the date of application. Where a seal bears a date, this should normally be recorded within the descriptive prose.</p>
<p><gi>date</gi> can be used within <gi>seal</gi> to record dates associated with a seal, such as the date it was applied, issued, or created. The date may be given as free text, but it can also be normalised using <att>when</att> for exact dates, or <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att> for approximate ranges.</p>
<p>Write centuries in words and lowercase, such as fifteenth century, rather than using numeric forms such as 15th century or 15th-century. Insert a hyphen when the term is used adjectivally, for example, fifteenth-century seal, and when expressing an uncertain or alternative range, connect the terms with a hyphen, for instance, fifteenth- or sixteenth-century seal.</p>
<p>Seals should be described fully within <gi>seal</gi>. If an individual or organisation associated with a seal is already encoded elsewhere in <gi>msDesc</gi>, for example as <gi>author</gi>, and the seal can be unambiguously attributed to that same entity, the name does <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> need to be encoded again within <gi>seal</gi>.</p>
<p>Where an additional name must be recorded within <gi>seal</gi>, it should be encoded using <gi>name</gi> containing either <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> as appropriate. If the name is listed in VIAF, include both <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> on <gi>name</gi> to reference the relevant VIAF authority record. Where both display and standard forms are required, include two <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> within <gi>name</gi>, one with <att>type</att>=<val>display</val> and one with <att>type</att>=<val>standard</val>. Otherwise, a single <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> within <gi>name</gi> may be used.</p>
<p>Where a seal has provenance significance, it should also be recorded briefly in <gi>provenance</gi>, so that the ownership or custodial association indicated by the seal is made explicit. Within <gi>provenance</gi>, the associated individual or organisation should be encoded using <code>&lt;name role="fmo"&gt;</code>, containing either <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> with only the minimum contextual information necessary to support the provenance interpretation. The detailed physical description of the seal should remain in <gi>seal</gi>, while the provenance note should provide a concise statement of the association and the evidence on which it is based.</p>
<p>Where a seal incorporates heraldry associated with ownership, the heraldic description should be encoded in detail within <gi>seal</gi> using <gi>heraldry</gi>. For guidance and examples, see the <gi>heraldry</gi> section in The John Rylands Library foundation collections.&lt;! -- Insert hyperlink--&gt;</p>
<p>The physical size of the seal, including <gi>height</gi>, <gi>width</gi>, and <gi>depth</gi> each with <att>quantity</att>, should be encoded using <code>&lt;dimensions type="seal"&gt;</code>.</p>
<table rend="rules">
  <row>
    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Seal(s):</hi></p>
      <p>Circular, double-sided pendent lead seal of Cosimo I de’ Medici, attached by cords and suspended from the lower edge of the parchment.</p>
      <p>On the obverse, an eight-pointed cross of the Order of Saint Stephen, surrounded by the legend <hi rend="italic">SANCTI STEPHANI SIGNVM RELIGIONIS</hi>.</p>
      <p>On the reverse, the arms of the House of Medici: Or, six roundels, five Gules and in chief one Azure charged with three fleurs‑de‑lis Or, surrounded by the legend <hi rend="italic">COSIMVS MAG. DUX ETR. MAGN. MAGIS</hi>.</p>
      <p>Seal height 38-41 mm, width 38-41.</p>
      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<sealDesc>
<seal type="pendent" subtype="leadSeal" contemporary="true">
<p>Circular, double-sided pendent lead seal of Cosimo I de’ Medici, attached by cords and suspended from the lower edge of the parchment.</p>
<p>On the <locus from="4" to="4">obverse</locus>, an eight-pointed cross of the <name source="#viaf key="156663616"><orgName type="display">Order of Saint Stephen</orgName><orgName type="standard">Sacro militare ordine di Santo Stefano papa e martire</orgName></name>, surrounded by the legend <hi rend="italic">SANCTI STEPHANI SIGNVM RELIGIONIS</hi>.</p>
<p>On the <locus from="3" to="3">reverse</locus>, the arms of the House of Medici: <heraldry>Or, six roundels, five Gules and in chief one Azure charged with three fleurs‑de‑lis Or</heraldry>, surrounded by the legend <hi rend="italic">COSIMVS MAG. DUX ETR. MAGN. MAGIS.</hi></p>
<p><dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
<height atLeast="38" atMost="41">38-41</height>
<width atLeast="38" atMost="41">38-41</width>
</dimensions></p>
</seal>
</sealDesc>]]></egXML></p>
      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Patent of Cosimo I</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-MDC-00027/1">MDC/27</ref></p></cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Seal(s):</hi></p>
      <p>Oval wafer seal of Ferdinando II de’ Medici, applied on the verso of the letter bearing the arms of the House of Medici: Or, six roundels, five Gules and in chief one Azure charged with three fleurs‑de‑lis Or, surrounded by the legend <hi rend="italic">FERDINANDVS II MAG. DVX ETRVRIÆ III</hi>.</p>
      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><sealDesc>
<seal type="applied" subtype="waferSeal" contemporary="true">
<p>Oval wafer seal of Ferdinando II de’ Medici applied on the <locus from="2" to="2">verso</locus> of the letter bearing the arms of the House of Medici: <heraldry>Or, six roundels, five Gules and in chief one Azure charged with three fleurs‑de‑lis Or</heraldry>, surrounded by the legend <hi rend="italic">FERDINANDVS II MAG. DVX ETRVRIÆ III</hi>.</p>
</seal>
</sealDesc></egXML></p>
      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Letter from Ferdinando II</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-MDC-00131/1">MDC/131</ref></p></cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Seal(s):</hi></p>
      <p>Irregular circular red wax seal of Heinrich Simon, applied on the verso of the folded letter: <hi rend="italic">H Simon</hi> in calligraphic cursive with flourishes, framed by a cross-hatched (diamond-shaped) pattern.</p>
      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><sealDesc>
<seal type="applied" subtype="waxSeal" contemporary="true">
<p>Irregular circular red wax seal of Heinrich Simon, applied on the <locus from="4" to="4">verso</locus> of the folded letter: <hi rend="italic">H Simon</hi> in calligraphic cursive with flourishes, framed by a cross-hatched (diamond-shaped) pattern.</p>
</seal>
</sealDesc></egXML></p>
      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Letter from Heinrich Simon to his parents Herrmann and Minna Simon</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-SIM-00001-00197/1">SIM1/197</ref></p></cell>
  </row>
</table>
<p>Use <code>&lt;hi</code> <code>rend="italic"&gt;</code> to present a literal transcription consistently and without quotation marks. <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">Avoid</hi></hi> using <gi>quote</gi> for seal legends, as a legend is an inscribed text on an object, not a quotation. If you prefer quotation marks, you may either record the legend as plain text in quotation marks or encode it using <gi>q</gi>, but do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> use <gi>quote</gi>.</p>
<p>A seal that no longer survives may still be recorded using <gi>seal</gi> where physical or documentary evidence indicates that it was once present. This practice is optional and should be followed only where the project, catalogue, or descriptive pattern systematically records seals, including evidence for those now missing.</p>
<p>If traces of a former seal survive, such as remnants of wax, broken tags or cords, or stitch holes, <gi>seal</gi> may still be used to describe that evidence, even though the seal itself is missing. The surviving evidence should be described briefly and factually in <gi>p</gi>. <att>type</att> should be included where the method of attachment can be identified. <att>subtype</att> should be used only if the seal medium can be confidently inferred. <att>contemporary</att> may also be included where applicable.</p>
<p>Distinguish seals from stamps. <gi>seal</gi> should be used for seals or sealing devices with an authenticating, validating, authorising, or securing function. Inked impressions that do not function as seals should be described as stamps and may be encoded with <gi>stamp</gi>. Depending on their function, stamps may be recorded in <gi>additions</gi> or, where they provide evidence of ownership or custodial history, in <gi>provenance</gi>.</p>
<p><gi>seal</gi> may optionally include more granular encoding to distinguish decorative, material, and condition-related aspects. Within a seal description, <code>&lt;decoNote type="seal"&gt;</code> and <gi>condition</gi> are available, as alternatives to <gi>p</gi>, dealing exclusively with information about decorative features of a seal, or about its condition, respectively. Materials used in the seal may be encoded using <code>&lt;term type="material"&gt;</code>. Other key features may also be encoded using <gi>term</gi> with relevant <att>type</att>. When applicable, and in all cases where controlled vocabulary is used, <gi>term</gi> should include both <att>source</att> and <att>key</att>, with the appropriate AAT identifier.</p>
</div>
<div xml:id="accMat">
  <head><code>&lt;accMat&gt;</code> | accompanying material</head>
  <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-accMat.html"><gi>accMat</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(accompanying material) contains details of any significant additional material which may be closely associated with the manuscript or object being described, such as non-contemporaneous documents or fragments bound in with it at some earlier historical period.</hi></p>
  <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Accompanying material</hi></p>
  <p><gi>accMat</gi> is the final component within <gi>physDesc</gi> and is used to record any material that is physically associated with the described item but was not originally part of its structure. It captures significant material that has been bound in, enclosed with, affixed to, or otherwise accompanies the item, but was not integrated into its production or textual formation.</p>
  <p><gi>additions</gi> records changes or interventions made directly to the item itself, such as annotations, corrections, or inscriptions, <gi>accMat</gi> describes additional material that accompanies the item in a physical or contextual sense.</p>
  <p>Accompanying material may include loose sheets, inserts, or enclosures supplied with the item, as well as letters, notes, or slips inserted into it. It may also include separate leaflets, pamphlets, or booklets issued with the main item. Folded documents stored with the item, such as certificates or receipts, may also be included. Supplementary visual material, such as photographs, plates, or prints, should be treated as accompanying material where it is present as an addition rather than as integral content. External packaging, including labels, wrappers, or containers, may also be recorded where it materially accompanies the item and is significant enough to describe. This applies to packaging that is loose, curatorial, or not physically or historically part of the item.</p>
  <p>If the wrapper or container is original, purpose-made, or historically associated with the item’s creation or use, for example, a textile case made for a manuscript, an attached chemise binding, or a historic slipcase with inscriptions or decoration, it should be described in <gi>binding</gi> as part of the item's original or historically intended enclosure.</p>
  <p>Any accompanying material associated with the item should be recorded in <gi>accMat</gi>, with each entry described in a separate <gi>p</gi> and using <gi>locus</gi> where relevant to indicate where it is located. The description should record the quantity and nature of the material, how it is physically present, and any identifying features, such as handwriting, printed text, dates, names, or other identifying marks.</p>
  <p>Within <gi>accMat</gi>, names are descriptive and do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> normally require encoding with <gi>name</gi> or <att>role</att>. If a name needs to be indexed or displayed as an associated person or organisation, encode it using <gi>name</gi> with an appropriate <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi>. Where authority control is available, or where display and indexed forms need to be distinguished, <gi>name</gi> may contain both display and standard forms.</p>
  <p><gi>date</gi> can be used within <gi>accMat</gi> to record dates associated with accompanying material, such as the date a document was issued, added, or created. The date may be given as free text, but it can also be normalised using <att>when</att> for exact dates, or <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att> for approximate ranges.</p>
  <p>Where accompanying material is of provenance significance, it should also be recorded briefly in <gi>provenance</gi>, so that the ownership or custodial association indicated by the seal is made explicit. Within <gi>provenance</gi>, the associated individual or organisation should be encoded using <code>&lt;name role="fmo"&gt;</code>, containing either <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> with only the minimum contextual information necessary to support the provenance interpretation. The detailed physical description of the accompanying material should remain in <gi>accMat</gi>, while the provenance note should provide a concise statement of the association and the evidence on which it is based.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Accompanying material:</hi></p>
        <p>Tipped-in letter from Henry Tattam to Johann Ludwig Krapf, concerning the manuscript, dated 17 January 1869.</p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><accMat>
<p><locus from="Endleaf_1r" to="Endleaf_1r">Tipped-in letter</locus> from Henry Tattam to Johann Ludwig Krapf, concerning the manuscript, dated <date when="1825-01-17">17 January 1869</date>.</p>
</accMat></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Gadla ḥawāryāt</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-ETHIOPIC-00006/1">Ethiopic MS 6</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Accompanying material:</hi></p>
        <p>Loose note inserted in the volume, probably an eighteenth-century letter cover: <hi rend="italic">A sua Eccellenza ... Il Sigre Principe D. Matteo Barberini Colonna di Sciarra Roma</hi>.</p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><accMat>
<p><locus from="Tipped_in_note_r" to="Tipped_in_note_r">Loose note</locus> inserted in the volume, probably an eighteenth-century letter cover: <hi rend="italic">A sua Eccellenza ... Il Sig<hi rend="superscript">re</hi> Principe D. Matteo Barberini Colonna di Sciarra Roma</hi>. </p>
</accMat></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Colonna Missal I</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00032/1">Latin MS 32</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
  </table>
  <p>A leaf that was missing from the codex at the time of acquisition but has since been recovered should be recorded in <gi>accMat</gi> if it is now preserved separately alongside the manuscript. Although it belongs to the manuscript, it accompanies it rather than forming part of its current physical structure. In such cases, the recovered leaf should also be described in full as a separate <gi>msPart</gi>.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Accompanying material:</hi></p>
        <p>The leaf formerly missing between 132v and 133r has now been secured and is preserved separately as Latin MS 22 A.</p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<accMat>
<p>The leaf formerly missing between 132v and 133r has now been secured and is preserved separately as <ref target=""https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00022/347">Latin MS 22 A</ref>.</p>
</accMat>]]></egXML></p>
        <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Psalter of Joan of Navarre</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00022/1">Latin MS 22</ref></p></cell>
    </row>
  </table>
</div>
<div xml:id="history">
  <head><code>&lt;history&gt;</code> | history</head>
  <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-history.html"><gi>history</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(history) groups elements describing the full history of a manuscript, manuscript part, or other object.</hi></p>
  <p><gi>history</gi> provides a structured container for recording what is known about an item’s history, from its creation to the present day. This may include information about its place and date of creation, later changes of ownership or custody, and the means by which it came into its current holding institution.</p>
  <p>The following elements are used within <gi>history</gi> to record this information:</p>
  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<teiHeader>
<fileDesc>|<titleStmt>|<PublicationStmt>|<sourceDesc>|<msDesc>|
<msContents>|<physDesc>
<history>
<origin>
<!-- Metadata about the origin of an item, its place and date of its creation -->
<!-- Contains <origDate> and <origPlace> -->
</origin>
<provenance>
<!-- Metadata about the stages in the history of an item before acquisition-->
</provenance>
<acquisition>
<!-- Metadata about the means by which an item was acquired -->
</acquisition>
</history>
<additional/>|</msDesc>| </sourceDesc>|</fileDesc>|<encodingDesc>|<profileDesc>|
<revisionDesc>
</teiHeader>]]></egXML></p>
</div>
<div xml:id="origin">
  <head><code>&lt;origin&gt;</code> | origin</head>
  <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-origin.html"><gi>origin</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(origin) contains any descriptive or other information concerning the origin of a manuscript, manuscript part, or other object.</hi></p>
  <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Origin</hi></p>
  <p><gi>origin</gi> may contain two elements, <gi>origDate</gi>, used to record the date of origin, and <gi>origPlace</gi>, used to record the place of origin. These elements may be used independently as standalone components or integrated into a prose description.</p>
</div>
<div xml:id="origdate">
  <head><code>&lt;origdate&gt;</code> | origin date</head>
  <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-origDate.html"><gi>origDate</gi></ref>  <hi rend="italic">(origin date) contains any form of date, used to identify the date of origin for a manuscript, manuscript part, or other object.</hi></p>
  <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Date of Creation</hi></p>
  <p><gi>origDate</gi> within <gi>origin</gi> is used to record the date associated with the production or creation of the item. It should normally be included where date information is available, whether as a specific date, partial date, date span, or approximate range. If an exact date cannot be determined, the most precise date range supported by the evidence may be encoded.</p>
  <p><gi>origDate</gi> is a member of the <ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-att.datable.html">att.datable</ref> class, which in turn inherits from the <ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-att.datable.w3c.html">att.datable.w3c</ref> class. It therefore includes attributes such as <att>when</att>, <att>from</att>, <att>to</att>, <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att>.</p>
  <p rend="right"><att>when</att> | <att>from</att>, <att>to</att> | <att>notBefore</att>, <att>notAfter</att></p>
  <p><att>when</att> supplies the value of a known single date in standard form.</p>
  <p><att>from</att>, <att>to</att> indicate the starting and ending points of the period in standard form.</p>
  <p><att>notBefore</att>, <att>notAfter</att> specify the earliest and latest possible dates for the item’s creation in standard form.</p>
  <p>Values supplied in these attributes must conform to W3C ISO 8601 format. They are usually encoded as YYYY-MM-DD, but may be reduced to YYYY-MM or YYYY where full precision is not available.</p>
  <p>In TEI-XML, standard dating attributes are interpreted as Gregorian or proleptic Gregorian by default. Consequently, <att>calendar</att>=<val>gregorian</val> is <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> required, since the calendar system is already assumed.</p>
  <p>Where a date is expressed or normalised using a calendar system other than the Gregorian calendar, use the custom dating attributes together with <att>datingMethod</att> and <att>calendar</att> of the <ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-att.datable.custom.html">att.datable.custom</ref> class. For more information, see <hi rend="bold">&lt;! -- hyperlink non-Gregorian dates | other calendar system --&gt;</hi></p>
  <p>BCE dates follow the same standard dating attributes, but require specific formatting in the encoded value. The standard attributes are based on the extended proleptic Gregorian calendar, meaning that the Gregorian calendar is applied retrospectively to dates that predate its historical introduction.</p>
  <p><hi rend="bold">BCE (Before Common Era) | CE (Common Era)</hi></p>
  <p>Use BCE for dates before the Common Era. Use CE where a date range spans BCE and CE, for example, 75 BCE–15 CE. Use CE also where a year under 100 is presented in isolation, for example, 15 CE, as such small numbers can be misread without an era marker. In all other cases, dates without a BCE suffix are presumed to be in the Common or Current Era.</p>
  <table rend="rules">
    <row>
      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 75 BCE-15 CE</p>
        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="-0075" notAfter="0015">75 BCE-15 CE</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
      </row>
    </table>
    <p>BCE dates are encoded as negative four-digit numbers, using a minus sign, for example, 15 BCE is encoded as <val>-0015</val>. CE dates are encoded as four-digit numbers with leading zeroes where needed, for example 15 CE is encoded as <val>0015</val>.</p>
    <table rend="rules">
      <row>
        <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 15 BCE</p>
          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate when="-0015">15 BCE</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 15 CE</p>
            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate when="0015">15 CE</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
          </row>
        </table>
        <p> <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">Avoid</hi></hi> using BC (Before Christ) or AD (Anno Domini). Instead, use the neutral and inclusive terms CE (Common or Current Era) and BCE (Before the Common or Current Era). Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> include full stops, use BCE and CE, <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> B.C.E. or C.E. Use CE only when the date would otherwise be ambiguous. For example, the Norman Conquest took place in 1066, <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> 1066 CE or AD 1066.</p>
        <p><hi rend="bold">Known single date | @when</hi></p>
        <p>The date of creation is known as a single specific point in time. A single known date can be encoded as precisely as the available information allows.</p>
        <p>@when may be used for a complete date, a month and year, or a year only. If the date is partial, any unspecified part of the value may be omitted.</p>
        <table rend="rules">
          <row>
            <cell><p rend="right">full date is known | <code>YYYY-MM-DD</code></p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 30 August 1821</p>
              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate when="1821-08-30">30 August 1821</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><p rend="right">only month and year is known | <code>YYYY-MM</code></p>
                <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> August 1821</p>
                <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate when="1821-08">August 1821</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell><p rend="right">only year is known | <code>YYYY</code></p>
                  <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 1821</p>
                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate when="1821">1821</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                </row>
              </table>
              <p>If the date appears in a contracted or non-standard form, expand shortened years, for example 1999 rather than 99. Use cardinal, <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> ordinal, forms for days, for example 21 March rather than 21st March. Use Arabic numerals rather than Roman numerals, for example 18 rather than XVIII. Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> include commas, add a leading zero to days 1 to 9, or abbreviate month names.</p>
              <p>Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> include additional wording such as in the year and anno or days of the week within <gi>origDate</gi>. If If the wording of the date as it appears on the item is significant, transcribe it in an optional note using <gi>p</gi> within <gi>origin</gi>.</p>
              <p>For example:</p>
              <p>20 July 1698, where the item reads the 20th of July, anno Dom. 1698</p>
              <p>25 December 1945, where the item reads Christmas Day, 1945</p>
              <p>4 July 1760, where the item reads July 4 MDCCLX</p>
              <p>If an item includes an explicit production date, such as in a colophon, transcribe the statement within <gi>colophon</gi>.</p>
              <p>Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> use an MM-DD value for <att>when</att>. Without a year, the date cannot identify when the item was created. If the item gives a month and/or day but the year is missing, and a year can be supplied from other evidence, encode the conjectural date using <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att> as appropriate (see <code>&lt;!--hyperlink--&gt;</code>).</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">Known date span | @from @to</hi></p>
              <p>The creation of the item took place over a defined period rather than at a single specific point in time.</p>
              <p><att>from</att> and <att>to</att> are used when both the beginning and end of the date span are known. This applies to items created over time, such as diaries, journal-letters, or sequences of correspondence written across multiple dates.</p>
              <table rend="rules">
                <row>
                  <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 16-22 November 1824</p>
                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate from="1824-11-16" to="1824-11-22">16-22 November 1824</origDate></egXML></p>
                    <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Letter from Heinrich Simon to his family (</hi><ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-SIM-00002-00023_00023-A_E/1">SIM/2/23 and 23a-e</ref>)<hi rend="italic">, written over several days</hi></p></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 1816-1824</p>
                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate from="1816" to="1824">1816-1814</origDate></egXML></p>
                    <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">The Heinrich Simon papers: The Pupil:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-SIM-00001/1">SIM/1</ref></p>
                    <list rend="bulleted">
                      <item><hi rend="italic">Inclusive dates are given as 1816-1824,</hi> <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> <hi rend="italic">1816-24</hi></item>
                    </list></cell>
                </row>
              </table>
              <p>A date span encoded with <att>from</att> and <att>to</att> is less common than an imprecise date range. Where the date cannot be precisely determined but is known to fall between two possible points, use <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att> instead.</p>
              <p><hi rend="bold">uncertain date limits | @notBefore @notAfter</hi></p>
              <p>The exact date of creation is not known, but the item can be dated within known limits.</p>
              <p><att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att> are used for broad or approximate dating, where the evidence supports an earliest and/or latest possible date. This applies to periods such as centuries, parts of centuries, decades, or other unspecified spans.</p>
              <p>These attributes may be used either individually or together. <att>notBefore</att> may be used where only the earliest limit (terminus a quo) can be established. <att>notAfte</att>r may be used where only the latest limit (terminus ad quem) can be established. Both attributes should be used where the date can be bounded at both ends.</p>
              <div xml:id="centuries-parts-of-centuries">
                <head>Centuries | parts of centuries</head>
                <p>Historical and pre-modern materials often lack explicit evidence for a precise date of origin. Catalogues and records may also vary in the level of detail they provide, and in the conventions used to express approximate dating.</p>
                <p>Where a precise date of creation cannot be established, an item may nevertheless be attributed to a particular century, half-century, part of a century, decade, or other approximate period.</p>
                <p>The following conventions for centuries and parts of centuries are based on Ker’s dating system for medieval manuscripts. Ker-style and other legacy dating forms, such as s. XIII, should <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> be reproduced directly in <gi>origDate</gi>. Instead, the textual value should use ordinal numbers and Arabic numerals for centuries, for example 13th century, <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> thirteenth century or s. XIII. Further specifications should follow after a comma, for example, 13th century, first half. Superscript should <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> be used, and century should be recorded in lowercase. The corresponding limits should be encoded with <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att>.</p>
                <p>Century-level attributions should be encoded according to conventional calendrical boundaries. A century begins in the year ending in 01 and ends in the year ending in 00. For example, the thirteenth century is normalised as 1201-1300, <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> 1200-1299 or 1200-1300. Using 1200-1299 excludes the final year of the thirteenth century. Using 1200-1300 covers 101 years and misplaces 1200, which is the final year of the twelfth century. The values used for approximate subdivisions are inclusive and may overlap. For example, early, middle, and late parts of a century are not mutually exclusive. Use round numbers to define these limits, for example 1201 to 1250 for the first half of the thirteenth century.</p>
                <p><hi rend="bold">Entire century | xx01–xx00</hi></p>
                <table rend="rules">
                  <row>
                    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 13th century</p>
                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1201" notAfter="1300">13th century</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                    </row>
                  </table>
                  <p><hi rend="bold">Beginning of a century | xx01–xx30</hi></p>
                  <table rend="rules">
                    <row>
                      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 13th century, early</p>
                        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1201" notAfter="1230">13th century, early</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                      </row>
                    </table>
                    <p><hi rend="bold">Middle of a century | xx30–xx70</hi></p>
                    <table rend="rules">
                      <row>
                        <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 13th century, middle</p>
                          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1230" notAfter="1270">13th century, middle</origDate></egXML></p>
                          <list rend="bulleted">
                            <item><hi rend="italic">Use middle,</hi> <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> <hi rend="italic">mid or mid-, when recording the middle part of a century.</hi></item>
                          </list></cell>
                      </row>
                    </table>
                    <p><hi rend="bold">End of a century | (xx70–xx00)</hi></p>
                    <table rend="rules">
                      <row>
                        <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 13th century, late</p>
                          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1270" notAfter="1300">13th century, late</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                        </row>
                      </table>
                      <p><hi rend="bold">1st half of a century | xx01–xx50</hi></p>
                      <table rend="rules">
                        <row>
                          <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 13th century, first half</p>
                            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1201" notAfter="1250">13th century, first half</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                          </row>
                        </table>
                        <p><hi rend="bold">2nd half of a century | xx50–xx00</hi></p>
                        <table rend="rules">
                          <row>
                            <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 13th century, second half</p>
                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1250" notAfter="1300">13th century, second half</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                            </row>
                          </table>
                          <p><hi rend="bold">1st – 4th quarter of a century</hi></p>
                          <p rend="right">First (xx01–xx25) | Second (xx25–xx50) | Third (xx50–xx75) | Fourth (xx75–xx00)</p>
                          <table rend="rules">
                            <row>
                              <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 13th century, first quarter</p>
                                <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1201" notAfter="1225">13th century, first quarter</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                              </row>
                            </table>
                            <p>When encoding centuries and their subdivisions, use inclusive Gregorian ranges that reflect the inherent imprecision of historical dating. These intervals allow for intentional overlap and support the representation of transitions, ambiguity, and interpretative flexibility. Use rounded, inclusive boundaries to convey the approximate nature of period terms.</p>
                            <p><hi rend="bold">two centuries</hi></p>
                            <table rend="rules">
                              <row>
                                <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 13th–14th centuries</p>
                                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1201" notAfter="1400">13th-14th centuries</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                </row>
                              </table>
                              <p><hi rend="bold">Early to middle Xth century</hi></p>
                              <table rend="rules">
                                <row>
                                  <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 13th century, early–middle</p>
                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1201" notAfter="1270">13th century, early-middle</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                  </row>
                                </table>
                                <p><hi rend="bold">Late Xth century to early Xth century</hi></p>
                                <table rend="rules">
                                  <row>
                                    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 13th century, late–14th century, early</p>
                                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1270" notAfter="1330">13th century, late–14th century, early</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                    </row>
                                  </table>
                                </div>
                                <div xml:id="conjectural-dates-approximate-uncertain-unknown">
                                  <head>Conjectural dates | approximate | uncertain | unknown</head>
                                  <p>Conjectural, approximate, uncertain, and supplied dates are dates based on incomplete, partial, indirect, or contextual evidence rather than direct confirmation from the item itself. Such dates may be based on historical references, physical evidence, textual evidence, related documentation, or scholarly judgement.</p>
                                  <p><hi rend="bold">@notBefore @notAfter</hi></p>
                                  <p>Where the date of creation cannot be determined precisely, an estimated, probable, approximate, or supplied date may be recorded, provided that its uncertain status is encoded explicitly. Use <att>notBefore</att> and/or <att>notAfter</att> to record the earliest and latest possible date boundaries. The values of these attributes can range from a broad year to a more specific year-month or year-month-day, depending on the level of certainty available. This distinguishes an inferred or conjectural date from a known date recorded with <att>when</att>.</p>
                                  <p>Where the date of creation cannot be determined precisely, an estimated, probable, approximate, or supplied date may be recorded, provided that its uncertain status is encoded explicitly using <att>cert</att> and, where appropriate, <att>evidence</att>.</p>
                                  <p><hi rend="bold">@cert</hi></p>
                                  <p><att>cert</att> (certainty) signifies the degree of certainty associated with the dating.</p>
                                  <p>The following values should be used:</p>
                                  <p><val>high</val> the dating is generally considered to be correct.</p>
                                  <p>Inferred | a certain date is known but not explicitly stated on the item. In other catalogues or finding aids, such dates may be recorded in square brackets, for example, [1821] or [182-] for something certainly published during the 1820s.</p>
                                  <p><val>medium</val> the dating is generally considered approximately correct.</p>
                                  <p>Approximate | a date that may not be exact, but is approximated, or is a rough estimate. In other catalogues or finding aids, variations of circa may be used, with or without punctuation or spaces, for example, ca. 1821, c. 1821, or circa 1821.</p>
                                  <p><val>low</val> the dating is generally considered doubtful but possible.</p>
                                  <p>Questionable | a date that is probable but might be questionable, uncertain, or incorrect. In other catalogues or finding aids, such dates may be recorded with a question mark, for example, 1821? or ?1821.</p>
                                  <p><val>unknown</val> no wish to assert an opinion, as the level of certainty is unknown.</p>
                                  <p>Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> use <att>cert</att> with <att>when</att>, <att>from</att> and <att>to</att>, as these attributes record a known date or date interval. The absence of <att>cert</att> implies a high degree of certainty. Instead, use <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att> to encode uncertain, approximate, or conjectural date boundaries.</p>
                                  <p><hi rend="bold">@evidence</hi></p>
                                  <p><att>evidence</att> indicates the nature of the evidence supporting the dating.</p>
                                  <p>The following values should be used:</p>
                                  <p><val>internal</val> the dating is based on evidence internal to the item, for example, an inscription, a script.</p>
                                  <p><val>external</val> the dating is based on evidence external to the item, for example, a reference to the item in another context.</p>
                                  <p><val>conjecture</val> the dating is based on conjecture. No specific evidence is available to support the dating. The date has been inferred by the encoder, cataloguer, or scholar based on their expertise and analysis of the item.</p>
                                  <table rend="rules">
                                    <row>
                                      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Publication:</hi> 1475</p>
                                        <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi></p>
                                        <p>Schreiber (1969-1976) states that the coat of arms of Pope Sixtus IV on leaf [*1] verso proves that the blockbook was made between 1471-1484, most probably in 1475 because of the Jubilee in that year.</p>
                                        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<p>Schreiber (1969-1976) states that the coat of arms of Pope Sixtus IV on leaf [*1] verso proves that the blockbook was made between 1471-1484, most probably in <origDate notBefore="1475" notAfter="1475" cert= "high" evidence="external">1475</origDate> because of the Jubilee in that year.</p>
</origin></egXML></p></cell>
                                      </row>
                                    </table>
                                    <p><att>cert</att> and <att>evidence</att> do not have to be used together.</p>
                                    <p>If no date of creation can be found in the item itself or determined from another source, but a date can be estimated, record the most precise probable dating that the evidence supports. The basis for the supplied or conjectural date should be explained in a <gi>p</gi> within <gi>origin</gi>, including the source of the information and how the dating was determined. Maintain consistency in the language used to express uncertainty:</p>
                                    <p><hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">probably</hi></hi> — highly likely to be the case than not (&gt;50% chance) — <att>cert</att>=<val>high</val></p>
                                    <p><hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">possibly</hi></hi> — could be the case or be true but not certain (&lt;50% chance) — <att>cert</att>=<val>medium</val> | <val>low</val></p>
                                    <p><hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">approximately</hi></hi> — around or about or close to an exact date, but not precise</p>
                                    <p>Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> use square brackets ([ ]), question marks (?), or any other markup normally used in MARC | RDA, or other cataloguing standards to indicate uncertainty, supplied or conjectural dates, missing or incorrect information.</p>
                                    <p>When assigning a date, particularly based on physical evidence, the distinction between an approximate or probable date and a known date relies on judgment.</p>
                                  </div>
                                  <div xml:id="approximate-estimated-dates">
                                    <head>Approximate | estimated dates</head>
                                    <p>Where exact dates are unknown but can be inferred, terms such as approximately or circa are often used, both in historical records and modern documentation, to indicate an estimated date based on contextual evidence.</p>
                                    <p>These terms are typically used when no direct evidence exists to support a precise date. Instead, the date is inferred by the encoder, cataloguer, or scholar through expertise and analytical judgement. Such inferences are educated estimates, grounded in indirect or incomplete evidence, including stylistic features, references to historical circumstances, physical evidence, production methods, or other contextual indicators.</p>
                                    <p>Although circa is traditionally used in historical description, and approximately may be clearer in modern explanatory prose, <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">neither</hi></hi> form should be recorded as part of the textual value within <gi>origDate</gi>. In TEI, uncertainty should be encoded explicitly using the appropriate attributes and explained in prose where necessary.</p>
                                    <p>When supplying or inferring a date, especially from physical or contextual evidence, use judgement to determine whether the evidence supports a single probable date or only a broader date range. If the evidence supports a single supplied or inferred date, use <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att> with the same value to distinguish the supplied or inferred date from a known date encoded with <att>when</att>. If the date is based on educated judgement or indirect evidence, use <att>cert</att> to indicate the degree of certainty. Use <att>evidence</att> to indicate the nature of the evidence supporting the dating, such as internal, external, or conjecture. Explain the reasoning in a <gi>p</gi> within <gi>origin</gi>, including the evidence and other contextual details for the supplied date.</p>
                                    <p>If the precise date of creation is not known, record the most precise probable date that the evidence supports. For example, if an item is likely to have been created during the mid-1850s, but the exact year is uncertain, the approximate year may be recorded as 1855.</p>
                                    <table rend="rules">
                                      <row>
                                        <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 1855</p>
                                          <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi></p>
                                          <p>The creation date is approximately 1855, inferred from the style and production methods of the item.</p>
                                          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<p>The creation date is approximately <origDate notBefore="1855" notAfter="1855" cert="medium" evidence="internal">1855</origDate>, inferred from the style and production methods of the item..</p>
</origin></egXML></p></cell>
                                        </row>
                                      </table>
                                      <p>Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> include approximate qualifiers such as approximately, circa, c., ca., around, or about in the textual value of <gi>origDate</gi>.</p>
                                      <p>Where a broader range is more accurate than a supplied single date, record the range instead. For example, if one item in a collection is known or strongly suspected to date from around 1850 and another from around 1859, while the rest are likely to date from the same decade, record the terminal dates as a range rather than using the vaguer form 1850s.</p>
                                      <table rend="rules">
                                        <row>
                                          <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 1850-1859</p>
                                            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1850" notAfter="1859">1850-1859</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                          </row>
                                        </table>
                                        <p> <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">Avoid</hi></hi> ambiguous or redundant constructions such as 1850s or circa 1850s. Inclusive dates are given as 1850-1859, not 1850-9 or 1850-59.</p>
                                      </div>
                                      <div xml:id="uncertain-date-within-known-range">
                                        <head>Uncertain date within known range</head>
                                        <p><hi rend="bold">between YYYY and YYYY</hi></p>
                                        <p>The creation date of an item is uncertain but falls within a specific date range.</p>
                                        <table rend="rules">
                                          <row>
                                            <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 1846-1874</p>
                                              <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi></p>
                                              <p>Broadside Ballads Online suggests that John Harkness, printer, of Preston, was active between 1840 and 1866, however advertisements in the 'Preston Chronicle' indicate that he was trading from 121 Church Street by August 1846 and continued there until at least 1874.</p>
                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<origDate notBefore="1846" notAfter="1874" cert="high" evidence="external">1846-1874</origDate>
<p>Broadside Ballads Online suggests that John Harkness, printer, of Preston, was active between 1840 and 1866. However, advertisements in the 'Preston Chronicle' indicate that he was trading from 121 Church Street by August 1846 and continued there until at least 1874.</p>
</origin></egXML></p>
                                              <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Broadside Ballad: Peterloo:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-R-00002-26579-00108/1">R226579.108</ref></p>
                                              <list rend="bulleted">
                                                <item><hi rend="italic">between 1846 and 1874</hi> <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> <hi rend="italic">between 1846-1874</hi></item>
                                              </list></cell>
                                          </row>
                                        </table>
                                      </div>
                                      <div xml:id="uncertain-date-one-date-or-the-other">
                                        <head>Uncertain date | one date or the other</head>
                                        <p><hi rend="bold">in YYYY or YYYY</hi></p>
                                        <p>The creation date of an item is uncertain and could be one of two possible dates or date ranges, such as one year or another, or one century or another.</p>
                                        <table rend="rules">
                                          <row>
                                            <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 1476-1477</p>
                                              <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi></p>
                                              <p>Believed to have been printed by Caxton in the earliest years of his innovative printing business in London, in either 1476 or 1477.</p>
                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<origDate notBefore="1476" notAfter="1477" cert="high" evidence="external">1476-1477</origDate>
<p>Believed to have been printed by Caxton in the earliest years of his innovative printing business in London, in either 1476 or 1477.</p>
</origin></egXML></p></cell>
                                            </row>
                                            <row>
                                              <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 17th-18th century</p>
                                                <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi></p>
                                                <p>The style of the script suggests that the manuscript from which this originated was probably copied in the 17th or 18th century, although the sample is too small to confirm this with certainty.</p>
                                                <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<origDate notBefore="1601" notAfter="1800" cert="low" evidence="internal">17th-18th century</origDate>
<p>The style of the script suggests that the manuscript from which this originated was probably copied in the seventeenth or eighteenth century, although the sample is too small to confirm this with certainty.</p>
</origin></egXML></p></cell>
                                              </row>
                                            </table>
                                          </div>
                                          <div xml:id="date-supplied-from-reference-sources">
                                            <head>Date supplied from reference sources</head>
                                            <p>The date is not directly available from the item but is supplied based on reference sources, such as historical records, external documentation, or scholarly analysis.</p>
                                            <table rend="rules">
                                              <row>
                                                <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 1850</p>
                                                  <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi> Kornicki (1993) dates the map to 1850, using Beans (1951, page 26) as reference.</p>
                                                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<p>Kornicki (1993) dates the map to <origDate notBefore="1850" notAfter="1850" cert="high" evidence="external">1850</origDate>, using Beans (1951, page 26) as reference.</p>
</origin></egXML></p>
                                                  <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Nikkō oyama no ezu:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-JAPANESE-00109/1">Japanese 109</ref></p></cell>
                                              </row>
                                              <row>
                                                <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 1475</p>
                                                  <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi> Schreiber (1969-1976) states that the coat of arms of Pope Sixtus IV on leaf [*1] verso proves that the blockbook was made between 1471-1484, most probably in 1475 because of the Jubilee in that year.</p>
                                                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<p>Schreiber (1969-1976) states that the coat of arms of Pope Sixtus IV on leaf [*1] verso proves that the blockbook was made between 1471-1484, most probably in <origDate notBefore="1475" notAfter="1475" cert="high" evidence="external">1475</origDate> because of the Jubilee in that year.</p>
</origin></egXML></p></cell>
                                                </row>
                                              </table>
                                            </div>
                                            <div xml:id="dates-based-on-contextual-evidence">
                                              <head>Dates based on contextual evidence</head>
                                              <p>Sometimes it might be impossible to give an exact date, but one can make an educated guess based on the content of an item. For example, it cannot have been written before a certain date if it refers to an event that happened on that date.</p>
                                              <table rend="rules">
                                                <row>
                                                  <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi>  2 March 1824</p>
                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi></p>
                                                    <p>Based on contextual information, this undated document, mentioned in Heinrich Simon’s school diary (SIM/1/238), can be dated to 2 March 1824.</p>
                                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<p>Based on contextual information, this undated document, mentioned in Heinrich Simon’s school diary (SIM/1/238), can be dated to <origDate notBefore="1824-03-02" notAfter="1824-03-02" cert="high" evidence="internal">2 March 1824</origDate>.</p>
</origin></egXML></p>
                                                    <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Raffle of schoolbooks by Heinrich Simon:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-SIM-00001-00239/1">SIM/1/239</ref></p></cell>
                                                </row>
                                              </table>
                                              <p>For letters with a missing or partial date, provide an approximate date based on context clues such as events or situations discussed in the letter. In many instances, the exact date can nevertheless be inferred from the contents.</p>
                                              <table rend="rules">
                                                <row>
                                                  <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi>  25- 26 November 1825</p>
                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi></p>
                                                    <p>Contextual information indicates that this letter was written just before the letter <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-SIM-00002-00146/1">SIM/2/146</ref>, dated 1 December 1825, in which Heinrich Simon’s siblings refer to the news about Singer imparted here. As it was written on a Friday and Saturday, the dates of 25 and 26 November 1825 are most probable.</p>
                                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<origin>
<origDate notBefore="1825-11-25" notAfter="1825-11-26" cert="high" evidence="internal">26-25 November 1825</origDate>
<p>Contextual information indicates that this letter was written just before the letter <ref target="https://digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-SIM-00002-00146/1">SIM/2/146</ref>, dated 1 December 1825, in which Heinrich Simon’s siblings refer to the news about Singer imparted here. As it was written on a Friday and Saturday, the dates of 26 and 25 November 1825</origDate> are most probable.</p>
</origin>]]></egXML></p>
                                                    <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Letter from Heinrich Simon to his family:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-SIM-00002-00120/1">SIM/2/120</ref></p></cell>
                                                </row>
                                              </table>
                                            </div>
                                            <div xml:id="non-gregorian-dates-other-calendar-systems">
                                              <head>Non-Gregorian dates | other calendar systems</head>
                                              <p>Origin dates may be expressed using calendars other than Gregorian, most commonly the Islamic Hijrī and Jewish calendars. Where a date is expressed in a non-Gregorian calendar, the original or source date may be retained in the textual content of <gi>origDate</gi> and identified using <att>calendar</att>. If the normalised value is also supplied in that non-Gregorian system, this must be encoded using the custom dating attributes, such as <att>when-custom</att>, <att>from-custom</att>, <att>to-custom</att>, <att>notBefore-custom</att>, <att>notAfter-custom</att>, together with <att>datingMethod</att>.</p>
                                              <p rend="attHead"><code>@x-custom | @datingMethod | @calendar</code></p>
                                              <p><att>when-custom</att> supplies the value of a date or time in some custom standard form.</p>
                                              <p><att>notBefore-custom</att> specifies the earliest possible date for the event in some custom standard form.</p>
                                              <p><att>notAfter-custom</att> specifies the latest possible date for the event in some custom standard form</p>
                                              <p><att>from-custom</att> indicates the starting point of the period in some custom standard form.</p>
                                              <p><att>to-custom</att> indicates the ending point of the period in some custom standard form.</p>
                                              <p><att>datingMethod</att> supplies a pointer to a calendar or other means of interpreting the values of the custom dating attributes.</p>
                                              <p><att>calendar</att> indicates the system or calendar to which the date represented by the content of this element belongs.</p>
                                              <p>Although <att>calendar</att> and <att>datingMethod</att> may refer to the same calendrical system, they serve different purposes. <att>calendar</att> identifies the calendar system used in the displayed date string, while <att>datingMethod</att> identifies the system used for the values recorded in the custom dating attributes.</p>
                                              <p>Custom dating attributes should be combined with standard dating attributes to encode both the non-Gregorian date and its Gregorian equivalent. Standard dating attributes are understood as Gregorian or proleptic Gregorian by default.</p>
                                              <p><att>datingMethod</att> and <att>calendar</att> values must be encoded in lowercase, without accents or spaces, with multi-word values in camelCase.</p>
                                              <p>In the textual content of <gi>origDate</gi>, years should be in Western-style Arabic numerals. The non-Gregorian date should be followed by its Gregorian equivalent in brackets, with CE included.</p>
                                              <p><hi rend="bold">Islamic calendar | Hijri Qamari (AH) | Hijri Shamsi (HS)</hi></p>
                                              <p>The Islamic tradition uses two distinct calendars: the Hijrī Qamarī, a lunar calendar used for religious observances, and the Hijrī Shamsī, a solar calendar used officially in countries like Iran and Afghanistan.</p>
                                              <table rend="rules">
                                                <row>
                                                  <cell><p><val>islamic</val></p></cell>
                                                  <cell><p><val>hijriQamari</val></p></cell>
                                                  <cell><p>Hijrī Qamarī</p></cell>
                                                  <cell><p>AH = Anno Hegirae | lunar calendar</p></cell>
                                                </row>
                                                <row>
                                                  <cell cols="4"><p>The Hijri Qamari calendar is a lunar calendar based on the phases of the Moon. It consists of 12 lunar months, each beginning at the new moon. The calendar year is approximately 354 or 355 days long. It is used across the Islamic world to determine the dates of religious observances, including Ramadan, Eid al-Fitr, and Hajj. The calendar begins with the Hijra (migration of Prophet Muhammad from Mecca to Medina), traditionally dated to 16 July 622 CE. Dates in this calendar are traditionally abbreviated AH (Anno Hegirae, Latin for "in the year of the Hijra").</p></cell>
                                                </row>
                                                <row>
                                                  <cell><p><val>islamic</val></p></cell>
                                                  <cell><p><val>hijriShamsi</val></p></cell>
                                                  <cell><p>Hijrī Shamsī</p></cell>
                                                  <cell><p>SH = Solar Hijrī | solar calendar</p></cell>
                                                </row>
                                                <row>
                                                  <cell cols="4"><p>The Hijri Shamsi calendar is a solar calendar used officially in Iran and Afghanistan. It is aligned with the Earth's revolution around the Sun and starts each year on the March equinox (typically 20 or 21 March in the Gregorian calendar). The year length is 365 or 366 days, and the calendar also traces its epoch to the Hijra (622 CE), though its solar calculation method differs from the lunar version. Dates are commonly abbreviated SH (Solar Hijri), to distinguish them from AH lunar dates.</p></cell>
                                                </row>
                                                <row>
                                                  <cell cols="4"><list rend="bulleted">
                                                      <item><ref target="https://www.muslimphilosophy.com/ip/hijri.htm">Conversion of Islamic (Hijri) AH and Gregorian CE dates</ref></item>
                                                    </list>
                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">Hijrī Qamarī months:</hi> 1- Muḥarram | 2- Ṣafar | 3 - Rabī I | 4 - Rabī II | 5- Jumādā I | 6- Jumādā II | 7- Rajab | 8- Shaʿbān | 9- Ramaḍān | 10- Shawwāl | 11- Ḏū al-Qaʿdah | 12- Ḏū al-Ḥijjah</p>
                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">Hijrī Shamsī months:</hi> 1- Farvardin | 2- Ordibehesht | 3- Khordad | 4- Tir | 5- Mordad | 6- Shahrivar | 7- Mehr | 8- Aban | 9- Azar | 10- Dey | 11- Bahman | 12- Esfand</p></cell>
                                                </row>
                                              </table>
                                              <p>Because year-only Hijrī Qamarī and Hijrī Shamsī dates can overlap two Gregorian years, <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att> should be used to encode the earliest and latest possible Gregorian years associated with the Hijrī year.</p>
                                              <table rend="rules">
                                                <row>
                                                  <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 14 Jumadā I 1085 AH (16 August 1674 CE)</p>
                                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate when="1674-08-16" when-custom="1085-05-14" datingMethod="islamic" calendar="hijriQamari">14 Jumādā I 1085 AH (16 August 1674 CE)</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                                  </row>
                                                  <row>
                                                    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 1085 AH (1674–1675 CE)</p>
                                                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1674" notAfter="1675" when-custom="1085" datingMethod="islamic" calendar="hijriQamari">1085 AH (1674–1675 CE)</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                                    </row>
                                                    <row>
                                                      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi>  1 Farvardin 1353 SH (21 March 1974 CE)</p>
                                                        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate when="1974-03-21" when-custom="1353-01-01" datingMethod="islamic"
calendar="hijriShamsi">1 Farvardin 1353 SH (21 March 1974 CE)</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                                      </row>
                                                      <row>
                                                        <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi>  1353 SH (1974-1975 CE)</p>
                                                          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1974" notAfter="1975" when-custom="1353" datingMethod="islamic"
calendar="hijriShamsi">1353 SH (1974-1975 CE)</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                                        </row>
                                                      </table>
                                                      <p>Where the distinction is known, the more precise values <val>hijriQamari</val> or <val>hijriShamsi</val> must be used. Use <att>calendar</att>=<val>hijri</val> only when the source does not specify whether the date follows the lunar Hijrī Qamarī or the solar Hijrī Shamsī system, and this cannot be determined from contextual evidence. The generic value <val>hijri</val> should be treated as a fallback and not as a preferred encoding choice.</p>
                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">Samaritan calendar | Creation Era (C) | Entry Era (E)</hi></p>
                                                      <p>The Samaritan tradition uses two principal chronological eras for dating: the Creation of the World and the Entry into Canaan, both derived from the biblical narrative.</p>
                                                      <table rend="rules">
                                                        <row>
                                                          <cell><p><val>samaritan</val></p></cell>
                                                          <cell><p><val>creationEra</val></p></cell>
                                                          <cell><p>C = Creation Era | lunisolar</p></cell>
                                                        </row>
                                                        <row>
                                                          <cell cols="3"><p>The Creation Era counts years from the Creation of the World, calculated according to the genealogies and lifespans recorded in the Samaritan Pentateuch. The period from Creation to the Entry into Canaan is fixed at 2794 years. This era served as a principal chronological framework in Samaritan tradition and was used in manuscripts, inscriptions, and historical records. The total length of time from Creation differs from Jewish and Christian chronological traditions.</p></cell>
                                                        </row>
                                                        <row>
                                                          <cell><p><val>samaritan</val></p></cell>
                                                          <cell><p><val>entryEra</val></p></cell>
                                                          <cell><p>E = Entry Era | lunisolar</p></cell>
                                                        </row>
                                                        <row>
                                                          <cell cols="3"><p>The Entry Era counts years from the entry of the Israelites into Canaan under Joshua. The first year of the Entry Era corresponds to the year 2800 of the Creation Era, establishing a defined internal relationship between the two systems. The date of the Entry is consistently transmitted in Samaritan chronicles, though minor variations occur in some manuscript traditions.</p></cell>
                                                        </row>
                                                      </table>
                                                      <p>The Creation Era (C) and the Entry Era (E) are distinct chronological eras within the same Samaritan calendrical framework and not separate calendars in the structural sense. The lunar calendar mechanics remain constant. What changes is the epoch from which years are counted. The Samaritan calendar is lunisolar, so a Samaritan year does not correspond to a single Gregorian year and typically overlaps two consecutive Gregorian years.</p>
                                                      <p>For year-only Samaritan dates, <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att> should be used to encode the earliest and latest possible Gregorian years associated with the Samaritan year.</p>
                                                      <table rend="rules">
                                                        <row>
                                                          <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 5594 C (1934-1935 CE)</p>
                                                            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1934" notAfter="1935" when-custom="5594" datingMethod="samaritan" calendar="creationEra">5594 C (1934-1935 CE)</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                                          </row>
                                                          <row>
                                                            <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi>  3574 E (1935 CE)</p>
                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1934" notAfter="1935" when-custom="3574" datingMethod="samaritan" calendar="entryEra">3574 E (1934-1935 CE)</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                                            </row>
                                                          </table>
                                                          <p>Where the distinction is known, the more precise values <val>creationEra</val> or <val>entryEra</val> must be used. Use <att>calendar</att>=<val>samaritan</val> only when the source does not specify whether the date follows the Samaritan Creation Era (C) or the Entry Era (E), and this cannot be determined from contextual evidence. The generic value <val>samaritan</val> should be treated as a fallback and not as a preferred encoding choice.</p>
                                                          <p><hi rend="bold">Jewish calendar | Anno Mundi (AM)</hi></p>
                                                          <p>The Jewish calendar is a lunisolar system in which lunar months are aligned with the solar year through intercalation. Years are counted from the Creation of the World according to rabbinic chronology.</p>
                                                          <table rend="rules">
                                                            <row>
                                                              <cell><p><val>jewish</val></p></cell>
                                                              <cell><p><val>annoMundi</val></p></cell>
                                                              <cell><p>AM = Anno Mundi | lunisolar</p></cell>
                                                            </row>
                                                            <row>
                                                              <cell cols="3"><p>The Jewish calendar is a lunisolar system in which lunar months are aligned with the solar year through a 19-year intercalation cycle. Years are counted according to the Anno Mundi era, from the Creation of the World, traditionally dated to 3761 BCE in the proleptic Gregorian calendar. The calendar regulates the observance of religious festivals and became the dominant chronological system in Jewish communities from the medieval period onward.</p></cell>
                                                            </row>
                                                            <row>
                                                              <cell cols="3"><list rend="bulleted">
                                                                  <item><ref target="https://www.torahcalc.com/tools/date-converter">Conversion of Jewish (Hebrew) AM and Gregorian CE dates</ref></item>
                                                                </list>
                                                                <p><hi rend="bold">Jewish calendar months:</hi> 1- Tishrei | 2- Cheshvan | 3- Kislev | 4 - Tevet | 5- Shevat | 6- Adar (Adar I in leap years) | 7- Nisan | 8- Iyar | 9- Sivan | 10- Tammuz | 11- Av | 12- Elul — Leap years: Adar I and Adar II.</p></cell>
                                                            </row>
                                                          </table>
                                                          <p>The year may take two forms: with the thousands explicitly, referred to as the major era, such as 5428, or without the thousands, referred to as the minor era, such as 428, with the thousands understood from context. This distinction reflects a difference in notation only and does not indicate a different era or calendar system. When encoding, record the full numeric year in <att>when-custom</att>, even if the thousands are omitted in the source, and retain the form exactly as it appears within <gi>origDate</gi>.</p>
                                                          <table rend="rules">
                                                            <row>
                                                              <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 14 Nisan 5695 AM (17 April 1935 CE)</p>
                                                                <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate when="1935-04-17" when-custom="5695-07-14" datingMethod="jewish" calendar="annoMundi">14 Nisan 5695 AM (17 April 1935 CE)</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                                              </row>
                                                            </table>
                                                            <p>When a source records only a Jewish year in Anno Mundi (AM), the year must be treated as spanning two Gregorian years. Because the Jewish year begins in Tishrei (September or October), each AM year spans two consecutive Gregorian years and does not correspond to a single Gregorian year.</p>
                                                            <p>For year-only Jewish dates, <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att> should be used to encode the earliest and latest possible Gregorian years associated with the Jewish year.</p>
                                                            <table rend="rules">
                                                              <row>
                                                                <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi>  5428 AM (1667–1668 CE)</p>
                                                                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="1667" notAfter="1668" when-custom="5428" datingMethod="jewish" calendar="annoMundi">5428 AM (1667–1668 CE)</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                </row>
                                                              </table>
                                                              <p>In this example, 5428 AM began at Rosh Hashanah in autumn 1667 and ended at Rosh Hashanah in autumn 1668. The use of <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att> records the Gregorian year limits without introducing false precision. <att>when-custom</att> preserves the original Anno Mundi year value, while <att>datingMethod</att>=<val>jewish</val> and <att>calendar</att>=<val>annoMundi</val> identify the calendrical system and era.</p>
                                                              <p><hi rend="bold">Seleucid Era (SE) | Babylonian | Macedonian</hi></p>
                                                              <p>The Seleucid Era (SE), also known as Anno Graecorum (AG), is a system of year numbering that begins with the re-conquest of Babylon by Seleucus I Nicator in 312/311 BCE, marking the foundation of the Seleucid Empire. It was applied within existing lunisolar calendrical frameworks derived from the Babylonian calendar. Two principal systems were employed: a Babylonian system and a Macedonian system. The era remained in use well beyond the Seleucid Empire itself, continuing in Jewish, Syriac, and Christian traditions into the medieval period and, in some communities, even later.</p>
                                                              <table rend="rules">
                                                                <row>
                                                                  <cell><p><val>seleucid</val></p></cell>
                                                                  <cell><p><val>seleucidBabylonian</val></p></cell>
                                                                  <cell><p>Babylonian system</p></cell>
                                                                  <cell><p>SE = Seleucid Era | lunisolar | spring</p></cell>
                                                                </row>
                                                                <row>
                                                                  <cell cols="4"><p>In the Babylonian system, year 1 began on 1 Nisanu (3 April 311 BCE). Each Seleucid year ran approximately from spring in one Gregorian year to spring in the next. This system was used in Babylon and Coele-Syria and was adopted by Jewish communities. Because the year began in spring, its correspondence with the Gregorian calendar differs by one year from the Macedonian system for part of each year.</p></cell>
                                                                </row>
                                                                <row>
                                                                  <cell><p><val>seleucid</val></p></cell>
                                                                  <cell><p><val>seleucidMacedonian</val></p></cell>
                                                                  <cell><p>Macedonian system</p></cell>
                                                                  <cell><p>SE = Seleucid Era | lunisolar | autumn</p></cell>
                                                                </row>
                                                                <row>
                                                                  <cell cols="4"><p>In the Macedonian system, year 1 began in autumn 312 BCE. The Macedonian court adopted the Babylonian lunisolar calendar structure but reckoned the New Year in autumn. Each Seleucid year therefore ran approximately from autumn in one Gregorian year to autumn in the next. Later West Syrian Christian usage standardised the year as running from 1 October to 30 September.</p></cell>
                                                                </row>
                                                                <row>
                                                                  <cell cols="4"><list rend="bulleted">
                                                                      <item>Conversion of Seleucid Era (SE) and Gregorian BCE | CE dates</item>
                                                                    </list>
                                                                    <p>If the Seleucid year (x) is less than 312, the corresponding BCE interval runs from autumn 313 − x to autumn 312 − x (Macedonian system) or from spring 312 − x to spring 311 − x (Babylonian system).</p>
                                                                    <p>If the Seleucid year (x) is greater than 312, the corresponding CE interval runs from autumn x − 312 to autumn x − 311 (Macedonian system) or from spring x − 311 to spring x − 310 (Babylonian system).</p>
                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">Babylonian months:</hi> 1- Nisanu | 2- Ayyaru | 3- Simanu | 4 - Duʾuzu | 5- Abu | 6- Ululu | 7- Tashritu | 8- Arahsamnu | 9- Kislimu | 10- Tebetu | 11- Shabatu | 12- Addaru — Leap years add a second Ululu or Addaru.</p>
                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">Macedonian months:</hi> 1- Dios | 2- Apellaios | 3- Audnaios | 4 - Peritios | 5- Dystros | 6- Xandikos | 7- Artemisios | 8- Daisios | 9- Panemos | 10- Loios | 11- Gorpiaios | 12- Hyperberetaios</p></cell>
                                                                </row>
                                                              </table>
                                                              <p>Because Seleucid years begin either in spring or in autumn, each SE year overlaps two Gregorian years and does not correspond to a single Gregorian year.</p>
                                                              <p>For year-only Seleucid dates, <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att> should be used to encode the earliest and latest possible Gregorian years associated with the Seleucid year.</p>
                                                              <table rend="rules">
                                                                <row>
                                                                  <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 670 SE (359–360 CE)</p>
                                                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="0359" notAfter="0360" when-custom="670" datingMethod="seleucid" calendar="seleucidBabylonian">670 SE (359–360 CE)</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                  </row>
                                                                  <row>
                                                                    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 15 Nisanu 670 SE (17 April 359 CE)</p>
                                                                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate when="0359-04-17" when-custom="670-01-15" datingMethod="seleucid" calendar="seleucidBabylonian">15 Nisanu 670 SE (17 April 359 CE)</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                    </row>
                                                                    <row>
                                                                      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 670 SE (358–359 CE)</p>
                                                                        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate notBefore="0358" notAfter="0359" when-custom="670" datingMethod="seleucid" calendar="seleucidMacedonian">670 SE (358–359 CE)</origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                      </row>
                                                                      <row>
                                                                        <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 15 Dios 670 SE (15 October 358 CE)</p>
                                                                          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origDate when="0358-10-15" when-custom="670-01-15" datingMethod="seleucid" calendar="seleucidMacedonian">15 Dios 670 SE (15 October 358 CE) </origDate></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                        </row>
                                                                      </table>
                                                                      <p>Where the distinction is known, the more precise values <val>seleucidBabylonian</val> or <val>seleucidMacedonian</val> must be used. Use <att>calendar</att>=<val>seleucidEra</val> only when the source does not specify whether the date follows the Babylonian or Macedonian system, and this cannot be determined from contextual evidence. The generic value <val>seleucidEra</val> should be treated as a fallback and not as a preferred encoding choice.</p>
                                                                      <p>Gregorian calendar dates recorded in the standard dating attributes must follow ISO 8601 formatting. The custom dating attributes are defined for non-ISO calendar systems and store the date value in that system’s own numbering. ISO 8601 formatting rules do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> apply to these attributes unless the original source itself presents the date in an ISO-compatible form. Where a source does not record a non-Gregorian date, or where only a normalised Gregorian equivalent is required, it is acceptable to supply the Gregorian date alone using the standard attributes without employing the custom dating attributes.</p>
                                                                    </div>
                                                                  </div>
                                                                  <div xml:id="origPlace">
                                                                    <head><code>&lt;origPlace&gt;</code> | origin Place</head>
                                                                    <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-origPlace.html"><gi>origPlace</gi></ref>  <hi rend="italic">(origin place) contains any form of place name, used to identify the place of origin for a manuscript, manuscript part, or other object.</hi></p>
                                                                    <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Origin Place</hi></p>
                                                                    <p><gi>origPlace</gi> within <gi>origin</gi> is used to record the place associated with the production or creation of the item.</p>
                                                                    <p>Although TEI supports many different approaches to place encoding, the place of origin is typically recorded within <gi>origPlace</gi> using <gi>country</gi>, and, where appropriate, <gi>settlement</gi>, or <gi>region</gi>.</p>
                                                                    <div xml:id="country-settlement-region">
                                                                      <head><code>&lt;country&gt;</code> | <code>&lt;settlement&gt;</code> | <code>&lt;region&gt;</code></head>
                                                                      <p><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-country.html"><gi>country</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(country) contains the name of a geo-political unit, such as a nation, country, colony, or commonwealth, larger than or administratively superior to a region and smaller than a bloc.</hi></p>
                                                                      <p><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-settlement.html"><gi>settlement</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(settlement) contains the name of a settlement such as a city, town, or village identified as a single geo-political or administrative unit.</hi></p>
                                                                      <p><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-region.html"><gi>region</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(region) contains the name of an administrative unit such as a state, province, or county, larger than a settlement, but smaller than a country.</hi></p>
                                                                      <p>When applicable, these elements must include <att>source</att> and <att>key</att>.</p>
                                                                      <p rend="attHead"><code>@source | @key</code></p>
                                                                      <p><att>source</att> specifies the authority or source from which the identifier is derived.</p>
                                                                      <p><att>key</att> a persistent, unique identifier for the named entity, provided by that source.</p>
                                                                      <p><att>source</att> and <att>key</att> should together provide a unique identifier drawn from a controlled vocabulary or classification system. The Getty Thesaurus of Geographic Names is the preferred source.</p>
                                                                      <table rend="rules">
                                                                        <row>
                                                                          <cell><p><val>tgn</val></p></cell>
                                                                          <cell><p>Getty Thesaurus of Geographic Names (TGN)</p></cell>
                                                                        </row>
                                                                        <row>
                                                                          <cell cols="2"><p>The <ref target="https://www.getty.edu/research/tools/vocabularies/tgn/index.html">Getty Thesaurus of Geographic Names (TGN)</ref> is a structured vocabulary, containing names, descriptions, and other metadata for extant and historical cities, empires, archaeological sites, and physical features.</p>
                                                                            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><taxonomy xml:id="tgn">
<bibl><ref target="https://www.getty.edu/research/tools/vocabularies/tgn/index.html">Getty Thesaurus of Geographic Names (TGN)</ref></bibl>
</taxonomy></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                          </row>
                                                                        </table>
                                                                        <p>When the value <code>#tgn</code> is used for <att>source</att>, it indicates that the identifier recorded in <att>key</att> is drawn from this authority file. The prefix <code>#</code> indicates a reference to an identifier defined elsewhere in the same file. In this case, it refers to the <gi>taxonomy</gi> declared in the header with <att>xml:id</att>=<val>tgn</val>. This value can be selected from a controlled dropdown list when entering the attribute and does not need to be typed manually.</p>
                                                                        <p>Place names are encoded using the preferred form from the Getty Thesaurus of Geographic Names (TGN). <att>key</att> must include the unique numeric ID for the place from TGN.</p>
                                                                        <table rend="rules">
                                                                          <row>
                                                                            <cell><p>Italy</p>
                                                                              <p>TGN ID: 1000080 | <code>source="#tgn" key="1000080"</code></p>
                                                                              <p>Permalink: <ref target="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/1000080">http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/1000080</ref></p>
                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="1000080">Italy</country></origPlace></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                            </row>
                                                                          </table>
                                                                          <p>The preferred format for the textual value is to record the country first, followed by a comma and space, and then the name of the city, town, or region.</p>
                                                                        </div>
                                                                        <div xml:id="city-town-village">
                                                                          <head>City, town, village</head>
                                                                          <table rend="rules">
                                                                            <row>
                                                                              <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Italy, Florence</p>
                                                                                <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="1000080">Italy</country>, <settlement source="#tgn" key="7000457">Florence</settlement></origPlace></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                              </row>
                                                                            </table>
                                                                            <p><hi rend="bold">Region</hi></p>
                                                                            <table rend="rules">
                                                                              <row>
                                                                                <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Italy, Tuscany</p>
                                                                                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="1000080">Italy</country>, <region source="#tgn" key="7009760">Tuscany</region></origPlace></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                </row>
                                                                              </table>
                                                                              <p>Examples of administrative units that are larger than a settlement but smaller than a country:</p>
                                                                              <p>Autonomous Community — Spain | Catalonia, Andalusia, Galicia</p>
                                                                              <p>County — England | Greater Manchester, Cambridgeshire, Oxfordshire, Kent, Surrey</p>
                                                                              <p>Prefecture — Japan | Tokyo, Osaka, Kyoto</p>
                                                                              <p>Province — Canada | Ontario, Quebec, British Columbia</p>
                                                                              <p>State — Germany | Bavaria, Saxony, Hesse</p>
                                                                              <p>Region — France | Île-de-France, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, Brittany</p>
                                                                              <p>Region — Italy | Tuscany, Lombardy, Sicily</p>
                                                                              <p>State — Australia | New South Wales, Victoria, Queensland</p>
                                                                              <p>State — United States | California, Texas, Florida</p>
                                                                              <table rend="rules">
                                                                                <row>
                                                                                  <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Spain, Catalonia</p>
                                                                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="1000095">Spain</country>, <region source="#tgn" key="7030216">Catalonia</region></origPlace></egXML></p>
                                                                                    <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">The Rylands Sephardi Haggadah:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-HEBREW-00006/1">Hebrew MS 6</ref></p></cell>
                                                                                </row>
                                                                              </table>
                                                                              <p><hi rend="bold">General region | cardinal points</hi></p>
                                                                              <table rend="rules">
                                                                                <row>
                                                                                  <cell><p rend="right">Central | North | South | East | West | Northeast | Northwest | Southeast | Southwest</p>
                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Italy, Central</p>
                                                                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="1000080">Italy</country><region source="#tgn" key="4005361">Central</region></origPlace></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                  </row>
                                                                                </table>
                                                                                <p><hi rend="bold">Country</hi></p>
                                                                                <table rend="rules">
                                                                                  <row>
                                                                                    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Italy</p>
                                                                                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="1000080">Italy</country></origPlace></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                    </row>
                                                                                  </table>
                                                                                  <p><hi rend="bold">Continent</hi></p>
                                                                                  <table rend="rules">
                                                                                    <row>
                                                                                      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Europe</p>
                                                                                        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origPlace><region source="#tgn" key="1000003">Europe</region></origPlace></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                      </row>
                                                                                    </table>
                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">Sub-continent</hi></p>
                                                                                    <table rend="rules">
                                                                                      <row>
                                                                                        <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Europe, Northern</p>
                                                                                          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origPlace><region source="#tgn" key="4003757">Europe, Northern</region></origPlace></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                        </row>
                                                                                      </table>
                                                                                      <p>The level of specificity applied when recording <gi>origPlace</gi> information depends on the details available. Where only broad geographical information is known, record the most specific level available, such as a continent or region. Where more detailed information is available, record the country and, where appropriate, the settlement or region.</p>
                                                                                      <p>If the country is unknown but a broader geographical area is known, record the most specific level available, such as a continent or broad region. For example, if the country is unknown but the continent or region is known, such as Africa, Europe, North Africa, or Central Europe, record that information.</p>
                                                                                      <p>For content concerning the entire United Kingdom rather than its individual countries, England, Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland, use the nation name: United Kingdom.</p>
                                                                                      <p>Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> record political or intergovernmental organisations, such as the European Union or United Nations, as places of origin. Instead, record the relevant member country or countries, based on the content and time of production.</p>
                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">Temporal | cultural places</hi></p>
                                                                                      <p>Temporal and cultural place names refer to forms of place names that are specific to a particular historical period, cultural context, language, community, or source tradition. These forms may include ancient names, historic names, colonial names, Indigenous names, or modern established names.</p>
                                                                                      <p>When recording temporal or cultural place names, use the form of the place name appropriate to the item’s context. Where the place name or boundary has changed, include the modern established or equivalent form as well, and record both the historic and current geographical context where relevant.</p>
                                                                                      <p>Maintain a hierarchical structure within <gi>origPlace</gi> using <gi>country</gi> and, where appropriate, <gi>settlement</gi> or <gi>region</gi>. Where both a context-specific form and a modern or equivalent form are recorded, encode them as two separate <gi>placeName</gi> within the relevant place element, and use <att>type</att> to distinguish the form of name being recorded.</p>
                                                                                      <p rend="attHead"><code>@type</code></p>
                                                                                      <p><att>type</att> classifies the form of place name being recorded, according to its temporal or cultural context.</p>
                                                                                      <p>The following values should be used:</p>
                                                                                      <p><val>ancient</val> used for place names that originate from ancient times, typically referring to places known from classical antiquity or prehistoric times. For instance, Babylon is the name for the ancient city located in present-day Bābil.</p>
                                                                                      <p><val>historic</val> indicates that the place name is of historical significance. It may refer to a name used in historical contexts, historical records, or literature. For instance, Constantinople is the historic name for what is now Istanbul.</p>
                                                                                      <p><val>modern</val> provided there is an equivalent modern place name, denotes that the place name is currently in use in the present day.  It refers to the contemporary name of a place.</p>
                                                                                      <p>The preferred format for the textual value is to record the country first, followed by a comma and space, then the ancient, historic, colonial, Indigenous, or otherwise context-specific name, with the modern or equivalent name in brackets where relevant.</p>
                                                                                      <p>Additional equivalents that are neither modern forms nor names relevant to the item’s historical, cultural, or source context should <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> be included as part of the item’s geographic information.</p>
                                                                                      <table rend="rules">
                                                                                        <row>
                                                                                          <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Egypt<hi rend="bold">,</hi> Hermopolis (Al Ashmūnayn)</p>
                                                                                            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="7016833">Egypt</country>, <settlement><placeName type="ancient" source="#tgn" key="7534548">Hermopolis</placeName> (<placeName type="modern" source="#tgn" key="7001218">Al Ashmūnayn</placeName>)</settlement>
</origPlace></egXML></p>
                                                                                            <list rend="bulleted">
                                                                                              <item><hi rend="italic">TGN preferred name</hi> | <hi rend="italic">Al Ashmūnayn, without a hyphen.</hi></item>
                                                                                            </list></cell>
                                                                                        </row>
                                                                                      </table>
                                                                                      <p>Where TGN provides a single place identifier for either the modern settlement or the ancient or historic place, but not separate identifiers for both, place <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> on <gi>settlement</gi> and encode the ancient or historic and modern names as separate <gi>placeName</gi> within it.</p>
                                                                                      <table rend="rules">
                                                                                        <row>
                                                                                          <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Egypt, Oxyrhynchus (Al Bahnasā)</p>
                                                                                            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="7001267">Egypt</country>, <settlement source="#tgn" key="7001267"><placeName type="ancient">Oxyrhynchus</placeName> (<placeName type="modern">Al Bahnasā</placeName>)<settlement>
</origPlace>]]></egXML></p>
                                                                                            <list rend="bulleted">
                                                                                              <item><hi rend="italic">TGN preferred name</hi> | <hi rend="italic">Al Bahnasā, without a hyphen.</hi></item>
                                                                                            </list></cell>
                                                                                        </row>
                                                                                      </table>
                                                                                      <p>When the place of creation differs from the place of discovery, use <gi>origPlace</gi> to record the place of creation and <gi>provenance</gi> to record the place of discovery. These should be kept separate, even where the locations are geographically close. (&lt;!-- Section XX – Hyperlink).</p>
                                                                                      <p>The same approach may be used for historic country or regional names with modern equivalents, where both forms are relevant to the item’s context. In such cases, encode the historic and modern names within the relevant place element.</p>
                                                                                      <table rend="rules">
                                                                                        <row>
                                                                                          <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Persia (Iran)</p>
                                                                                            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<origPlace><country><placeName type="historic" source="#tgn" key="7024079">Persia</placeName> (<placeName type="modern" source="#tgn" key="7000231">Iran</placeName>)<country>
</origPlace>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                          </row>
                                                                                          <row>
                                                                                            <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Siam (Thailand)</p>
                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="1000142"><placeName type="historic">Siam</placeName> (<placeName type="modern">Thailand</placeName>)<country>
</origPlace>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                            </row>
                                                                                          </table>
                                                                                          <p rend="right">Case example | The Heinrich Simon Papers</p>
                                                                                          <p><ref target="https://digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/collections/simonpapers">The Heinrich Simon Papers</ref> consist principally of letters, most of them exchanged within the Simon family, diaries and other documents relating to the various stages of Heinrich Simon’s life. These materials were created in locations that are now part of modern-day Germany and Poland, but were within the historical Kingdom of Prussia.</p>
                                                                                          <p>The Kingdom of Prussia was a major German state that existed from 1701 to 1918. It played a crucial role in European history, particularly in the unification of Germany in the nineteenth century. Prussian territories included parts of modern-day Germany, Poland, Russia, Lithuania, Denmark, Belgium, and the Czech Republic.</p>
                                                                                          <p>The distinction between historical German place names and modern official Polish names is significant because many places in the collection have undergone changes in sovereignty, borders, and official naming. This approach preserves historical context while respecting historical naming practices and aligning with contemporary naming conventions, ensuring that the information remains accessible and meaningful to users today.</p>
                                                                                          <p>In the following example, Breslau is used as the historical German name found on the item, with Wrocław recorded in brackets as the modern Polish name. <att>xml:lang</att> is used on each <gi>placeName</gi> to specify the language of that form of the place name, distinguishing the German and Polish forms.</p>
                                                                                          <table rend="rules">
                                                                                            <row>
                                                                                              <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Poland, Breslau (Wrocław)</p>
                                                                                                <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="7006366">Poland</country>, <settlement source="#tgn" key="7007601"><placeName type="historic" xml:lang="ger">Breslau</placeName> (<placeName type="modern" xml:lang="pol">Wrocław</placeName>)</settlement></origPlace>
</origin></egXML></p>
                                                                                                <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Letter from Herrmann Simon to his brother Heinrich Simon the Elder:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/EX-CADBURY-SIMON-HS-C-00013/1">HS/C/13</ref></p></cell>
                                                                                            </row>
                                                                                          </table>
                                                                                          <p rend="right">Case example | decolonising the Arctic: Manchester Geographical Society Lantern Slides Collection</p>
                                                                                          <p>The Manchester Geographical Society Lantern Slides Collection offers insight into how geography, exploration, and empire were visually represented and taught in late nineteenth- and early twentieth-century Britain. While the collection has educational and scientific value, it also reflects the colonial attitudes that shaped geographic knowledge at the time. Modern preservation and digitisation make the collection available as a resource for studying the history of geography, visual culture, and imperialism.</p>
                                                                                          <p>Decolonising the Arctic involves recognising Indigenous rights, knowledge, sovereignty, and connections to land. In descriptive metadata, this means moving beyond colonial naming conventions alone and recording Indigenous place names where they are relevant to the item and its historical context, so that the description more accurately reflects Indigenous relationships to place.</p>
                                                                                          <p>Recording both the English colonial name and the Indigenous Inuktitut name acknowledges the historical context of the item while supporting more inclusive and culturally sensitive description. This approach preserves historical context while respecting Indigenous naming practices and aligning with contemporary naming conventions, ensuring that the information remains accessible and meaningful to users today.</p>
                                                                                          <p>In the following example, Pond Inlet is used as the English historic or colonial name, with Mittimatalik recorded in brackets as the Indigenous Inuktitut name for the settlement in Nunavut, Canada. <att>xml:lang</att> is used on each <gi>placeName</gi> to specify the language and script of that form of the place name, distinguishing the English and romanised Inuktitut forms.</p>
                                                                                          <table rend="rules">
                                                                                            <row>
                                                                                              <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Canada, Pond Inlet (Mittimatalik)</p>
                                                                                                <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="7005685">Canada</country>, <settlement source="#tgn" key="1014385"><placeName type="historic" xml:lang="eng">Pond Inlet</placeName> (<placeName type="modern" xml:lang="iku-latn-x-lc">Mittimatalik</placeName>)</settlement></origPlace>
</origin></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                              </row>
                                                                                            </table>
                                                                                            <p><val>iku-latn-x-lc</val> specifies that <hi rend="italic">Mittimatalik</hi> is the romanised form of the Inuktitut name <hi rend="italic">ᒥᑦᑎᒪᑕᓕᒃ,</hi> according to the ALA-LC Romanisation standard.</p>
                                                                                            <p><code>iku</code> is the ISO 639-3 language code for Inuktitut.</p>
                                                                                            <p><code>latn</code> is the ISO 15924 script code for the Latin alphabet. Normally, Inuktitut is written in the Inuktitut script, but here, it specifies that the content is in Inuktitut but written using the Latin alphabet (romanisation).</p>
                                                                                            <p><code>x-lc</code> is a custom extension sub-tag indicating adherence to the ALA-LC Romanisation standard.</p>
                                                                                            <p>The <ref target="https://www.loc.gov/catdir/cpso/roman.html">ALA-LC Romanisation Tables</ref> are widely used in library cataloguing and bibliographic metadata for converting non-Latin scripts into Latin script.</p>
                                                                                          </div>
                                                                                          <div xml:id="various-multiple-places-of-origin">
                                                                                            <head>Various | multiple places of origin</head>
                                                                                            <p>If an item was produced in more than one place, such as a travel diary, scrapbook, or composite volume, use judgement to determine the most appropriate level of place description. This may be the widest shared geographical area, or some or all of the individual places of production, where these are significant to the item’s creation or interpretation.</p>
                                                                                            <table rend="rules">
                                                                                              <row>
                                                                                                <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Germany — Berlin, Hirschberg; Poland — Breslau (Wrocław), Brieg (Brzeg), Schmiedeberg im Riesengebirge (Kowary)</p>
                                                                                                  <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi></p>
                                                                                                  <p>Individual items within the volume were created during the years 1816–1824, in various parts of present-day Germany and Poland, in the Kingdom of Prussia (1701-1918):</p>
                                                                                                  <p>Germany — Berlin, Hirschberg
                                                                                                    Poland — Breslau (Wrocław), Brieg (Brzeg), Schmiedeberg im Riesengebirge (Kowary)</p>
                                                                                                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<p>Individual items within the volume were created during the years ..., in various parts of present-day Germany and Poland, in the Kingdom of Prussia (<date from="1701" to="1918">1701-1918 </date>):</p>
<list>
<item>
<origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="7000084">Germany</country> — <settlement source="#tgn" key="7003712">Berlin</settlement>, <settlement source="#tgn" key="7171504">Hirschberg</settlement>
</origPlace>
</item>
<item>
<origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="7006366">Poland</country> — <settlement source="#tgn" key="7007601"><placeName type="historic" xml:lang="ger">Breslau</placeName> (<placeName type="modern" xml:lang="pol">Wrocław</placeName>)</settlement>, <settlement source="#tgn" key="7007623"><placeName type="historic" xml:lang="ger">Brieg</placeName> (<placeName type="modern" xml:lang="pol">Brzeg </placeName>)</settlement>, <settlement>Schmiedeberg im Riesengebirge (Kowary)</settlement>.
</origPlace>
</item>
</list>
</origin></egXML></p>
                                                                                                  <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Papers of Heinrich Simon: The Pupil:</hi>  <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-SIM-00001/1">SIM/1</ref></p>
                                                                                                  <list rend="bulleted">
                                                                                                    <item><hi rend="italic">em dash (—) may be used to separate the country from the associated settlements where this improves clarity.</hi></item>
                                                                                                  </list></cell>
                                                                                              </row>
                                                                                            </table>
                                                                                            <p><hi rend="bold">Conjectural | supplied places of origin</hi></p>
                                                                                            <p>Conjectural places are hypothesised locations based on incomplete or indirect evidence, such as historical references, internal evidence in the item, external documentation, or geographical analysis, but lacking definitive proof. Where the place of origin or creation cannot be determined, an estimated, probable, or supplied place may be recorded, provided that its uncertain status is encoded explicitly using <att>cert</att> and, where appropriate, <att>evidence</att>.</p>
                                                                                            <p><hi rend="bold">@cert</hi></p>
                                                                                            <p><att>cert</att> (certainty) signifies the degree of certainty associated with the localisation</p>
                                                                                            <p>The following values should be used:</p>
                                                                                            <p><val>high</val> the localisation is generally considered to be correct.</p>
                                                                                            <p>Inferred | a place name is known but not explicitly stated on the item, it is inferred. In other catalogues or finding aids, such names may be recorded in square brackets, for example, [Florence].</p>
                                                                                            <p><val>medium</val> the localisation is generally considered approximately correct.</p>
                                                                                            <p>Approximate | a place name that is probable, most likely correct but might be doubtful. In other catalogues or finding aids, such names might be recorded with a question mark, for example, Florence? or ?Florence.</p>
                                                                                            <p><val>low</val> the localisation is generally considered uncertain but possible.</p>
                                                                                            <p>Questionable | a place name that is possible but might be questionable, uncertain, or incorrect; tentative identification.</p>
                                                                                            <p><val>unknown</val> no wish to assert an opinion, as the level of certainty is unknown.</p>
                                                                                            <p><hi rend="bold">@evidence</hi></p>
                                                                                            <p><att>evidence</att> indicates the nature of the evidence supporting the localisation</p>
                                                                                            <p>The following values should be used:</p>
                                                                                            <p><val>internal</val> the localisation is based on evidence internal to the item, for example, an inscription, a script.</p>
                                                                                            <p><val>external</val> the localisation is based on evidence external to the item, for example, a reference to the item in another context.</p>
                                                                                            <p><val>conjecture</val> the localisation is based on conjecture. No specific evidence is available to support the localisation. The place name has been inferred by the encoder, cataloguer, or scholar based on contextual knowledge or expertise.</p>
                                                                                            <p>In the following example, Florence is recorded as a probable place of origin. <att>cert</att>=<val>medium</val> indicates that the localisation is probable but not definitive. The supporting evidence is described in prose within <gi>origin</gi>.</p>
                                                                                            <table rend="rules">
                                                                                              <row>
                                                                                                <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Italy, Florence</p>
                                                                                                  <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi></p>
                                                                                                  <p>Circumstantial evidence suggests that this manuscript may have been created in Tuscany, possibly in Florence. The use of the word 'huopo' instead of 'uo' suggests Florentine dialect, while the inclusion of the 'Visione contemplativa di San Bernardo', originally published in Tuscany in 1397, may hint at a geographical link. St Bernardo appears in Paradiso, acting as Dante's final guide (cantos 31 to 33).</p>
                                                                                                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="1000080">Italy</country>, <settlement source="#tgn" key="7000457" cert="medium" evidence="internal">Florence</settlement></origPlace>
<p>Circumstantial evidence suggests that this manuscript may have been created in Tuscany, possibly in Florence. The use of the word 'huopo' instead of 'uo' suggests Florentine dialect, while the inclusion of the 'Visione contemplativa di San Bernardo', originally published in Tuscany in 1397, may hint at a geographical link. St Bernardo appears in Paradiso, acting as Dante's final guide (cantos 31 to 33).</p>
</origin></egXML></p>
                                                                                                  <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">La Commedia:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-ITALIAN-00002/1">Italian MS 2</ref></p></cell>
                                                                                              </row>
                                                                                            </table>
                                                                                            <p><att>cert</att> and <att>evidence</att> do not have to be used together.</p>
                                                                                            <p>The use of <att>cert</att> and <att>evidence</att> provide a clear spatial context for uncertain or probable places (supplied or conjectural), especially when the exact place of origin is unknown.</p>
                                                                                            <p>If no place of origin can be found in the item itself or determined from another source, but a place can be estimated, record the most precise probable location that the evidence supports. The basis for the supplied or conjectural place should be explained in a <gi>p</gi> within <gi>origin</gi>, including the source of the information and how the localisation was determined. Maintain consistency in the language used to express uncertainty:</p>
                                                                                            <p><hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">probably</hi></hi> — highly likely to be the case than not (&gt;50% chance) — <att>cert</att>=<val>high</val></p>
                                                                                            <p><hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">possibly</hi></hi> — could be the case or be true but not certain (&lt;50% chance) — <att>cert</att>=<val>medium</val> | <val>low</val></p>
                                                                                            <p>Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> use square brackets ([ ]) | question marks (?) or any other markup normally used in MARC | RDA, or other cataloguing standards to indicate uncertainty, supplied or conjectural places, missing or incorrect information. In TEI, uncertainty should be encoded explicitly using the appropriate attributes and explained in prose where necessary.</p>
                                                                                          </div>
                                                                                          <div xml:id="uncertain-place-one-place-or-another">
                                                                                            <head>Uncertain place | one place or another</head>
                                                                                            <p>The place of origin is known to be one of two possible places.</p>
                                                                                            <p>The following encoding approach may be used where the available evidence does not allow one place to be confirmed, particularly when distinguishing between multiple settlements within a single country.</p>
                                                                                            <p>Where the possible places are settlements within the same country, the shared country may be recorded once, followed by each possible settlement. Where the possible places are countries, regions, or other places at the same geographical level, each possible place should be encoded separately within the explanatory prose. In all cases, the prose should make clear that the place of origin is uncertain.</p>
                                                                                            <table rend="rules">
                                                                                              <row>
                                                                                                <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Italy, Padua; Venice</p>
                                                                                                  <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi></p>
                                                                                                  <p>Stylistic evidence suggests that it was created in Italy, possibly in Padua or Venice.</p>
                                                                                                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<origPlace>
<country source="#tgn" key="1000080">Italy</country>, <settlement source="#tgn" key="7003085" cert="low" evidence="internal">Padua</settlement>; <settlement source="#tgn" key="7018159" cert="low" evidence="internal">Venice</settlement>
</origPlace>
<p>Stylistic evidence suggests that it was created in Italy, possibly in Padua or Venice.</p>
</origin></egXML></p>
                                                                                                  <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Johannes Cassianus:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-LATIN-00049/1">Latin MS 49</ref></p></cell>
                                                                                              </row>
                                                                                              <row>
                                                                                                <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Greater Iran; Indian subcontinent</p>
                                                                                                  <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi></p>
                                                                                                  <p>Possibly completed in either Greater Iran or the Indian subcontinent.</p>
                                                                                                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<origin>
<p>Possibly completed in either <origPlace><region source="#tgn" key="7000235" cert="medium" >Greater Iran</region></origPlace> or <origPlace><region source="#tgn" key="7000208" cert="medium">Indian subcontinent</region></origPlace>.</p>
<origin>]]></egXML></p>
                                                                                                  <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Nafāʾis al-Funūn fī ʻArāʾis al-ʻUyūn:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-PERSIAN-00147/1">Persian MS 147</ref></p></cell>
                                                                                              </row>
                                                                                              <row>
                                                                                                <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Italy; France</p>
                                                                                                  <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi></p>
                                                                                                  <p>Possibly completed in either Italy or France.</p>
                                                                                                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<p>Possibly completed in either <origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="1000080" cert="medium">Italy</country></origPlace> or <origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="1000070" cert="medium">France</country></origPlace>.</p>
</origin></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                </row>
                                                                                              </table>
                                                                                              <p>Place information should not be recorded as plain text within <gi>origPlace</gi> where a structured place element can be used. Encode countries, regions, settlements, and place names using the appropriate TEI elements, such as <gi>country</gi>, <gi>region</gi>, <gi>settlement</gi>, and <gi>placeName</gi>. This is especially important where more than one possible place of origin is recorded, as each possible place should remain distinguishable in the encoding.</p>
                                                                                              <p>unknown origin <gi>origDate</gi> | <gi>origPlace</gi></p>
                                                                                              <p>Where the place and date of origin cannot be established, and no estimate is intended, this may be recorded explicitly in <gi>origin</gi> where required or useful for a particular project. This approach is optional. Where used, it should be applied consistently across the project.</p>
                                                                                              <p>This approach may be useful where the item contains no internal or external evidence of origin or where supplying an estimated place or date would be misleading. Where Unknown is recorded explicitly, use <att>cert</att>=<val>unknown</val> on either <gi>origDate</gi> or <gi>origPlace</gi>, as appropriate, and provide <code>Unknown</code> as the content value. If the absence of information is the result of analytical judgement, include <att>evidence</att>=<val>conjecture</val> as well. Where useful, include <gi>p</gi> within <gi>origin</gi> to explain that the date, place, or both could not be determined.</p>
                                                                                              <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                <row>
                                                                                                  <cell><p rend="right">date and place unknown</p>
                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Unknown</p>
                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> Unknown</p>
                                                                                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<origDate cert="unknown" evidence="conjecture">Unknown</origDate>
<origPlace cert="unknown" evidence="conjecture">Unknown</origPlace>
</origin></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                  </row>
                                                                                                </table>
                                                                                                <p>If the project does not require Unknown origin information to be displayed or encoded, <gi>origDate</gi> and <gi>origPlace</gi> may be omitted.</p>
                                                                                              </div>
                                                                                              <div xml:id="place-known-date-unknown-date-known-place-unknown">
                                                                                                <head>Place known, date unknown | date known, place unknown</head>
                                                                                                <p>In cases where only one of the origin elements is unknown, place known | date unknown or date known | place unknown, apply the same principle:  use <att>cert</att>=<val>unknown</val> on either <gi>origPlace</gi> or <gi>origDate</gi> as appropriate, and provide <hi rend="italic">Unknown</hi> as the content value. If the absence is the result of analytical judgement, include <att>evidence</att>=<val>conjecture</val> as well.</p>
                                                                                                <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                  <row>
                                                                                                    <cell><p rend="right">date known, place unknown</p>
                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Unknown</p>
                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 17th century, late</p>
                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi></p>
                                                                                                      <p>The date is estimated as the late seventeenth century, while the place of origin is unknown.</p>
                                                                                                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<origDate notBefore="1670" notAfter="1700" cert="medium">17th century, late</origDate>
<origPlace cert="unknown" evidence="conjecture">Unknown</origPlace>
<p>The date is estimated as the late seventeenth century, while the place of origin is unknown.</p>
</origin></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                    </row>
                                                                                                    <row>
                                                                                                      <cell><p rend="right">place known, date unknown</p>
                                                                                                        <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Italy, Florence</p>
                                                                                                        <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> Unknown</p>
                                                                                                        <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi></p>
                                                                                                        <p>The place of origin is Italy, Florence, while the date is unknown.</p>
                                                                                                        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<origDate cert="unknown" evidence="conjecture">Unknown</origDate>
<origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="1000080">Italy</country>, <settlement source="#tgn" key="7000457">Florence</settlement></origPlace>
<p>The place of origin is Italy, Florence, while the date is unknown.</p>
</origin></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                      </row>
                                                                                                    </table>
                                                                                                    <p> <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">Avoid</hi></hi> using terms like no date, n.d., and date not identified within <gi>origDate</gi>, or terms such as s.d., S.l., S.n., and place not identified within <gi>origPlace</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                  </div>
                                                                                                </div>
                                                                                                <div xml:id="provenance">
                                                                                                  <head><code>&lt;provenance&gt;</code> | provenance</head>
                                                                                                  <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-provenance.html"><gi>provenance</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(provenance) contains any descriptive or other information concerning a single identifiable episode during the history of a manuscript, manuscript part, or other object after its creation but before its acquisition.</hi></p>
                                                                                                  <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Provenance</hi></p>
                                                                                                  <p><gi>provenance</gi> within <gi>history</gi> is used to record identifiable stages in the item’s post-creation history, tracing its chain of ownership, custody, discovery, and use as it passed between people or organisations before its acquisition by the present holding institution.</p>
                                                                                                  <p><gi>provenance</gi> may be used to record provenance information relating to the entire item or to an individual <gi>msPart</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                  <p><gi>provenance</gi> may take one of two forms:</p>
                                                                                                  <p>Unstructured | a single <gi>provenance</gi> with one or more <gi>p</gi>, describing provenance stages narratively.</p>
                                                                                                  <p>Structured | a sequence of <gi>provenance</gi>, each with one or more <gi>p</gi>, describing a distinct stage in the item’s provenance history.</p>
                                                                                                  <p>Although unstructured encoding is permitted, it is <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> recommended as the default where multiple stages can be identified. Wherever possible, provenance information should be organised using one or more separate <gi>provenance</gi>, as this supports a clearer distinction between provenance stages.</p>
                                                                                                  <p>Combining multiple stages within a single <gi>provenance</gi> is generally discouraged. It may occasionally be necessary in retroconversion workflows, particularly when existing catalogue information cannot be reliably separated into distinct stages.</p>
                                                                                                  <p>Multiple <gi>provenance</gi> should be arranged in chronological order, from the earliest known stage to the most recent. The item’s acquisition by the present holding institution should be recorded separately in <gi>acquisition</gi>, where known.</p>
                                                                                                  <p><gi>provenance</gi> may include <att>when</att>, <att>from</att>, <att>to</att>, or <att>notBefore</att>, <att>notAfter</att>, to date the individual stages in the provenance chain.</p>
                                                                                                  <p rend="right"><att>when</att> | <att>from</att>, <att>to</att> | <att>notBefore</att>, <att>notAfter</att></p>
                                                                                                  <p><att>when</att> supplies the value of a single known provenance date in standard form.</p>
                                                                                                  <p><att>from</att>, <att>to</att> indicate known starting and ending points of a provenance stage in standard form.</p>
                                                                                                  <p><att>notBefore</att>, <att>notAfter</att> specify the earliest and latest possible dates of a provenance stage in standard form.</p>
                                                                                                  <p>Dating attributes are recommended where the date or date range of a provenance stage can be established or reliably inferred. Where no reliable date can be assigned, dating attributes are <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> required, and <gi>provenance</gi> remains valid without them.</p>
                                                                                                  <p>Where dates are mentioned within the prose of <gi>provenance</gi>, they may be recorded as text only, encoded using <gi>date</gi>, or encoded using <gi>date</gi> with dating attributes, as appropriate.</p>
                                                                                                  <p>Any name associated with former ownership should be encoded using <code>&lt;name role="fmo"&gt;</code>, containing either <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> as appropriate. If the name is listed in VIAF, include both <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> on <gi>name</gi> to reference the relevant VIAF authority record. <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> should be given in both a display and a standard form using <att>type</att>=<val>display</val> and <att>type</att>=<val>standard</val> respectively.</p>
                                                                                                  <p><att>role</att> specifies the relationship of a person or organisation to an item’s provenance. For the provenance heading, this value should normally be <val>fmo</val>, used for former owners, or, where appropriate, <val>pat</val>, used for patrons. Other MARC relator codes, such as <val>bsl</val> for booksellers or <val>asn</val> for associated names, may be used for names encoded within the supporting prose, where appropriate.</p>
                                                                                                  <p>Each <gi>provenance</gi> should begin with a <gi>p</gi> containing the name of the associated former owner or patron. Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> include a full stop at the end of a provenance heading where <gi>p</gi> contains only the encoded name.</p>
                                                                                                  <p>The following format is required for individuals and organisations:</p>
                                                                                                  <p>For individuals, <code>&lt;persName type="display"&gt;</code> should give the display form of the name, followed by life dates in parentheses where known (birth and death years), and a brief descriptive qualifier indicating an occupation and or role.</p>
                                                                                                  <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                    <row>
                                                                                                      <cell><p><code>Full personal name (YYYY-YYYY), descriptive qualifier</code></p></cell>
                                                                                                    </row>
                                                                                                    <row>
                                                                                                      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Former Owner(s):</hi> Patarolo, Lorenzo, 1674-1757</p>
                                                                                                        <p><hi rend="bold">• Provenance:</hi></p>
                                                                                                        <p>▪ Lorenzo Patarolo (1674-1757), scholar and antiquarian</p>
                                                                                                        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><p><name source="#viaf" key="44644175" role="fmo"><persName type="display">Lorenzo Patarolo (1674-1757), scholar and antiquarian</persName><persName type="standard">Patarolo, Lorenzo, 1674-1757</persName></name></p></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                      </row>
                                                                                                    </table>
                                                                                                    <p>When a name functions as a provenance heading, a brief descriptive qualifier should be included in <code>&lt;persName type="display"&gt;</code> or <code>&lt;orgName type="display"&gt;</code>. Where a name appears within narrative prose, descriptive qualifiers should, where necessary, be provided in the surrounding text rather than within <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                    <p>For organisations, <code>&lt;orgName type="standard"&gt;</code> should give the authorised form of the name, following the preferred term from VIAF where available. VIAF forms may be qualified or unqualified depending on disambiguation needs. <code>&lt;orgName type="display"&gt;</code> should give the form intended for presentation in the MDC interface and may include an added geographical qualifier in parentheses where this improves clarity. Where a place qualifier is supplied in the display form, it should be given consistently as city, country, aligning with established VIAF presentation conventions.</p>
                                                                                                    <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                      <row>
                                                                                                        <cell><p><code>Full organisation name (city, country)</code></p></cell>
                                                                                                      </row>
                                                                                                      <row>
                                                                                                        <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Former Owner(s):</hi> Accademia della Crusca</p>
                                                                                                          <p><hi rend="bold">• Provenance:</hi></p>
                                                                                                          <p>▪ Accademia della Crusca (Florence, Italy)</p>
                                                                                                          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><p><name source="#viaf" key="143077072" role="fmo"><orgName type="display">Accademia della Crusca (Florence, Italy)</orgName><orgName type="standard">Accademia della Crusca</orgName></name></p></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                        </row>
                                                                                                      </table>
                                                                                                      <p>Descriptive qualifiers, such as occupations or roles, should be derived primarily from the <ref target="https://www.oxforddnb.com/">Oxford Dictionary of National Biography (DNB)</ref>, and secondarily from <ref target="https://viaf.org/">VIAF®</ref>.</p>
                                                                                                      <p>Where a personal name is accompanied by a descriptive qualifier, check whether the same name–qualifier combination is already in use within the system. Where an established form exists, it should be reused exactly as recorded. Where no such form is available, assess whether the proposed combination is current, authoritative, and appropriate, and ensure that it is consistent with established authority sources and local practice.</p>
                                                                                                      <p>Supporting evidence should follow the provenance heading, in one or more subsequent <gi>p</gi> within the same <gi>provenance</gi>. These <gi>p</gi> should be ordered in a clear and logical sequence. Where applicable, give any relevant institutional or collection context before the supporting evidence of ownership, whether internal, external, or both.</p>
                                                                                                      <p>Internal evidence may include, but is not limited to, bookplates, colophons, ownership inscriptions, autographs, signatures, manuscript numbers, sale prices, labels, stamps, shelfmarks, descriptions of ownership marks, including heraldic features where present, or other notes of ownership or use. Where the location of the evidence is known, <gi>locus</gi> should be used within the description to indicate where it appears on the item.</p>
                                                                                                      <p>External evidence may derive from sources such as dealer or auction catalogues, booklists, inventories, wills, accounts, archival records, scholarly descriptions, reference works, or other published sources that mention the item. Sources should be cited clearly, either in full within the prose or by using a short-form reference with a corresponding full entry within <gi>listBibl</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                      <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                        <row>
                                                                                                          <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Former Owner(s):</hi> Patarolo, Lorenzo, 1674-1757</p>
                                                                                                            <p><hi rend="bold">• Provenance:</hi></p>
                                                                                                            <p>▪ Lorenzo Patarolo (1674-1757), scholar and antiquarian</p>
                                                                                                            <p>Early manuscript inscription on the lower margin of *1r: <hi rend="italic">Laurentii Patarol</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><provenance>
<p><name source="#viaf" key="44644175" role="fmo"><persName type="display">Lorenzo Patarolo (1674-1757), scholar and antiquarian</persName><persName type="standard">Patarolo, Lorenzo, 1674-1757</persName></name></p>
<p>Early manuscript inscription on the lower margin of <locus from="*1r" to="*1r">*1r</locus>: <hi rend="italic">Laurentii Patarol</hi>.</p>
</provenance></egXML></p>
                                                                                                            <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Vita nuoua di Dante Alighieri...:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-SPCC-R-17114/1">R17114</ref></p></cell>
                                                                                                        </row>
                                                                                                      </table>
                                                                                                      <p>A patron is not normally a primary provenance figure in the same way as a former owner or custodian. Their role may, however, be relevant where commissioning, financial support, or other evidence of patronage forms part of the item’s history.</p>
                                                                                                      <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                        <row>
                                                                                                          <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Provenance:</hi></p>
                                                                                                            <p>▪ Lorenzo di Strozzi (-1400), nobleman of the influential Strozzi family</p>
                                                                                                            <p>The colophon on 174r acknowledges Lorenzo Strozzi as the commissioner and Paolo as the scribe. It also includes a blessing for the wellbeing of both the patron and the scribe.</p>
                                                                                                            <p>The lower borders on 3r and 105r bear the arms of the Strozzi family: Or, on a fess Gules, three crescent moons Argent.</p>
                                                                                                            <p>Diagonal pencil inscription on the Flyleaf 1r: Written for Lorenzo di Strozzi | circa 1520.</p>
                                                                                                            <p>▪ Theodor Oswald Weigel (1812-1881), bookseller, art dealer, publisher, and collector</p>
                                                                                                            <p>Stamped in gilt on the lower margin of the front cover: the initials <hi rend="italic">T.O.W</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><provenance>
<p><name role="pat"><persName type="display">Lorenzo di Strozzi (-1400), nobleman of the influential Strozzi family</persName><persName type="standard">Strozzi, Lorenzo, -1400</persName></name></p>
<p>The colophon on <locus from="174r" to="174r">174r</locus> acknowledges Lorenzo Strozzi as the commissioner and Paolo as the scribe. It also includes a blessing for the wellbeing of both the patron and the scribe.</p>
<p>The lower borders on <locus from="3r" to="3r">3r</locus> and <locus from="105r" to="105r">105r</locus> bear the Strozzi family arms: <heraldry>Or, on a fess Gules, three crescent moons Argent</heraldry>.</p>
<p>Diagonal pencil inscription on the <locus from="Flyleaf_1r" to="Flyleaf_1r">flyleaf 1r</locus>: <hi rend="italic">Written for Lorenzo di Strozzi | circa 1520</hi>.</p>
</provenance>
<provenance>
<p><name source="#viaf" key="40150737" role="fmo"><persName type="display">Theodor Oswald Weigel (1812-1881), bookseller, art dealer, publisher, and collector</persName><persName type="standard">Weigel, T.O. (Theodor Oswald), 1812-1881 </persName></name></p>
<p>Stamped in gilt on the lower margin of the <locus from="Front_cover" to="Front_cover">front cover</locus>: the initials <hi rend="italic">T.O.W</hi>.</p>
</provenance></egXML></p>
                                                                                                            <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Il Canzoniere di Petrarca e Le Rime di Dante</hi>: <hi rend="italic"><ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-ITALIAN-00001/1">Italian MS 1</ref></hi></p></cell>
                                                                                                        </row>
                                                                                                      </table>
                                                                                                      <p><gi>orgName</gi> is used for any named collection of people regarded as a single unit, including a family, institution, or organisation.</p>
                                                                                                      <p>When the place of creation differs from the place of discovery, the two should be encoded separately and unambiguously, even where the locations are geographically close. Use <gi>origPlace</gi> to encode the place where the item was created or written, representing its geographic origin at the point of production. Use <gi>provenance</gi> to encode the place where the item was found or discovered, describing a specific episode in the object’s history after its creation and prior to its acquisition.</p>
                                                                                                      <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                        <row>
                                                                                                          <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Egypt<hi rend="bold">,</hi> Krokodilopolis (Al Fayyūm)</p>
                                                                                                            <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 14 June 250</p>
                                                                                                            <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin:</hi> Written on 14 June 250, in Egypt, Krokodilopolis (Al Fayyūm).</p>
                                                                                                            <p><hi rend="bold">• Provenance:</hi></p>
                                                                                                            <p>▪ Found at Theadelphia (Batn-Ihrît).</p>
                                                                                                            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<p>Written on <origDate when="0250-06-14">14 June 250</origDate> in <origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="7016833">Egypt</country>, <settlement><placeName type="ancient" source="#tgn" key="7000991">Krokodilopolis</placeName> (<placeName type="modern" source="#tgn" key="7001197">Al Fayyūm</placeName>)</settlement></origPlace>.</p>
</origin>
<provenance>
<p>Found at <settlement><placeName type="ancient" source="#tgn" key="5000721">Theadelphia</placeName> (<placeName type="modern">Batn-Ihrît</placeName>)</settlement></p>
</provenance>
<!-- additional metadata --></egXML></p>
                                                                                                            <p rend="right">Certificate of Pagan Sacrifice: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-GREEK-P-00012/1">Greek P 12</ref></p></cell>
                                                                                                        </row>
                                                                                                      </table>
                                                                                                      <p>When the value <val>#viaf</val> is used for <att>source</att>, it indicates that the identifier recorded in <att>key</att> is drawn from this authority file. The prefix <code>#</code> indicates a reference to an identifier defined elsewhere in the same file. In this case, it refers to the <gi>taxonomy</gi> declared in the header with <att>xml:id</att>=<val>viaf</val>. This value can be selected from a controlled dropdown list when entering the attribute and does not need to be typed manually.</p>
                                                                                                      <p><att>role</att> on <gi>name</gi> is constrained by a controlled vocabulary defined in our customised TEI schema, extended via an ODD (One Document Does it all). The permitted values for the MARC relator codes appear in the XML editor as a drop-down list. Additional terms may be included through the ODD. Only these values are valid. Any others will result in a schema validation error.</p>
                                                                                                      <p>Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> use <gi>list</gi> for provenance evidence.</p>
                                                                                                      <p>Evidence of former ownership or custody, including heraldry, former shelfmarks, notes on endleaves, or other inscriptions, should be recorded in <gi>provenance</gi> even where it cannot be securely attributed to a named person or institution. If no clear provenance connection can be established, use <gi>additions</gi> instead.</p>
                                                                                                    </div>
                                                                                                    <div xml:id="acquisition">
                                                                                                      <head><code>&lt;acquisition&gt;</code> | acquisition</head>
                                                                                                      <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-acquisition.html"><gi>acquisition</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(acquisition) contains any descriptive or other information concerning the process by which a manuscript or manuscript part or other object entered the holding institution</hi></p>
                                                                                                      <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label— <hi rend="bold">Acquisition</hi></p>
                                                                                                      <p><gi>acquisition</gi> within <gi>history</gi> is used to record how the item was acquired by the present holding institution as the final stage in its history.</p>
                                                                                                      <p>Any information specific to the means by which the item was acquired by its present owners should be given as one or more <gi>p</gi> within <gi>acquisition</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                      <p>Any name associated with the acquisition of an item should be encoded using <gi>name</gi>, containing either <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> as appropriate, and must include a <att>role</att> indicating the nature of the relationship to the item in the context of acquisition. If the name is listed in VIAF, include both <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> on <gi>name</gi> to reference the relevant VIAF authority record. <gi>persName</gi> or <gi>orgName</gi> should be given in both a display and a standard form using <att>type</att>=<val>display</val> and <att>type</att>=<val>standard</val> respectively.</p>
                                                                                                      <p><att>role</att> specifies the relationship of a person or organisation to an item’s acquisition. In most cases, this value should normally be <val>dnr</val>, used for donors, and <val>own</val> for the current owner, that is, the holding institution that acquired the item. Other MARC relator codes, such as <val>bsl</val> for booksellers or <val>asn</val> for associated names, may be used for names encoded within the supporting prose, where appropriate, to reflect the acquisition pathway. For example, where the item was purchased from a named vendor, auction house, or intermediary.</p>
                                                                                                      <p>The date of acquisition should be encoded within <gi>acquisition</gi> using <gi>date</gi> with <att>when</att> for single known dates, or <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att> for approximate or inferred ranges, as appropriate. This date will be pulled through into the display field labelled <hi rend="bold">Acquisition Date</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                      <p>Acquisition information should follow a clear and consistent sentence structure, using the following pattern, omitting any components that are not applicable or not known:</p>
                                                                                                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">Action — by agent [personal or organisation name, with life dates where applicable] — in/on [date] — to the Library
Action — by the Library — in/on [date] — from agent [personal or organisation name, with life dates where applicable]</egXML></p>
                                                                                                      <p>The statement should begin with the method of acquisition, for example, Purchased, Acquired, Presented, Donated, or Bequeathed. It should then record the relevant person or organisation involved in the acquisition, the date of acquisition, and the holding institution, where applicable. Additional transaction details, such as price, fund, or accession number, may be included where known.</p>
                                                                                                      <p>In MDC, unless otherwise stated, The John Rylands Library is assumed to be the final custodian and current owner.</p>
                                                                                                      <p>Any further evidence, whether internal or external, may be included in prose and, where necessary, recorded in one or more <gi>p</gi> within the same <gi>acquisition</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                      <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                        <row>
                                                                                                          <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Acquisition:</hi></p>
                                                                                                            <p>Presented by David Lindsay, 27th Earl of Crawford (1871-1940) in 1924 to The John Rylands Library.</p>
                                                                                                            <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Acquisition:</hi> 1924</p>
                                                                                                            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<acquisition>
<p>Presented by <name source="#viaf" key="46770980" role="dnr"><persName type="display">David Lindsay, 27th Earl of Crawford (1871-1940)</persName><persName type="standard">Crawford, David Lindsay, Earl of, 1871-1940</persName></name> in <date when="1924">1924</date> to <name source="#viaf" key="312795145" role="own"><orgName>The John Rylands Library</orgName></name>.</p>
<acquisition>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                          </row>
                                                                                                          <row>
                                                                                                            <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Acquisition:</hi></p>
                                                                                                              <p>Purchased by The John Rylands Library on 24 November 1908 from Bernard Quaritch Ltd for £225. Accession number: R16980.</p>
                                                                                                              <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Acquisition:</hi> 24 November 1908</p>
                                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><acquisition>
<p>Purchased by <name source="#viaf" key="312795145" role="own"><orgName>The John Rylands Library</orgName></name> on <date when="1908-11-24">24 November 1908</date> from <name source="#viaf" key="141331450" role="bsl"><orgName type="display">Bernard Quaritch Ltd </orgName><orgName type="standard">Bernard Quaritch (Firm)</orgName></name> for £225. Accession number: R16980.</p>
</acquisition></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                            </row>
                                                                                                            <row>
                                                                                                              <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Acquisition:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                <p>Purchased by The John Rylands Library on 2 July 2024 from Sotheby’s for £16,000.</p>
                                                                                                                <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Acquisition:</hi> 2 July 2024</p>
                                                                                                                <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><acquisition>
<p>Purchased by <name source="#viaf" key="312795145" role="own"><orgName>The John Rylands Library</orgName></name> on <date when="2024-07-02">2 July 2024</date> from Sotheby's for £16,000.</p>
</acquisition></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                              </row>
                                                                                                            </table>
                                                                                                            <p>Within <gi>acquisition</gi>, the institution that acquired or obtained the item should be recorded explicitly as the owner. This should be encoded using <gi>name</gi> with <att>role</att>=<val>own</val> and <gi>orgName</gi>. This records ownership in the context of acquisition and is distinct from <gi>repository</gi> and <gi>idno</gi> within <gi>msIdentifier</gi>, which identify the item’s current repository and shelfmark.</p>
                                                                                                            <p>Where individuals or organisations are referenced multiple times within <gi>history</gi>, they should normally be encoded in a controlled form only once, at the first occurrence of the name. Subsequent occurrences may be given in plain text, unless additional encoding is required to express a different role, relationship, or authority context.</p>
                                                                                                            <p>Transfer details may be included where known, such as acquisition from a previous holder or intermediary, or transfer to the current repository. Where the acquisition history includes multiple institutional stages, and the provenance cannot be separated into distinct transactions, for example, acquired by the University and later transferred to the Library, this should be recorded as a single narrative statement that reflects the sequence of custody as accurately as possible.</p>
                                                                                                            <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                              <row>
                                                                                                                <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Donor(s):</hi> Bullock, Hélène Louise, 1881-1973</p>
                                                                                                                  <p><hi rend="bold">• Acquisition:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                  <p>Donated by Hélène Louise Bullock (1881-1973), widow of Walter Llewellyn Bullock, in 1944 to The University of Manchester, and later transferred to The John Rylands Library.</p>
                                                                                                                  <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Acquisition:</hi> 1899</p>
                                                                                                                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><acquisition>
<p>Donated by <name role="dnr"><persName type="display">Hélène Louise Bullock (1881-1973)</persName><persName type="standard">Bullock, Hélène Louise, 1881-1973</persName></name>, widow of Walter Llewellyn Bullock, in <date when="1944">1944</date> to <name source="#viaf" key="157695433"><orgName>The University of Manchester</orgName></name>, and later transferred to <name source="#viaf" key="312795145" role="own"><orgName>The John Rylands Library</orgName></name>.</p>
</acquisition></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                </row>
                                                                                                              </table>
                                                                                                              <p>Acquisition information may sometimes include provenance-related information where this forms part of the available acquisition evidence, particularly where it provides the only available account of how the item came into the holding institution’s possession.</p>
                                                                                                              <p><hi rend="bold">The John Rylands Library foundation collections</hi></p>
                                                                                                              <p>The John Rylands Library’s foundation collections were established through two major acquisitions, both personally overseen by Enriqueta Rylands. Together, these acquisitions underpinned the Library’s exceptional collections of rare books and manuscripts.</p>
                                                                                                              <p>For provenance purposes, Enriqueta Rylands should be recorded as a former owner. Many early acquisitions were purchased by her directly, and her name therefore appears in early transaction records as purchaser or owner, even where the material was acquired with the explicit intention of forming the Library’s collections.</p>
                                                                                                              <p>For acquisition purposes, Enriqueta Rylands should be recorded as the donor. The Spenceriana was transferred during her lifetime, while the Lindesiana manuscripts entered the Library by bequest. In both cases, the acquisition reflects her foundational role in establishing the Library’s holdings.</p>
                                                                                                              <p><hi rend="bold">Bibliotheca Spenceriana | Spencer Collection</hi></p>
                                                                                                              <p>The Bibliotheca Spenceriana is one of the most celebrated private libraries of early printed books ever assembled. Formed by George John Spencer, 2nd Earl Spencer (1758–1834) at Althorp, the collection is particularly rich in incunabula, early Bibles, Aldines, Caxtons, and works of classical and Renaissance humanist scholarship. It is renowned not only for the rarity and quality of individual items but also for its scholarly coherence, careful organisation, and elegant bindings.</p>
                                                                                                              <p>In 1892, the entire Althorp Library was purchased by Enriqueta Rylands from John Poyntz Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer (1835–1910) for £210,000. She donated the collection to The John Rylands Library in 1899, making it the foundational printed book collection of the institution. The Bibliotheca Spenceriana catalogue, compiled by Thomas Frognall Dibdin, remains a landmark of bibliographical literature.</p>
                                                                                                              <p>The agreed form for the Spencer Collection is:</p>
                                                                                                              <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                <row>
                                                                                                                  <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Former Owner(s):</hi> Spencer, George John Spencer, Earl, 1758-1834; Spencer, John Poyntz Spencer, Earl, 1835-1910; Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</p>
                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">• Donor(s):</hi> Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</p>
                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">• Provenance:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                    <p>▪ George John Spencer, 2nd Earl Spencer (1758-1834), politician and book collector</p>
                                                                                                                    <p>▪ John Poyntz Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer (1835-1910), politician and viceroy of Ireland</p>
                                                                                                                    <p>Formerly in the Spencer Library (Bibliotheca Spenceriana) at Althorp, Northamptonshire, largely assembled by George John Spencer and subsequently passing by descent to John Poyntz Spencer.</p>
                                                                                                                    <p>▪ Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908), philanthropist and founder of The John Rylands Library</p>
                                                                                                                    <p>Purchased by Enriqueta Rylands in 1901 from John Poyntz Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer (1835-1910).</p>
                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">• Acquisition:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                    <p>Donated by Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908) in 1899 to The John Rylands Library.</p>
                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Acquisition:</hi> 1899</p>
                                                                                                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<provenance>
<p><name source="#viaf" key="17584030" role="fmo"><persName type="display">George John Spencer, 2nd Earl Spencer (1758-1834), politician and book collector</persName><persName type="standard">Spencer, George John Spencer, Earl, 1758-1834</persName></name></p>
<p><name source="#viaf" key="54160187" role="fmo"><persName type="display">John Poyntz Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer (1835-1910), politician and viceroy of Ireland</persName><persName type="standard">Spencer, John Poyntz Spencer, Earl, 1835-1910</persName></name></p>
<p>Formerly in the Spencer Library (Bibliotheca Spenceriana) at Althorp, Northamptonshire, largely assembled by George John Spencer and subsequently passing by descent to John Poyntz Spencer.</p>
<!-- Evidence of previous ownership, including bookplates and stamps recorded in one or more <p> -->
</provenance>
<provenance>
<name role="fmo"><persName type="display">Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908), philanthropist and founder of The John Rylands Library</persName><persName type="standard">Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</persName></name></p>
<p>Purchased by Enriqueta Rylands in <date when="1892">1892</date> from John Poyntz Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer (1835-1910).</p>
</provenance>
<provenance>
<name role="dnr"><persName type="display">Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908), philanthropist and founder of The John Rylands Library</persName><persName type="standard">Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</persName></name></p>
<p>Purchased by Enriqueta Rylands in <date when="1892">1892</date> from John Poyntz Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer (1835-1910).</p>
</provenance>
<acquisition>
<p>Donated by <name role="dnr"><persName type="display">Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908)</persName><persName type="standard">Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</persName></name> in <date when="1899">1899</date> to <name source="#viaf" key="312795145" role="own"><orgName>The John Rylands Library</orgName></name>.</p>
<!-- Evidence of acquisition, including bookplates and stamps recorded in one or more <p> -->
</acquisition>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                  </row>
                                                                                                                </table>
                                                                                                                <p><hi rend="bold">Bibliotheca Lindesiana | Crawford Collection</hi></p>
                                                                                                                <p>The Bibliotheca Lindesiana was one of the most ambitious and cosmopolitan manuscript libraries established in Britain during the nineteenth century. Developed by Alexander William Crawford Lindsay (1812–1880), 25th Earl of Crawford and 8th Earl of Balcarres, known for most of his life as Lord Lindsay, and his son, James Ludovic Lindsay (1847–1913), 26th Earl of Crawford and 9th Earl of Balcarres, the collection was housed at Haigh Hall in Haigh, near Wigan. Conceived as a repository of universal knowledge, it possessed exceptional strengths across both European and non-European traditions, encompassing medieval and early modern codices, scrolls, fragments, papyri, and printed books in a remarkable array of languages, scripts, materials, and formats.</p>
                                                                                                                <p>In 1901, a significant portion of the manuscript collection was purchased by Enriqueta Rylands from James Ludovic Lindsay for £155,000, with the intention of enhancing the new Library’s holdings. However, the majority of the manuscripts remained in her personal possession at Longford Hall and were bequeathed to The John Rylands Library after her death in 1908. This bequest greatly expanded the Library’s global manuscript coverage and remains a cornerstone of its special collections.</p>
                                                                                                                <p>The agreed form for the Crawford Collection is:</p>
                                                                                                                <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                  <row>
                                                                                                                    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Former Owner(s):</hi> Crawford, Alexander Crawford Lindsay, 1812-1880; Crawford, James Ludovic Lindsay, Earl of, 1847-1913; Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</p>
                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Donor(s):</hi> Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</p>
                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Provenance:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                      <p>▪ Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812-1880), book collector and writer on art</p>
                                                                                                                      <p>▪ James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847-1913), astronomer and book collector</p>
                                                                                                                      <p>Formerly in the Crawford Library (Bibliotheca Lindesiana) at Haigh Hall, Lancashire, which was formed and developed by Alexander and James Ludovic Lindsay.</p>
                                                                                                                      <p>▪ Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908), philanthropist and founder of The John Rylands Library</p>
                                                                                                                      <p>Purchased by Enriqueta Rylands in 1901 from James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847-1913).</p>
                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Acquisition:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                      <p>Bequeathed by Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908) in 1908 to The John Rylands Library.</p>
                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Acquisition:</hi> 1908</p>
                                                                                                                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<provenance>
<p><name source="#viaf" key="97751058" role="fmo"><persName type="display">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812-1880), book collector and writer on art</persName><persName type="standard">Crawford, Alexander Crawford Lindsay, 1812-1880</persName></name></p>
<p><name source="#viaf" key="9985420" role="fmo"><persName type="display">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847-1913), astronomer and book collector</persName><persName type="standard">Crawford, James Ludovic Lindsay, Earl of, 1847-1913</persName></name></p>
<p>Formerly in the Crawford Library (Bibliotheca Lindesiana) at Haigh Hall, Lancashire, which was formed and developed by Alexander and James Ludovic Lindsay.</p>
<!-- Evidence of provenance, including bookplates and stamps recorded in one or more <p> -->
</provenance>
<provenance>
<name role="fmo"><persName type="display">Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908), philanthropist and founder of The John Rylands Library</persName><persName type="standard">Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</persName></name></p>
<p>Purchased by Enriqueta Rylands in <date when="1901">1901</date> from James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847-1913).</p>
</provenance>
<acquisition>
<p>Bequeathed by <name role="dnr"><persName type="display">Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908)</persName><persName type="standard">Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</persName></name> in <date when="1908">1908</date> to <name source="#viaf" key="312795145" role="own"><orgName>The John Rylands Library</orgName></name>.</p>
<!-- Evidence of acquisition, including bookplates and stamps recorded in one or more <p> -->
</acquisition>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                    </row>
                                                                                                                  </table>
                                                                                                                  <p>There may be cases in which only one of the Crawfords and only one of the Spencers is associated with provenance, and the statement should reflect only the individual or entity directly involved.</p>
                                                                                                                  <p>It should be noted that the Bibliotheca Lindesiana manuscripts did not enter The John Rylands Library solely through Enriqueta Rylands’s 1901 purchase and 1908 bequest. Further material from the Crawford library continued to come to the Library during the early twentieth century through additional gifts and deposits by the Lindsay family, including the European Proclamations and Broadsides presented to The John Rylands Library by David Lindsay, 27th Earl of Crawford, in 1924.</p>
                                                                                                                  <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                    <row>
                                                                                                                      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Former Owner(s):</hi> Crawford, Alexander Crawford Lindsay, 1812-1880; Crawford, James Ludovic Lindsay, Earl of, 1847-1913; Crawford, David Lindsay, Earl of, 1871-1940</p>
                                                                                                                        <p><hi rend="bold">• Donor(s):</hi> Crawford, David Lindsay, Earl of, 1871-1940</p>
                                                                                                                        <p><hi rend="bold">• Provenance:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                        <p>▪ Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812-1880), book collector and writer on art</p>
                                                                                                                        <p>▪ James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847-1913), astronomer and book collector</p>
                                                                                                                        <p>Formerly in the Crawford Library (Bibliotheca Lindesiana) at Haigh Hall, Lancashire, which was formed and developed by Alexander and James Ludovic Lindsay.</p>
                                                                                                                        <p>During the last quarter of the nineteenth century, the 26th Earl of Crawford actively directed a series of large purchases at auction to expand the French Revolution collection, which his son, David Lindsay, 27th Earl of Crawford (1871-1940), politician and art connoisseur, then transferred to The John Rylands Library during the first half of the twentieth century in the form of a gift and a semi-permanent loan.</p>
                                                                                                                        <p><hi rend="bold">• Acquisition:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                        <p>Presented by David Lindsay, 27th Earl of Crawford (1871-1940) in 1924 to The John Rylands Library.</p>
                                                                                                                        <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Acquisition:</hi> 1924</p>
                                                                                                                        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><provenance>
<p><name source="#viaf" key="97751058" role="fmo"><persName type="display">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812-1880), book collector and writer on art</persName><persName type="standard">Crawford, Alexander Crawford Lindsay, 1812-1880</persName></name></p>
<p><name source="#viaf" key="9985420" role="fmo"><persName type="display">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847-1913), astronomer and book collector</persName><persName type="standard">Crawford, James Ludovic Lindsay, Earl of, 1847-1913</persName></name></p>
<p>Formerly in the Crawford Library (Bibliotheca Lindesiana) at Haigh Hall, Lancashire, which was formed and developed by Alexander and James Ludovic Lindsay.</p>
<p>During the last quarter of the nineteenth century, the 26th Earl of Crawford actively directed a series of large purchases at auction to expand the French Revolution collection, which his son, <name source="#viaf" key="46770980" role="fmo"><persName type="display">David Lindsay, 27th Earl of Crawford (1871-1940), politician and art connoisseur</persName><persName type="standard">Crawford, David Lindsay, Earl of, 1871-1940</persName></name>, then transferred to The John Rylands Library during the first half of the twentieth century in the form of a gift and a semi-permanent loan.</p>
</provenance>
<acquisition>
<p>Presented by <name source="#viaf" key="46770980" role="dnr"><persName type="display">David Lindsay, 27th Earl of Crawford (1871-1940)</persName><persName type="standard">Crawford, David Lindsay, Earl of, 1871-1940</persName></name> in <date when="1924">1924</date> to <name source="#viaf" key="312795145" role="own"><orgName>The John Rylands Library</orgName></name>.</p>
</acquisition></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                      </row>
                                                                                                                    </table>
                                                                                                                    <p>Armorial bookplates associated with titled families such as the Earls of Crawford and Balcarres and the Earls of Spencer may appear in multiple heraldic variants, including forms with and without marital impalement. Descriptions should record the form present on the item. Where no individual is explicitly named, such bookplates should be attributed at the family or title level rather than to a specific person.</p>
                                                                                                                  </div>
                                                                                                                  <div xml:id="heraldry">
                                                                                                                    <head><code>&lt;heraldry&gt;</code> | heraldry</head>
                                                                                                                    <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-heraldry.html"><gi>heraldry</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(heraldry) contains a heraldic formula or phrase, typically found as part of a blazon, coat of arms, etc.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                    <p><gi>heraldry</gi> is a phrase-level, context-dependent element used to encode heraldic description within prose.</p>
                                                                                                                    <p>In heraldry, an achievement is the complete armorial display associated with a person, family, or institution. This may comprise the coat of arms together with associated components such as crest, coronet, supporters, badges, motto, order, or mantling. A heraldic description may refer to the arms alone, or to part or all of an achievement.</p>
                                                                                                                    <p><gi>heraldry</gi> may be used within <gi>physDesc</gi> where heraldry forms part of a binding, seal, or decorative programme and is not being recorded as provenance evidence. In such cases, the full heraldic description should be encoded in the relevant element, such as <gi>binding</gi>, <code>&lt;seal&gt;,</code> or <gi>decoNote</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                    <p>Where heraldry has both a physical and a provenance function, the full heraldic description should normally be encoded in <gi>provenance</gi>. The relevant physical description element may refer to the presence of the heraldry but should <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> repeat the full heraldic description encoded using <gi>heraldry</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                    <p><gi>heraldry</gi> may also be used within <gi>acquisition</gi> where armorial evidence is mentioned as part of the acquisition history.</p>
                                                                                                                    <p>Where heraldry serves primarily as evidence of former ownership, patronage, commissioning, or custody, the full heraldic description should be encoded using <gi>heraldry</gi> within <gi>provenance</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                    <p>For British armorial ownership marks on bindings, the <ref target="https://armorial.bibsoc.org.uk/owners.html">British Armorial Bindings</ref> database may be consulted to support identification of owners, heraldic stamps, mottoes, and related armorial evidence.</p>
                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">Crawford and Spencer heraldry, and variant forms</hi></p>
                                                                                                                    <p>Armorial evidence associated with titled families should be described according to the heraldic form present on the item, including its location using <gi>locus</gi> where appropriate. This is particularly important where arms associated with the same family or peerage title may appear in different variants, including forms with and without marital impalement. Where no individual is explicitly named, the evidence should be attributed to the family or peerage title rather than to a specific person, for example, bearing the arms of the Earls of Crawford and Balcarres or bearing the arms of the Earls of Spencer.</p>
                                                                                                                    <p>For Crawford material, the following pattern will usually be applicable:</p>
                                                                                                                    <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                      <row>
                                                                                                                        <cell><p>..., the armorial bookplate (Ex Libris), bearing the arms of the Earls of Crawford and Balcarres: Quarterly, 1st and 4th, Gules a fess chequy Argent and Azure. 2nd and 3rd, Or a lion rampant Gules, debruised of a ribbon in bend Sable. Crest: a swan’s head, neck, and wings proper, issuing from an antique ducal coronet Or. Supporters: two lions, rampant guardant Gules. Motto: <hi rend="italic">ENDURE FORT</hi> | <hi rend="italic">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                                          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><p>..., the armorial bookplate (Ex Libris), bearing the arms of the Earls of Crawford and Balcarres: <heraldry>Quarterly, 1st and 4th, Gules a fess chequy Argent and Azure. 2nd and 3rd, Or a lion rampant Gules, debruised of a ribbon in bend Sable. Crest: a swan’s head, neck, and wings proper, issuing from an antique ducal coronet Or. Supporters: two lions, rampant guardant Gules. Motto: <hi rend="italic">ENDURE FORT</hi></heraldry> | <hi rend="italic">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</hi>.</p></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                        </row>
                                                                                                                      </table>
                                                                                                                      <p>For Spencer material, the same principle will usually apply, although the heraldry may appear in several variant forms. One frequently encountered variant is associated with George John Spencer, 2nd Earl Spencer:</p>
                                                                                                                      <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                        <row>
                                                                                                                          <cell><p>..., the armorial bookplate (Ex Libris), bearing the arms of the Earls of Spencer, associated with the 2nd Earl Spencer: Quarterly, in the 2nd and 3rd quarters a fret Or, over all on a bend Sable three escallops Argent (Spencer), impaling Quarterly, 1st and 4th, a bend cotised between six crosses patty (Bingham), 2nd and 3rd, Ermine a lion rampant ducally crowned (Turberville). Supporters: a griffin and a wyvern erect on its tail, both collared and chained. Coronet of an Earl. Motto: <hi rend="italic">DIEU DEFEND LE DROIT</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                                            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><p>..., the armorial bookplate (Ex Libris), bearing the arms of the Earls of Spencer, associated with the 2nd Earl Spencer: <heraldry>Quarterly, 2nd and 3rd a fret Or, over all on a bend Sable three escallops Argent (Spencer), impaling Quarterly, 1st and 4th, a bend cotised between six crosses patty (Bingham), 2nd and 3rd, Ermine a lion rampant ducally crowned (Turberville). Supporters: a griffin and a wyvern erect on its tail, both collared and chained. Coronet of an Earl. Motto: <hi rend="italic">DIEU DEFEND LE DROIT</hi></heraldry>.</p></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                          </row>
                                                                                                                        </table>
                                                                                                                        <p>A less frequently encountered variant is that associated with John Spencer, 1st Earl Spencer:</p>
                                                                                                                        <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                          <row>
                                                                                                                            <cell><p>... the armorial bookplate (Ex Libris) bearing the arms of the Earls of Spencer, associated with John Spencer, 1st Earl Spencer (1734-1783): Quarterly Argent and Gules, on the second and third quarters a fret Or, over all on a bend Sable three escallops Argent (Spencer), impaling Barry of eight Or and Gules (Poyntz). Crest: a ducal coronet. Supporters: a griffin and a wyvern erect on its tail, both collared and chained. Coronet: of an Earl. Motto: <hi rend="italic">DIEU DEFEND LE DROIT</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<p>... the armorial bookplate (Ex Libris), bearing the arms of the Earls of Spencer, associated with name source="#viaf" key="43873805" role="fmo"><persName type="display">John Spencer, 1st Earl Spencer (1734-1783)</persName><persName type="standard">Spencer, John Spencer, Earl, 1734-1783</persName></name>: <heraldry>Quarterly Argent and Gules, on the 2nd and 3rd quarters a fret Or, over all on a bend Sable three escallops Argent (Spencer), impaling Barry of eight Or and Gules (Poyntz). Crest: a ducal coronet. Supporters: a griffin and a wyvern erect on its tail, both collared and chained. Coronet: of an Earl. Motto: <hi rend="italic">DIEU DEFEND LE DROIT</hi></heraldry>.</p>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                            </row>
                                                                                                                          </table>
                                                                                                                          <p>The following examples provide model patterns for recording recurring forms of armorial provenance evidence associated with Crawford and Spencer material. They show how to describe the physical evidence present on the item, attribute arms at family or title level where no individual is explicitly named, record identifiable heraldic variants where appropriate, and encode the heraldic description using <gi>heraldry</gi>. The wording should be adapted to the specific evidence found on the item.</p>
                                                                                                                          <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                            <row>
                                                                                                                              <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Provenance:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                <p>▪ Lorenzo di Strozzi (-1400), nobleman of the influential Strozzi family</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>The colophon on 174r acknowledges Lorenzo Strozzi as the commissioner and Paolo as the scribe. It also includes a blessing for the wellbeing of both the patron and the scribe.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>The lower borders on 3r and 105r bear the arms of the Strozzi family: Or, on a fess Gules, three crescent moons Argent.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>Diagonal pencil inscription on the Flyleaf 1r: <hi rend="italic">Written for Lorenzo di Strozzi</hi> | <hi rend="italic">circa 1520</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>▪ Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812-1880), book collector and writer on art</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>▪ James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847-1913), astronomer and book collector</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>Formerly in the Crawford Library (Bibliotheca Lindesiana) at Haigh Hall, Lancashire, which was formed and developed by Alexander and James Ludovic Lindsay.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>On the front pastedown, the armorial bookplate (Ex Libris) bearing the arms of the Earls of Crawford and Balcarres: Quarterly, 1st and 4th, Gules a fess chequy Argent and Azure. 2nd and 3rd, Or a lion rampant Gules, debruised of a ribbon in bend Sable. Crest: a swan’s head, neck, and wings proper, issuing from an antique ducal coronet Or. Supporters: two lions, rampant guardant Gules. Motto: <hi rend="italic">ENDURE FORT</hi> | <hi rend="italic">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</hi> | pencilled <hi rend="italic">L/4</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>The manuscript was purchased by Bernard Quaritch (1819-1899), bookseller and publisher, for Lord Lindsay for £250 at the Guglielmo Libri sale on 2 April 1859, the sixth day of the auction, lot 784 (Sotheby &amp; Wilkinson, 1859, page 174).</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>▪ Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908), philanthropist and founder of The John Rylands Library</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>Purchased by Enriqueta Rylands in 1901 from James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847-1913).</p>
                                                                                                                                <p><hi rend="bold">• Acquisition:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                <p>Bequeathed by Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908) in 1908 to The John Rylands Library.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Acquisition:</hi> 1908</p>
                                                                                                                                <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<provenance>
<p><name role="pat"><persName type="display">Lorenzo di Strozzi (-1400), nobleman of the influential Strozzi family</persName><persName type="standard">Strozzi, Lorenzo, -1400</persName></name></p>
<p>The colophon on <locus from="174r" to="174r">174r</locus> acknowledges Lorenzo Strozzi as the commissioner and Paolo as the scribe. It also includes a blessing for the wellbeing of both the patron and the scribe.</p>
<p>The lower borders on <locus from="3r" to="3r">3r</locus> and <locus from="105r" to="105r">105r</locus> bear the Strozzi family arms: <heraldry>Or, on a fess Gules, three crescent moons Argent</heraldry>.</p>
<p>Diagonal pencil inscription on the <locus from="Flyleaf_1r" to="Flyleaf_1r">flyleaf 1r</locus>: <hi rend="italic">Written for Lorenzo di Strozzi | circa 1520</hi>.</p>
</provenance>
<provenance>
<p><name source="#viaf" key="40150737" role="fmo"><persName type="display">Theodor Oswald Weigel (1812-1881), bookseller, art dealer, publisher, and collector</persName><persName type="standard">Weigel, T.O. (Theodor Oswald), 1812-1881 </persName></name></p>
<p>Stamped in gilt on the lower margin of the <locus from="Front_cover" to="Front_cover">front cover</locus>: the initials <hi rend="italic">T.O.W</hi>.</p>
</provenance>
<p><name source="#viaf" key="97751058" role="fmo"><persName type="display">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812-1880), book collector and writer on art</persName><persName type="standard">Crawford, Alexander Crawford Lindsay, 1812-1880</persName></name></p>
<p><name source="#viaf" key="9985420" role="fmo"><persName type="display">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847-1913), astronomer and book collector</persName><persName type="standard">Crawford, James Ludovic Lindsay, Earl of, 1847-1913</persName></name></p>
<p>Formerly in the Crawford Library (Bibliotheca Lindesiana) at Haigh Hall, Lancashire, which was formed and developed by Alexander and James Ludovic Lindsay.</p>
<p>On the <locus from="Inner_front_cover" to="Inner_front_cover">front pastedown</locus>, the armorial bookplate (Ex Libris), bearing the arms of the Earls of Crawford and Balcarres: <heraldry>Quarterly, 1st and 4th, Gules a fess chequy Argent and Azure. 2nd and 3rd, Or a lion rampant Gules, debruised of a ribbon in bend Sable. Crest: a swan’s head, neck, and wings proper, issuing from an antique ducal coronet Or. Supporters: two lions, rampant guardant Gules. Motto: <hi rend="italic">ENDURE FORT</hi></heraldry> |<hi rend="italic">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</hi> | pencilled <hi rend="italic">L/4</hi>.</p>
<p>The manuscript was purchased by <name source="#viaf" key="5679225" role="bsl"><persName type="display">Bernard Quaritch (1819-1899)</persName><persName type="standard">Quaritch, Bernard, 1819–1899</persName></name>, bookseller and publisher, for Lord Lindsay for £250 at the Guglielmo Libri sale on <date when="1859-04-02">2 April 1859</date>, the sixth day of the auction, lot 784 (Sotheby &amp; Wilkinson, 1859, page 174).</p>
</provenance>
<provenance>
<name role="fmo"><persName type="display">Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908), philanthropist and founder of The John Rylands Library</persName><persName type="standard">Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</persName></name></p>
<p>Purchased by Enriqueta Rylands in <date when="1901">1901</date> from James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847-1913).</p>
</provenance>
<acquisition>
<p>Bequeathed by <name role="dnr"><persName type="display">Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908)</persName><persName type="standard">Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</persName></name> in <date when="1908">1908</date> to <name source="#viaf" key="312795145" role="own"><orgName>The John Rylands Library</orgName></name>.</p>
</acquisition>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                              </row>
                                                                                                                            </table>
                                                                                                                            <p>It is quite rare for Spencer material to feature heraldic bookplates. More often, the arms of the Earls of Spencer appear stamped on the front cover of the binding. Evidence of Spencer provenance, usually indicating former ownership, is more commonly found in the form of a leather label pasted to the inner front cover or front pastedown.</p>
                                                                                                                            <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                              <row>
                                                                                                                                <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Former Owner(s):</hi> Nicolet, Jean Baptiste Thomas; Fréret, Nicolas, 1688-1749; Spencer, George John Spencer, Earl, 1758-1834; Spencer, John Poyntz Spencer, Earl, 1835-1910; Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p><hi rend="bold">• Donor(s):</hi> Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p><hi rend="bold">• Provenance:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>▪ Jean Baptiste Thomas Nicolet</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>Bookplate on the back pastedown: <hi rend="italic">EX LIBRIS Joannis Baptistæ Thomæ NICOLET</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>▪ Nicolas Fréret (1688-1749), historian and linguist</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>Manuscript inscription in the upper right corner of a1r: <hi rend="italic">N. Freret | # | 1710</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>▪ George John Spencer, 2nd Earl Spencer (1758-1834), politician and book collector</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>▪ John Poyntz Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer (1835-1910), politician and viceroy of Ireland</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>Formerly in the Spencer Library (Bibliotheca Spenceriana) at Althorp, Northamptonshire, largely assembled by George John Spencer and subsequently passing by descent to John Poyntz Spencer.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>Armorial binding with the arms of the Earls of Spencer, associated with the 2nd Earl Spencer on both the front back covers: Quarterly, 2nd and 3rd a fret Or, over all on a bend Sable three escallops Argent (Spencer), impaling Quarterly, 1st and 4th, a bend cotised between six crosses patty (Bingham), 2nd and 3rd, Ermine a lion rampant ducally crowned (Turberville). Supporters: a griffin and a wyvern erect on its tail, both collared and chained. Coronet of an Earl. Motto: <hi rend="italic">DIEU DEFEND LE DROIT</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>Oval leather label on the front pastedown: <hi rend="italic">E BIBLIOTHECA SPENCERIANA</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>▪ Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908), philanthropist and founder of The John Rylands Library</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>Purchased by Enriqueta Rylands in 1901 from John Poyntz Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer (1835-1910).</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p><hi rend="bold">• Acquisition:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>Donated by Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908) in 1899 to The John Rylands Library.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>On the front pastedown: the armorial bookplate of the John Rylands Library, with the Latin motto: NIHIL SINE LABORE.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>On the a1r:  a circular red stamp of The John Rylands Library, with the interlaced monogram: <hi rend="italic">JR</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Acquisition:</hi> 1899</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<provenance>
<p><name role="fmo"><persName type="display">Jean Baptiste Thomas Nicolet</persName><persName type="standard">Nicolet, Jean Baptiste Thomas</persName></name></p>
<p>Bookplate on the <locus from="Inner_back_cover" to="Inner_back_cover">back pastedown</locus>: <hi rend="italic">EX LIBRIS Joannis Baptistæ Thomæ NICOLET</hi>.</p>
</provenance>
<p><name source="#viaf" key="34456779" role="fmo"><persName type="display">Nicolas Fréret (1688-1749), historian and linguist</persName><persName type="standard">Fréret, Nicolas, 1688-1749 </persName></name></p>
<p>Manuscript inscription in the upper right corner of <locus from="a1r" to="a1r">a1r</locus>: <hi rend="italic">N. Freret | # | 1710</hi>.</p>
</provenance>
<p><name source="#viaf" key="17584030" role="fmo"><persName type="display">George John Spencer, 2nd Earl Spencer (1758-1834), politician and book collector</persName><persName type="standard">Spencer, George John Spencer, Earl, 1758-1834</persName></name></p>
<p><name source="#viaf" key="54160187" role="fmo"><persName type="display">John Poyntz Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer (1835-1910), politician and viceroy of Ireland</persName><persName type="standard">Spencer, John Poyntz Spencer, Earl, 1835-1910</persName></name></p>
<p>Formerly in the Spencer Library (Bibliotheca Spenceriana) at Althorp, Northamptonshire, largely assembled by George John Spencer and subsequently passing by descent to John Poyntz Spencer.</p>
<p>Armorial binding with the arms of the Earls of Spencer, associated with the 2nd Earl Spencer on both the <locus from="Front_cover" to="Front_cover">front</locus> and <locus from="Back_cover" to="Back_cover">back</locus> covers: <heraldry>Quarterly, 2nd and 3rd a fret Or, over all on a bend Sable three escallops Argent (Spencer), impaling Quarterly, 1st and 4th, a bend cotised between six crosses patty (Bingham), 2nd and 3rd, Ermine a lion rampant ducally crowned (Turberville). Supporters: a griffin and a wyvern erect on its tail, both collared and chained. Coronet of an Earl. Motto: <hi rend="italic">DIEU DEFEND LE DROIT</hi></heraldry>.</p>
<p>Oval leather label on the <locus from="Inner_front_cover" to="Inner_front_cover">front pastedown</locus>: <hi rend="italic">E BIBLIOTHECA SPENCERIANA</hi>.</p>
</provenance>
<provenance>
<name role="fmo"><persName type="display">Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908), philanthropist and founder of The John Rylands Library</persName><persName type="standard">Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</persName></name></p>
<p>Purchased by Enriqueta Rylands in <date when="1892">1892</date> from John Poyntz Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer (1835-1910).</p>
</provenance>
<provenance>
<name role="dnr"><persName type="display">Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908), philanthropist and founder of The John Rylands Library</persName><persName type="standard">Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</persName></name></p>
<p>Purchased by Enriqueta Rylands in <date when="1892">1892</date> from John Poyntz Spencer, 5th Earl Spencer (1835-1910).</p>
</provenance>
<acquisition>
<p>Donated by <name role="dnr"><persName type="display">Enriqueta Rylands (1843-1908)</persName><persName type="standard">Rylands, Enriqueta, 1843-1908</persName></name> in <date when="1899">1899</date> to <name source="#viaf" key="312795145" role="own"><orgName>The John Rylands Library</orgName></name>.</p>
<p>On the <locus from="Inner_front_cover" to="Inner_front_cover">front pastedown</locus>: the armorial bookplate of the John Rylands Library, with the Latin motto: <hi rend="italic">NIHIL SINE LABORE</hi>.</p>
<p>On <locus from="a1r" to="a1r">a1r</locus>: a circular red stamp of The John Rylands Library, with the interlaced monogram: <hi rend="italic">JR</hi>.</p>
</acquisition>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                </row>
                                                                                                                              </table>
                                                                                                                            </div>
                                                                                                                            <div xml:id="additional">
                                                                                                                              <head><code>&lt;additional&gt;</code> | additional</head>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-additional.html"><gi>additional</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(additional) groups additional information, combining bibliographic information about a manuscript or other object, or surrogate copies of it, with curatorial or administrative information.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>additional</gi> is used to record supplementary descriptive information that supports but falls outside the core intellectual, physical, and historical description of the item. This may include the source of the descriptive metadata, access and availability conditions, custodial history, references to surrogate copies or facsimiles, and relevant bibliographic citations.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>additional</gi> appears immediately after <gi>history</gi> and forms the final component of <gi>msDesc</gi>, unless <gi>msPart</gi> is present, and may include the following elements where relevant:</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<teiHeader>
<fileDesc>|<titleStmt>|<publicationStmt>|<sourceDesc>|<msDesc>|
<msContents>|<physDesc> |<history>
<additional>
<adminInfo>
<!-- Metadata about relating to the curation and management of an item -->
<!-- Contains <recordHist> | <availability> | <custodialHist> -->
</adminInfo>
<surrogates>
<!-- Metadata linking to digital facsimiles -->
<!-- N/A to MDC - only used in online catalogues: FIHRIST + Bodleian Medieval -->
</surrogates>
<listBibl>
<!-- Metadata bibliographic references listing referring to the item -->
<!-- Contains <bibl> and <ref> -->
</listBibl>
</additional>
</msDesc>|</sourceDesc>|</fileDesc>|<encodingDesc>|<profileDesc>|<revisionDesc>
</teiHeader>]]></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                            </div>
                                                                                                                            <div xml:id="adminInfo">
                                                                                                                              <head><code>&lt;adminInfo&gt;</code> | administrative information</head>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-adminInfo.html"><gi>adminInfo</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(administrative information) contains information about the present custody and availability of the manuscript or other object, and also about the record description itself.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>adminInfo</gi> is used to record information relating to the curation and management of the item described. It commonly includes source attribution and revision history, access and availability conditions, usage guidance, and details concerning the custody or public display of the physical object, as defined by the holding institution.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>In MDC, <gi>adminInfo</gi> is not displayed in the public interface. As administrative metadata, it is suppressed in the public-facing view but remains essential and should be recorded consistently, following the standards and guidance defined below. The aim is to keep the interface focused on descriptive and interpretive information, while administrative content remains accessible only through the <hi rend="bold">Download Metadata</hi> option, which provides full access to the complete TEI output.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>This information is typically structured using the elements <gi>recordHist</gi> for the source, attribution, and revision of the description, <gi>availability</gi> for access conditions and usage notes, and <gi>custodialHist</gi> for institutional custody or exhibition history.</p>
                                                                                                                            </div>
                                                                                                                            <div xml:id="recordHist-source">
                                                                                                                              <head><code>&lt;recordHist&gt;</code> | recorded history | <code>&lt;source&gt;</code> | source</head>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-recordHist.html"><gi>recordHist</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(recorded history) provides information about the source and revision status of the parent manuscript or object description itself.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-source.html"><gi>source</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(source) describes the original source for the information contained with a manuscript or object description.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>source</gi> within <gi>recordHist</gi> is used to record the origin of the descriptive metadata. It refers to earlier catalogues, handlists, or other sources on which the current description is based. This is particularly relevant where the description draws on or updates previous cataloguing. It provides transparency about how the description was constructed and supports attribution of earlier descriptive work.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>In MDC, <gi>source</gi> is treated as internal source metadata and is <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> intended for public display. It serves as a form of metadata provenance and is used primarily for internal or scholarly reference.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>Typically, <gi>source</gi> refers to a source on which the description is based, whether published or unpublished, and is cited using a brief author–date reference. If the description has been editorially revised, this should be noted. Include your name only if you have substantively revised or expanded the description. Full bibliographic details should not be included in this element. Instead, the cited source must also be referenced in <gi>listBibl</gi>, using <gi>bibl</gi> that contains complete publication details.</p>
                                                                                                                              <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                <row>
                                                                                                                                  <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Data Source(s):</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                    <p>Description based on Tyson (1930), revised and expanded by Ourania Karapasia.</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><recordHist>
<source>
<p>Description based on Tyson (1930), revised and expanded by Ourania Karapasia.</p>
</source>
</recordHist></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                                    <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Il Canzoniere di Petrarca e Le Rime di Dante</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-ITALIAN-00001/1">Italian MS 1</ref></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                </row>
                                                                                                                              </table>
                                                                                                                            </div>
                                                                                                                            <div xml:id="availability">
                                                                                                                              <head><code>&lt;availability&gt;</code> | availability</head>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-availability.html"><gi>availability</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(availability) supplies information about the availability of a text, for example any restrictions on its use or distribution, its copyright status, any licence applying to it, etc.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>availability</gi> is used to provide information about the availability and access conditions of the physical item, including any restrictions, consultation arrangements, and relevant contact details.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>In MDC, <gi>availability</gi> usually contains a standard statement for material held by The John Rylands Library. This statement is treated as boilerplate and should be used consistently across TEI files unless institutional guidance changes or the item belongs to an external institution with different access conditions. Here, <att>status</att>=<val>restricted</val> indicates that access restrictions apply, as is standard for Special Collections material.</p>
                                                                                                                              <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                <row>
                                                                                                                                  <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><adminInfo>
<availability status="restricted">
<p>The item is available for consultation by any accredited reader.</p>
<p>For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see <ref target="https://www.library.manchester.ac.uk/rylands/special-collections/using-the-reading-rooms/john-rylands-library/">Using Special Collections at The John Rylands Library</ref>.</p>
<p>For further information on the availability of the item, please contact the <ref target="uml.special-collections@manchester.ac.uk">Special Collections Reader Services</ref>.</p>
</availability>
</adminInfo></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                                  <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Il Canzoniere di Petrarca e Le Rime di Dante</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-ITALIAN-00001/1">Italian MS 1</ref></p></cell>
                                                                                                                              </row>
                                                                                                                            </table>
                                                                                                                          </div>
                                                                                                                          <div xml:id="custodialHist">
                                                                                                                            <head><code>&lt;custodialHist&gt;</code> | custodial history</head>
                                                                                                                            <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-custodialHist.html"><gi>custodialHist</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(custodial history) contains a description of a manuscript or other object's custodial history, either as running prose or as a series of dated custodial events.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                            <p><gi>custodialHist</gi> is used to describe the custodial history of an item, recording any significant events noted during the period that it has been located within its holding institution. It may contain either a series of <gi>p</gi> or a sequence of <gi>custEvent</gi>, each describing a distinct incident or event.</p>
                                                                                                                          </div>
                                                                                                                          <div xml:id="custEvent">
                                                                                                                            <head><code>&lt;custEvent&gt;</code> | custodial event</head>
                                                                                                                            <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-custEvent.html"><gi>custEvent</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(custodial event) describes a single event during the custodial history of a manuscript or other object.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                            <p><gi>custEvent</gi> within <gi>custodialHist</gi> is used to record a single, dated custodial action or incident involving the item, primarily during its time in the care of the current institution. It is typically used to record conservation treatment or exhibition history, whether the item was featured as part of an internal or external exhibition.</p>
                                                                                                                            <p><gi>custEvent</gi> is repeatable and must contain at least one <gi>p</gi>. Each <gi>custEvent</gi> may include a descriptive statement, a responsible agency, and a date. The nature of the event can be recorded using <att>type</att>, with values such as <val>conservation</val> and <val>exhibition</val>. Other values may be used where appropriate, but usage should remain consistent across files. It should also have at least one dating attribute, such as <att>when</att>, <att>notBefore</att>, <att>notAfter</att>, or <att>from</att>, <att>to</att>, to indicate the date or date range of the event.</p>
                                                                                                                            <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                              <row>
                                                                                                                                <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<custodialHist>
<custEvent type="exhibition" from="2012-06-19" to="2012-11-04">
<p>Exhibited in <ref target="https://www.uffizi.it/en/events/gleam-gold-gothic-uffizi-2012">Bagliori dorati. Il Gotico Internazionale a Firenze 1375–1440</ref></title> (The Gleam of Gold. The International Gothic Style in Florence 1375–1440), Uffizi Gallery, Florence, 19 June to 4 November 2012.</p>
</custEvent>
</custodialHist>]]></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                                <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Il Canzoniere di Petrarca e Le Rime di Dante</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-ITALIAN-00001/1">Italian MS 1</ref></p></cell>
                                                                                                                            </row>
                                                                                                                            <row>
                                                                                                                              <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><custodialHist>
<custEvent type="conservation" notBefore="2023-11-01" to="2024-10-14">
<p>Conserved between 1 November 2023 and 14 October 2024 by Heather Garner and Zoë Lanceley at the conservation studio of The John Rylands Library.</p>
</custEvent>
</custodialHist></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Esther scroll</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-HEBREW-00054/1">Hebrew MS 54</ref></p></cell>
                                                                                                                          </row>
                                                                                                                          <row>
                                                                                                                            <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><custodialHist>
<custEvent type="digitisation" when="2026-03-26">
<p>Digitised on 26 March 2026 by Jo Castle at the Rylands Heritage Imaging Lab of The John Rylands Library as part of the X Project.</p>
</custEvent>
</custodialHist></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                          </row>
                                                                                                                        </table>
                                                                                                                      </div>
                                                                                                                      <div xml:id="surrogates">
                                                                                                                        <head><code>&lt;surrogates&gt;</code> | surrogates</head>
                                                                                                                        <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-surrogates.html"><gi>surrogates</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(surrogates) contains information about any representations of the manuscript or other object being described which may exist in the holding institution or elsewhere.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                        <p><gi>surrogates</gi> is not relevant in MDC, where each digital resource consists of a TEI XML file describing a physical item, linked directly to a set of digital facsimile images using <gi>facsimile</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                        <p>The use of <gi>surrogates</gi> applies only in other TEI frameworks, such as FIHRIST and the Bodleian Medieval, where it is used to reference or link to digital facsimiles hosted independently of the catalogue. Such information is typically recorded using <gi>bibl</gi> with <att>type</att>=<val>digital-facsimile</val>, followed by <att>subtype</att> with values <val>full</val>, where a manuscript has been digitised in its entirety, or <val>partial</val>, where only selected leaves are digitised.</p>
                                                                                                                        <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                          <row>
                                                                                                                            <cell><p>Digital Images</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><hi rend="italic">Manchester Digital Collections</hi> (full digital resource)</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><surrogates>
<bibl type="digital-facsimile" subtype="full">
<ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-PERSIAN-00051">Manchester Digital Collections</ref>.
<note>(full digital resource).</note>
</bibl>
</surrogates></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">An album of paintings and calligraphic specimens</hi>: <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7005">Persian MS 51</ref></p></cell>
                                                                                                                          </row>
                                                                                                                        </table>
                                                                                                                      </div>
                                                                                                                      <div xml:id="listBibl">
                                                                                                                        <head><code>&lt;listBibl&gt;</code> | citation list</head>
                                                                                                                        <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-listBibl.html"><gi>listBibl</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(citation list) contains a list of bibliographic citations of any kind.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                        <p><gi>listBibl</gi> within <gi>additional</gi> provides a container for bibliographic references to external sources in which the item has been identified, listed, or described. It may include a reference to the publicly available institutional catalogue record, serving as an access point for discovery and indicating where an authoritative bibliographic record is available.</p>
                                                                                                                        <p>Depending on the collection and material type, this may take the form of an entry in Library Search (Primo), <ref target="https://search.worldcat.org/">WorldCat</ref> (worldwide union catalogue), <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/about">FIHRIST</ref> (union catalogue of manuscripts from the Islamicate world), <ref target="https://medieval.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/">Medieval Manuscripts in Oxford Libraries</ref>, or other relevant union catalogues, directories, or finding aids such as <ref target="https://archiveshub.jisc.ac.uk/">Archives Hub</ref> (UK gateway to archive descriptions).</p>
                                                                                                                        <p>In addition, <gi>listBibl</gi> records references to external catalogues, bibliographies, and scholarly resources, including printed short-title catalogues, collection-specific descriptive catalogues, exhibition catalogues, and major reference databases such as <ref target="https://edit16.iccu.sbn.it/en/">EDIT16</ref> (Edizioni Italiane del XVI Secolo), <ref target="https://data.cerl.org/istc/_search">ISTC</ref> (Incunabula Short Title Catalogue), <ref target="https://incunables.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/">Bod-Inc Online</ref> (Bodleian Libraries’ Incunable Catalogue), <ref target="https://www.trismegistos.org/">Trismegistos</ref> (interdisciplinary portal of papyrological and epigraphical resources), <ref target="https://pinakes.irht.cnrs.fr/">Pinakes</ref> (IRHT database of Greek Manuscripts online), <ref target="https://cdli.earth/">CDLI</ref> (Cuneiform Digital Library Initiative).</p>
                                                                                                                        <p>Each reference within <gi>listBibl</gi> is encoded using a <gi>bibl</gi>, which represents a single bibliographic citation.</p>
                                                                                                                        <p>Bibliographical information relating to the item as a whole should be recorded within <gi>additional</gi>, typically using <gi>listBibl</gi>. Where bibliographical references apply only to an individual text or component described in the record, <gi>bibl</gi>, or <gi>listBibl</gi> if multiple citations are required, may instead be recorded within the relevant <gi>msItem</gi> or <gi>msPart</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                      </div>
                                                                                                                      <div xml:id="bibl">
                                                                                                                        <head><code>&lt;bibl&gt;</code> | bibliographic citation</head>
                                                                                                                        <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-bibl.html"><gi>bibl</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(bibliographic citation) contains a loosely-structured bibliographic citation of which the sub-components may or may not be explicitly tagged.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                        <p><gi>bibl</gi> within <gi>listBibl</gi> is used to record a single catalogue entry, bibliography, database record, exhibition catalogue, or scholarly publication. The citation may be encoded as plain text or with more granular tagging, depending on the level of structure required by the project framework.</p>
                                                                                                                        <p><gi>bibl</gi> entries should, wherever possible, be listed in chronological order, from the earliest dated source to the most recent, reflecting the development of the item’s bibliographic record over time. In MDC, references may ideally be grouped by type, with the institutional catalogue record listed first, such as Library Search or FIHRIST, followed by major reference databases including ISTC, EDIT16, and then printed catalogues and scholarship arranged in chronological order from oldest to newest.</p>
                                                                                                                        <p>This ordering should be followed when creating new TEI files. However, as is often the case with MARC-derived metadata, the order of entries may initially reflect the structure or sequence of the source Alma record. In such cases, the original arrangement may be retained at the point of conversion, but entries should be reordered and standardised wherever feasible, in line with the MDC framework.</p>
                                                                                                                        <p>Where available, a <gi>bibl</gi> entry should include a link to the cited resource using <gi>ref</gi> with a <att>target</att> supplying the URL. This enables the bibliography to serve both as a citation and as a direct access point to an external catalogue record or electronic resource, such as <ref target="https://search.worldcat.org/">WorldCat</ref> or another authoritative database.</p>
                                                                                                                        <p>The bibliographic references should follow the citation style of the Modern Language Association (MLA) 8th or 9th edition. For example, an Alma record may appear in Primo as: Adams, H. M. Catalogue of Books Printed on the Continent of Europe, 1501–1600, in Cambridge Libraries, D84. In MDC, this would be encoded as:</p>
                                                                                                                        <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                          <row>
                                                                                                                            <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Bibliography:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Adams, Herbert Mayow. Catalogue of books printed on the Continent of Europe, 1501-1600, in Cambridge Libraries.   University  Press, 1967, D84</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><listBibl>
<bibl><ref target="https://search.worldcat.org/en/title/892641">Adams, Herbert Mayow. Catalogue of books printed on the Continent of Europe, 1501-1600, in Cambridge Libraries. University Press, 1967, D84</ref></bibl>
</listBibl></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                            </row>
                                                                                                                          </table>
                                                                                                                          <p>The following format should be used in MDC to record a link to the University of Manchester Library Search record in Primo:</p>
                                                                                                                          <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                            <row>
                                                                                                                              <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Bibliography:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Recorded in University of Manchester Library Search</p>
                                                                                                                                <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><listBibl>
<bibl>Recorded in University of Manchester <ref target="https://www.librarysearch.manchester.ac.uk/permalink/44MAN_INST/elks2a/alma9913563574401631">Library Search</ref></bibl>
</listBibl></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                              </row>
                                                                                                                            </table>
                                                                                                                            <p>The following format should be used in MDC when linking to an external catalogue record such as FIHRIST:</p>
                                                                                                                            <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                              <row>
                                                                                                                                <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Bibliography:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                  <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Catalogue record in Fihrist</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<listBibl>
<bibl>Catalogue record in <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6964">FIHRIST</ref></bibl>
/ref></bibl>
</listBibl>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                </row>
                                                                                                                              </table>
                                                                                                                              <p>The following examples demonstrate the standard MDC format for recording bibliographic references within <gi>listBibl</gi>, with database entries followed by printed scholarship arranged chronologically.</p>
                                                                                                                              <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                <row>
                                                                                                                                  <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Bibliography:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Trismegistos: TM 6947</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Mertens-Pack 3 Online: MP³ 1106</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Hunt, Arthur Surridge. Catalogue of the Greek Papyri in the John Rylands Library, Manchester, Volume I, Literary Texts. Manchester University Press, 1911, page 91</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> West, Martin Litchfield. Homerus, Odyssea. Bibliotheca Scriptorum Graecorum et Romanorum Teubneriana. De Gruyter, 2017</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><listBibl>
<bibl>Trismegistos: <ref target="http://www.trismegistos.org/text/60947">TM 60947</ref></bibl>
<bibl>Mertens-Pack 3 Online: <ref target="http://www.cedopalmp3.uliege.be/cdp_MP3_display.aspx?numNot=01106.000">MP³ 1106</ref></bibl>
<bibl><ref target="https://archive.org/details/catalogueofgreek01johnuoft/page/90">Hunt, Arthur Surridge. Catalogue of the Greek Papyri in the John Rylands Library, Manchester, Volume I,
Literary Texts. Manchester University Press, 1911, page 91</ref></bibl>
<bibl><ref target="https://search.worldcat.org/title/1008765676">West, Martin Litchfield. Homerus, Odyssea. Bibliotheca Scriptorum Graecorum et Romanorum Teubneriana. De Gruyter, 2017</ref></bibl>
</listBibl></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                                    <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Odyssey</hi>: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-GREEK-P-00053/1">Greek P 53</ref></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                </row>
                                                                                                                                <row>
                                                                                                                                  <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Bibliography:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Recorded in University of Manchester Library Search</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Bodleian Libraries. Bod-Inc Online: D–008</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> British Library. Incunabula Short Title Catalogue (ISTC): id00025000</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Staatsbibliothek zu Berlin. Gesamtkatalog der Wiegendrucke (GW): 7961</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Dibdin, Thomas Frognall. Bibliotheca Spenceriana, or, A descriptive catalogue of the books printed in the fifteenth century, lately forming part of the library of the Duke di Cassano Serra, and now the property of George John, earl Spencer. With a general index of authors and editions contained in the present volume, and in the Bibliotheca Spenceriana and Aedes Althorpianae. W. Nicol, Shakespeare Press, 1823, volume 7, no. 68, page 44</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> John Rylands Library, and Henry Guppy. Catalogue of an exhibition of the works of Dante Alighieri shown in the John Rylands Library from March to October, MCMIX. Printed by order of the Governors, 1909, no. 8 (case 1), page 5</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Mambelli, Giuliano. Gli annali delle edizioni dantesche: con XLVI tavole fuori testo. N. Zanichelli, 1931, 6</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">•</hi> Goff, Frederick Richmond. Incunabula in American libraries: a third census of fifteenth-century books recorded in North American collections. Bibliographical Society of America, 1964, D25</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><listBibl>
<bibl>Recorded in University of Manchester <ref target="https://www.librarysearch.manchester.ac.uk/permalink/44MAN_INST/elks2a/alma9913563574401631">Library Search</ref></bibl>
<bibl>Bodleian Libraries. Bod-Inc Online: <ref target="http://incunables.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/record/D-008">D-008</ref></bibl>
<bibl>British Library. Incunabula Short Title Catalogue (ISTC): <ref target="https://data.cerl.org/istc/id00025000">id00025000</ref></bibl>
<bibl>Staatsbibliothek zu Berlin. Gesamtkatalog der Wiegendrucke (GW): <ref target="https://gesamtkatalogderwiegendrucke.de/docs/GW07961.htm">7961</ref></bibl>
<bibl><ref target="https://search.worldcat.org/title/1113560586">Dibdin, Thomas Frognall. Bibliotheca Spenceriana, or, A descriptive catalogue of the books printed in the fifteenth century, lately forming part of the library of the Duke di Cassano Serra, and now the property of George John, earl Spencer. With a general index of authors and editions contained in the present volume, and in the Bibliotheca Spenceriana and Aedes Althorpianae. W. Nicol, Shakespeare Press, 1823, volume 7, no. 68, page 44</ref></bibl>
<bibl><ref target="https://search.worldcat.org/en/title/32020074">John Rylands Library, and Henry Guppy. Catalogue of an exhibition of the works of Dante Alighieri shown in the John Rylands Library from March to October, MCMIX. Printed by order of the Governors, 1909, no. 8 (case 1), page 5</ref></bibl>
<bibl><ref target="https://search.worldcat.org/en/title/250057050">Mambelli, Giuliano. Gli annali delle edizioni dantesche: con XLVI tavole fuori testo. N. Zanichelli, 1931, 6</ref></bibl>
<bibl><ref target="https://search.worldcat.org/title/245837069">Goff, Frederick Richmond. Incunabula in American libraries: a third census of fifteenth-century books recorded in North
American collections. Bibliographical Society of America, 1964, D25 </ref></bibl>
</listBibl></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                                    <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Incominciano le cantiche de la Comedia di Dante Alleghieri firentino</hi>: <hi rend="bold"><ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-INCU-18321/1">18321</ref></hi></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                </row>
                                                                                                                              </table>
                                                                                                                              <p>Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> end <gi>bibl</gi> with a full stop. Spell out <hi rend="italic">page</hi> and <hi rend="italic">pages</hi> in full rather than using abbreviated forms such as <hi rend="italic">p.</hi> or <hi rend="italic">pp</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><hi rend="bold">Optional workflow: importing bibliographic references from Zotero</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p>Where bibliographical references are already maintained in <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/">Zotero</ref>, they may be exported in TEI format and incorporated into <gi>listBibl</gi>. This is an optional workflow and should only be used where the encoder is confident in reviewing and normalising the exported XML.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>Bibliographic entries can be exported from Zotero in TEI format as follows:</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>— Open Zotero and navigate to the relevant shelfmark folder.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>— Select all entries within the folder, then right-click and select <hi rend="italic">Export Items</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>— Select the export format TEI. Ensure that the following options are enabled (ticked): <hi rend="italic">Export Notes</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Generate XML IDs</hi>, and <hi rend="italic">Full TEI Document</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>— Save the XML file in an appropriate location and open it in Oxygen.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>— Apply formatting and indentation. Click the Format and Indent button (or press CTRL+SHIFT+P).</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>After export, the XML will require editorial refinement:</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>— Remove page references encoded within &lt;note&gt; that do not relate to the specific item being described. These can be verified by checking the shelfmark references within Zotero.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>— Use CTRL+F to replace all <gi>note</gi> that represent citation ranges with <gi>citedRange</gi>. Ensure both opening and closing tags are updated.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>— Rearrange entries into chronological order. Bibliographic entries are typically encoded as <gi>biblStruct</gi> within <gi>listBibl</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>— Once normalised, copy <gi>listBibl</gi> and its contents into the appropriate location within <gi>additional</gi> in the TEI header.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>In practice, <gi>biblStruct</gi> is preferable where full bibliographic structure is required, with discrete elements for authors, titles, publication details, and identifiers. Within MDC TEI, the choice between <gi>bibl</gi> and <gi>biblStruct</gi> should depend on whether a simple citation is sufficient or whether a fully structured, machine-processable representation is needed.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>For further detail on the encoding of bibliographic citations and references, including alternative modelling approaches and more granular structures, consult the TEI Guidelines for Electronic Text Encoding and Interchange, section <ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/CO.html">3.12 Bibliographic Citations and References</ref>.</p>
                                                                                                                            </div>
                                                                                                                            <div xml:id="msPart">
                                                                                                                              <head><code>&lt;msPart&gt;</code> | manuscript part</head>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-msPart.html"><gi>msPart</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(manuscript part) contains information about an originally distinct manuscript or part of a manuscript, which is now part of a composite manuscript.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>msPart</gi> is used for composite manuscripts, that is, manuscripts comprising two or more originally distinct parts now kept together as a single unit. Definitions and understandings of composite manuscripts vary across codicological traditions, but the element is generally used when a single item contains multiple distinct parts that require separate description.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>Although the element name refers to manuscripts, <gi>msPart</gi> may also be used to describe multi-part, composite, and similar structures across a range of Special Collections materials, such as photograph albums, scrapbooks, and compilations containing works by different authors or dealing with different subjects.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>Structurally, each &lt;<code>msPart&gt;</code> follows the same general model as <gi>msDesc</gi> and may include elements such as <gi>msIdentifier</gi>, <gi>msContents</gi>, <gi>physDesc</gi>, <gi>history</gi>, and <gi>additional</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><msDesc>
<msIdentifier/>
<head/>
<msContents/>
<physDesc/>
<history/>
<additional/>
<msPart n="1">
<!-- first distinct part -->
<msIdentifier/>
<msContents/>
<physDesc/>
<history/>
<additional/>
</msPart>
<msPart n="2">
<!-- second distinct part -->
<msIdentifier/>
<msContents/>
<physDesc/>
<history/>
<additional/>
</msPart>
</msDesc></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                              <p>When <gi>msPart</gi> is used, <gi>msDesc</gi> must have <gi>head</gi> to provide the overarching title for the entire item. Without it, the MDC interface will <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> prioritise or even display a title at all. This does not replace the structural requirements of <gi>msContents</gi>, which must still contain at least one <gi>msItem</gi> with a <gi>title</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>msPart</gi> should have its own <gi>msIdentifier</gi> with <gi>idno</gi> to record the identifier of that part, in addition to <gi>msIdentifier</gi> provided for the item as a whole within <gi>msDesc</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>Each <gi>msPart</gi> should be numbered using <att>n</att> and may include <att>xml:id</att>. While optional in TEI, the use of <att>xml:id</att>. is recommended for composite items in order to provide a stable identifier for each structural part and to support citation, linking, indexing, and internal referencing.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="attHead"><code>&lt;msPart&gt; @xml:id</code></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><hi rend="bold"><att>xml:id</att></hi> derives from the unique identifier of the physical item and matches the XML filename.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>Where <att>xml:id</att> is used on <gi>msPart</gi>, the identifier should extend the XML filename using a suffix corresponding to the part identifier, for example, <code>-A</code>, <code>-B</code>, <code>-C</code>, or <code>-1</code>, <code>-2</code>, <code>-3</code>. This convention provides a persistent identifier for each component of a composite item.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="MS-LATIN-000XX">
<teiHeader>
<fileDesc>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<sourceDesc>
<msDesc>
<msIdentifier>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<idno>Latin MS XX</idno>
</msIdentifier>
<head/>
<msContents>
<summary/>
<msItem>
<!-- top-level <msItem> | additional metadata-->
</msItem>
</msContents>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<additional/>
<msPart n="1" xml:id="MS-LATIN-000XX-A">
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msPart>
<msPart n="2" xml:id="MS-LATIN-000XX-B">
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msPart>
<msPart n="3" xml:id="MS-LATIN-000XX-C">
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msPart>
</msDesc>
</sourceDesc>
</fileDesc>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</teiHeader>]]></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>msPart</gi> is used to describe distinct physical or structural parts of the item, whereas <gi>msItem</gi> is used to describe the intellectual or content units contained within those parts.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>msContents</gi> within <gi>msPart</gi> must contain at least one <gi>msItem</gi>. This part-level <gi>msItem</gi> will normally include <gi>locus</gi> to indicate the folio or page range where the part occurs. One or more nested <gi>msItem</gi> should then be numbered using <att>n</att> and should include <gi>locus</gi> to indicate where each textual unit begins and ends within that range.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>textLang</gi> within the top-level <gi>msItem</gi> within <gi>msDesc</gi> must have <att>mainLang</att> and, where applicable, <att>otherLangs</att>, providing the language statement for the item as a whole. Within <gi>msPart</gi>, the part-level <gi>msItem</gi> must also include <gi>textLang</gi> to record the language of that part. Each nested <gi>msItem</gi> should repeat <gi>textLang</gi> where necessary to maintain accurate language identification and display.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><msPart n="1" xml:id="MS-LATIN-000XX-A">
<msIdentifier>
<idno>Latin MS XX A</idno>
</msIdentifier>
<msContents>
<msItem>
<locus from="1r" to="30v">1r-30v</locus>
<!-- part-level <msItem> -->
<title>title of this part</title>
<textLang mainLang="lat" otherLangs="ara">Latin and Arabic</textLang>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<msItem n="1">
<!-- first nested <msItem> -->
<locus from="1r" to="20v">1r-20v</locus>
<title>title of this unit</title>
<textLang mainLang="lat">Latin</textLang>
</msItem>
<msItem n="2">
<!-- second nested <msItem> -->
<locus from="21r" to="30v">21r-30v</locus>
<title>title of this unit</title>
<textLang mainLang="ara">Arabic</textLang>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msItem>
</msItem>
</msContents>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msPart></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                              <p>Each <gi>msItem</gi> may include <att>xml:id</att>, depending on project requirements. See also &lt;msItem&gt; @xml:id  &lt;!--insert hyperlink--&gt; .</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<msPart n="1" xml:id="MS-LATIN-000XX-A">
<!-- first distinct part -->
<!-- additional metadata-->
<msContents>
<msItem>
<locus from="1r" to="30v">1r-30v</locus>
<!-- part-level <msItem> -->
<!-- additional metadata-->
<msItem n="1" xml:id="MS-LATIN-000XX-A-item1">
<!-- first nested <msItem> -->
<locus from="1r" to="20v">1r-20v</locus>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msItem>
<msItem n="2" xml:id="MS-LATIN-000XX-A-item2">
<!-- second nested <msItem> -->
<locus from="21r" to="30v">21r-30v</locus>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msItem>
</msItem
</msContents>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msPart>]]></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                              <p>The remainder of <gi>msPart</gi> follows the same encoding principles as the general <gi>msDesc</gi> model and may include the same core components, such as <gi>physDesc</gi>, <gi>history</gi>, and <gi>additional</gi>, together with their subordinate elements and attributes wherever applicable.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>Information that applies to the entire item should be recorded at the <gi>msDesc</gi> level rather than repeated within individual <gi>msPart</gi>. For example, features common to all parts, such as <gi>binding</gi> of a codex, are encoded in <gi>physDesc</gi> within <gi>msDesc</gi>. Similarly, <gi>extent</gi> at the <gi>msDesc</gi> level may record the total number of leaves for the complete item, while each <gi>msPart</gi> may include its own <gi>extent</gi> to specify the number of leaves within that part.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>Where the original item survives only as separate fragments rather than as a single physical object, <gi>msFrag</gi> may be used.</p>
                                                                                                                            </div>
                                                                                                                            <div xml:id="msFrag">
                                                                                                                              <head><code>&lt;msFrag&gt;</code> | manuscript fragment</head>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-msFrag.html"><gi>msFrag</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(manuscript fragment) contains information about a fragment described in relation to a prior context, typically as a description of a virtual reconstruction of a manuscript or other object whose fragments were catalogued separately</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>msFrag</gi> within <gi>msDesc</gi> may be used where an item no longer survives as a single physical unit, but only as fragments that once formed part of the same item. For example, this may apply where several detached fragments are understood to have come from the same manuscript of Homer’s Odyssey.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>Structurally, <gi>msFrag</gi> follows the same general model as <gi>msPart</gi>, and may include elements such as <gi>msIdentifier</gi>, <gi>msContents</gi>, <gi>physDesc</gi>, <gi>history</gi>, and <gi>additional</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>The main difference between <gi>msFrag</gi> and <gi>msPart</gi> is one of meaning: <gi>msPart</gi> describes parts that are now physically combined, while <gi>msFrag</gi> describes fragments that are now physically separate.</p>
                                                                                                                            </div>
                                                                                                                            <div xml:id="encodingDesc">
                                                                                                                              <head><code>&lt;encodingDesc&gt;</code> | encoding description</head>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-encodingDesc.html"><gi>encodingDesc</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(encoding description) documents the relationship between an electronic text and the source or sources from which it was derived.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>encodingDesc</gi> is the second major subdivision of <gi>teiHeader</gi>. In MDC, it serves two primary functions. Where relevant, it may provide contextual information about the project or purpose for which the digital resource has been created. More importantly, it records the source of persistent identifiers drawn from recognised controlled vocabularies and authority files whenever these are used within <gi>teiHeader</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>encodingDesc</gi> may contain the following elements, as applicable:</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<teiHeader>
<fileDesc>|<titleStmt>|<publicationStmt>|<sourceDesc>|<msDesc>|
<msContents>|<physDesc>|<history>|<additional>|</msDesc>|</sourceDesc>|</fileDesc>
<encodingDesc>
<projectDesc>
<!-- Metadata describing the background and scope of the project -->
<!-- Contains <p> -->
</projectDesc>
<classDecl>
<!-- Metadata declaring controlled vocabularies and authority sources -->
<!-- Contains <taxonomy>, <bibl> and <ref> -->
</classDecl>
</encodingDesc>
<profileDesc>|<revisionDesc>
</teiHeader>]]></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                            </div>
                                                                                                                            <div xml:id="projectDesc">
                                                                                                                              <head><code>&lt;projectDesc&gt;</code> | project description</head>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-projectDesc.html"><gi>projectDesc</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(project description) describes in detail the aim or purpose for which an electronic file was encoded, together with any other relevant information concerning the process by which it was assembled or collected.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Project Information</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>projectDesc</gi> may be used to provide contextual information about the project framework of the digital resource, outlining its aims, scope, funding context, and institutional setting.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>The content of <gi>projectDesc</gi> is generally informed by the project lead and is typically expressed in prose using one or more <gi>p</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                <row>
                                                                                                                                  <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Project Information:</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                    <p>Created as part of the AHRC-funded research project: “Envisioning Dante, c. 1472-c. 1630: Seeing and Reading the Early Printed Page” (AH/W005220/1), on the Dante Alighieri early printed editions held at The John Rylands Research Institute and Library, led by Professor Guyda Armstrong (Principal Investigator, School of Arts, Languages and Cultures, The University of Manchester); Professor Simon Gilson (Co-Investigator, Faculty of Medieval and Modern Languages, University of Oxford); Dr Giles Bergel, Research Fellow (Visual Geometry Group, Department of Engineering Science, University of Oxford); Dr Rebecca Bowen, Postdoctoral Research Associate (Faculty of Medieval and Modern Languages, University of Oxford), and Dr Gloria Moorman (School of Arts, Languages and Cultures, The University of Manchester).</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><projectDesc>
<p>Created as part of the AHRC-funded research project: "Envisioning Dante, c. 1472-c. 1630: Seeing and Reading the Early Printed Page" (AH/W005220/1), on the Dante Alighieri early printed editions held at The John Rylands Research Institute and Library, led by Professor Guyda Armstrong (Principal Investigator, School of Arts, Languages and Cultures, The University of Manchester); Professor Simon Gilson (Co-Investigator, Faculty of Medieval and Modern Languages, University of Oxford); Dr Giles Bergel, Research Fellow (Visual Geometry Group, Department of Engineering Science, University of Oxford); Dr Rebecca Bowen, Postdoctoral Research Associate (Faculty of Medieval and Modern Languages, University of Oxford), and Dr Gloria Moorman (School of Arts, Languages and Cultures, The University of Manchester).
</p>
</projectDesc></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                                    <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Le terze rime di Dante: <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/PR-ALDI-18873/1">18873</ref></hi></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                </row>
                                                                                                                              </table>
                                                                                                                            </div>
                                                                                                                            <div xml:id="classDecl">
                                                                                                                              <head><code>&lt;classDecl&gt;</code> | classification declarations</head>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-classDecl.html"><gi>classDecl</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(classification declarations) contains one or more taxonomies defining any classificatory codes used elsewhere in the text.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>classDecl</gi> within <gi>encodingDesc</gi> serves as a container in which classification systems, controlled vocabularies, taxonomies, and authority files are declared. It does not contain the individual authority identifiers. Instead, it declares the authority sources from which those identifiers are taken.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>When <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> are used together on relevant elements, <att>source</att> specifies the controlled vocabulary, authority source, or taxonomy being used, while <att>key</att> provides the identifier taken from that source. The value of <att>source</att> must correspond to a <gi>taxonomy</gi> declared within <gi>classDecl</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>classDecl</gi> contains one or more <gi>taxonomy</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                            </div>
                                                                                                                            <div xml:id="taxonomy">
                                                                                                                              <head><code>&lt;taxonomy&gt;</code> | taxonomy</head>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-taxonomy.html"><gi>taxonomy</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(taxonomy) defines a typology either implicitly, by means of a bibliographic citation, or explicitly by a structured taxonomy.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>taxonomy</gi> within <gi>classDecl</gi> is repeatable, allowing the declaration of multiple authority sources within a single TEI file. In MDC, taxonomies most commonly take the implicit form: they refer to an external vocabulary or authority source, rather than listing all terms within <gi>taxonomy</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>Each <gi>taxonomy</gi> includes <att>xml:id</att>, which acts as the internal identifier for that vocabulary or authority source, and <gi>bibl</gi>, which typically includes <code>&lt;ref target="…"&gt;</code> that provides a resolvable URI for the authority source.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>Instead of embedding a full URI in <att>ref</att> for each occurrence, the vocabulary or authority source is declared once in <gi>classDecl</gi> using <gi>taxonomy</gi>. When a vocabulary declared in <gi>taxonomy</gi> is referenced elsewhere in <gi>teiHeader</gi> provide the relevant identifier in <att>key</att> and refer to the declared source in <att>source</att>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>The value of <att>source</att> or <att>scheme</att> must match the <att>xml:id</att> of the corresponding <gi>taxonomy</gi>, preceded by <code>#</code>. For example, <att>scheme</att>=<val>#lcsh</val> or <att>source</att>=<val>#viaf</val> refers to the <gi>taxonomy</gi> declared with <att>xml:id</att>=<val>lcsh</val> or <att>xml:id</att>=<val>viaf</val> within <gi>classDecl</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>The following <gi>classDecl</gi> forms part of the standard MDC TEI-XML template. These six vocabularies constitute the standard authority declarations.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><classDecl>
<taxonomy xml:id="lcsh">
<bibl><ref target="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects.html">Library of Congress Subject Headings (LCSH)</ref></bibl>
</taxonomy>
<taxonomy xml:id="iso639-2">
<bibl><ref target="https://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/php/code_list.php">ISO 639-2 Codes for the Representation of Names of Languages (LC)</ref></bibl>
</taxonomy>
<taxonomy xml:id="marcrelator">
<bibl><ref target="https://www.loc.gov/marc/relators/relaterm.html">MARC Code List for Relators (LC)</ref></bibl>
</taxonomy>
<taxonomy xml:id="viaf">
<bibl><ref target="https://viaf.org">Virtual International Authority File (VIAF)</ref></bibl>
</taxonomy>
<taxonomy xml:id="tgn">
<bibl><ref target="https://www.getty.edu/research/tools/vocabularies/tgn/index.html">Getty Thesaurus of Geographic Names® (TGN)</ref></bibl>
</taxonomy>
<taxonomy xml:id="aat">
<bibl><ref target="https://www.getty.edu/research/tools/vocabularies/aat">Getty Art &amp; Architecture Thesaurus® (AAT)</ref></bibl>
</taxonomy>
</classDecl></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                              <p>These taxonomies should <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> be deleted or amended unless a vocabulary is demonstrably <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> used in <gi>teiHeader</gi> or has been formally replaced by an explicitly required alternative. Where <att>key</att> values are identified by <att>source</att> as belonging to one of these vocabularies, the corresponding <gi>taxonomy</gi> declaration must remain in place.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>Where manuscripts catalogued in FIHRIST are included in MDC and identifiers from FIHRIST authority databases are recorded using <att>source</att>=<val>#fihrist</val>, a corresponding <code>&lt;taxonomy xml:id="fihrist"&gt;</code> must be declared within <gi>classDecl</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><classDecl>
<taxonomy xml:id="lcsh"></taxonomy>
<taxonomy xml:id="iso639-2"></taxonomy>
<taxonomy xml:id="marcrelator"></taxonomy>
<taxonomy xml:id="viaf"></taxonomy>
<taxonomy xml:id="tgn"></taxonomy>
<taxonomy xml:id="aat"></taxonomy>
<taxonomy xml:id="fihrist">
<bibl><ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk">FIHRIST: Union Catalogue of Manuscripts from the Islamicate World</ref></bibl>
</taxonomy>
</classDecl></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                            </div>
                                                                                                                            <div xml:id="profileDesc">
                                                                                                                              <head><code>&lt;profileDesc&gt;</code> | text-profile description</head>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-profileDesc.html"><gi>profileDesc</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(text-profile description) provides a detailed description of non-bibliographic aspects of a text, specifically the languages and sublanguages used, the situation in which it was produced, the participants and their setting.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>profileDesc</gi> is the third major subdivision of <gi>teiHeader</gi> and is used to record subject headings and, in the case of letters, structured correspondence metadata.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>profileDesc</gi> may contain the following elements:</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<teiHeader>
<fileDesc>|<titleStmt/>|<publicationStmt/>|<sourceDesc>|<msDesc>|
<msContents/>|<physDesc/>|<history/>|<additional/>|</msDesc>|</sourceDesc>|</fileDesc>|</encodingDesc>
<profileDesc>
<textClass>
<!-- Metadata for subject classification -->
<!-- Contains <keywords> -->
</textClass>
<correspDesc>
<!-- Metadata for an act of correspondence -->
<!-- Contains <correspAction> -->
</correspDesc>
</profileDesc>
<revisionDesc/>
</teiHeader>]]></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                            </div>
                                                                                                                            <div xml:id="textClass">
                                                                                                                              <head><code>&lt;textClass&gt;</code> | text classification</head>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-textClass.html"><gi>textClass</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(text classification) groups information which describes the nature or topic of a text in terms of a standard classification scheme, thesaurus, etc.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>textClass</gi> within <gi>profileDesc</gi> is used to record subject classification metadata for the item and contains <gi>keywords</gi> listing the subject headings.</p>
                                                                                                                            </div>
                                                                                                                            <div xml:id="keywords">
                                                                                                                              <head><code>&lt;keywords&gt;</code> | keywords</head>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-keywords.html"><gi>keywords</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(keywords) contains a list of keywords or phrases identifying the topic or nature of a text.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Subject(s)</hi></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>keywords</gi> is used to record the subject headings associated with the item. These headings describe the subject, topic, or thematic content of the item and are used to classify it for discovery and retrieval.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>At least three subject headings should be included where possible. These may be broad or more specific depending on the nature of the material.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p>The subject headings are encoded using <gi>list</gi> containing three or more <gi>item</gi>. Each <gi>item</gi> must contain <gi>term</gi> with <att>key</att> giving the authority identifier for that heading.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><gi>keywords</gi> includes <att>scheme</att> that identifies the controlled vocabulary governing the list of subject terms.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p rend="attHead"><code>@scheme</code></p>
                                                                                                                              <p><att>scheme</att> identifies the controlled vocabulary within which the set of keywords concerned is defined.</p>
                                                                                                                              <p><att>scheme</att> with value <val>#lcsh</val> indicates that the subject headings are drawn from the Library of Congress Subject Headings (LCSH).</p>
                                                                                                                              <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                <row>
                                                                                                                                  <cell><p><val>lcsh</val></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                  <cell><p>Library of Congress Subject Headings (LCSH)</p></cell>
                                                                                                                                </row>
                                                                                                                                <row>
                                                                                                                                  <cell cols="2"><p>The <ref target="https://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects.html">Library of Congress Subject Headings (LCSH)</ref> is perhaps the most widely adopted subject indexing language in the world, has been translated into many languages, and is used around the world by libraries large and small. LCSH has been actively maintained since 1898 to catalogue materials held at the Library of Congress.</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><taxonomy xml:id="lcsh">
<bibl><ref target="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects.html">Library of Congress Subject Headings (LCSH)</ref></bibl>
</taxonomy></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                  </row>
                                                                                                                                </table>
                                                                                                                                <p>When the value <code>#lcsh</code> is used for <att>scheme</att>, it indicates that the subject headings recorded in <gi>keywords</gi> are drawn from this authority. The prefix <code>#</code> indicates a reference to an identifier defined elsewhere in the same file. In this case, it refers to the <gi>taxonomy</gi> declared in the header with <att>xml:id</att>=<val>lcsh</val>. This value can be selected from a controlled dropdown list when entering the attribute and does not need to be typed manually.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>Because the vocabulary is declared at the <gi>keywords</gi> level, it applies to all subject terms listed within that element and does <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> need to be repeated for each individual <gi>term</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                                <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                  <row>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Subjects:</hi> Manuscripts, Medieval--Italy--14th century; Illumination of books and manuscripts; Literature, Medieval; Italian literature-- To 1400; Italian poetry--To 1400</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><textClass>
<keywords scheme="#lcsh">
<list>
<item><term key="sh85080744">Manuscripts, Medieval--Italy--14th century</term></item>
<item><term key="sh85064332">Illumination of books and manuscripts</term></item>
<item><term key="sh85077548">Literature, Medieval</term></item>
<item><term key="sh85068817">Italian literature--To 1400</term></item>
<item><term key="sh85068842">Italian poetry--To 1400</term></item>
</list>
</keywords>
</textClass></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                                      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Il Canzoniere di Petrarca e Le Rime di Dante</hi>: <hi rend="bold"><ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-ITALIAN-00001/1">Italian MS 1</ref></hi></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                  </row>
                                                                                                                                </table>
                                                                                                                                <p><gi>keywords</gi> is repeatable within <gi>textClass</gi>, allowing multiple sets of subject terms to be recorded where different vocabularies or classification schemes are used. Each <gi>keywords</gi> normally corresponds to a single controlled vocabulary, identified through <att>scheme</att>. Additional <gi>keywords</gi> should be used only where subject terms from other controlled vocabularies or classification systems need to be recorded.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>Where subject terms are drawn from a controlled vocabulary other than those already declared in <gi>classDecl</gi>, the corresponding vocabulary must be declared as a <gi>taxonomy</gi> in the header before it is referenced in <gi>keywords</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>Where terms do not correspond to an external authority or controlled vocabulary, <att>scheme</att>=<val>local</val> may be used.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>In cases where it is necessary to distinguish between subject and genre terms, <att>type</att> on <gi>term</gi> may be used with values such as <val>subject</val> or <val>genre</val> respectively.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>Where <gi>correspDesc</gi> is included, <gi>keywords</gi> should be included after <gi>correspDesc</gi>, <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> before.</p>
                                                                                                                              </div>
                                                                                                                              <div xml:id="correspDesc">
                                                                                                                                <head><code>&lt;correspDesc&gt;</code> | correspondence description</head>
                                                                                                                                <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-correspDesc.html"><gi>correspDesc</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(correspondence description) contains a description of the actions related to one act of correspondence.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                <p><gi>correspDesc</gi> within <gi>profileDesc</gi> provides structured correspondence-specific metadata concerning the communicative aspects of an act of correspondence, such as sending and receiving, and identifies the participants involved. This information complements the detailed description of the physical item, such as a letter, postcard, or other form of correspondence, typically provided in <gi>sourceDesc</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>The individual stages of the correspondence are encoded using <gi>correspAction</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                              </div>
                                                                                                                              <div xml:id="correspAction">
                                                                                                                                <head><code>&lt;correspAction&gt;</code> | correspondence action</head>
                                                                                                                                <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-correspAction.html"><gi>correspAction</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(correspondence action) contains a structured description of the place, the name of a person/organization and the date related to the sending/receiving of a message or any other action related to the correspondence.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                <p><gi>correspAction</gi> within <gi>correspDesc</gi> is used to record each action associated with a correspondence event, most commonly the sending or receiving of a communication. It may record the person, organisation, place, or date associated with that action.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p><att>type</att> on <gi>correspAction</gi> should be used to distinguish correspondence actions.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p rend="attHead"><code>@type</code></p>
                                                                                                                                <p><att>type</att> indicates the nature of the correspondence action.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>The following values should be used:</p>
                                                                                                                                <p><val>sent</val> indicates the action of sending a communication.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p><val>received</val> indicates the action of receiving a communication.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>The table below shows how MDC display labels match the relevant TEI elements used to encode correspondence.</p>
                                                                                                                                <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                  <row>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p>MDC display label</p></cell>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p><code>TEI &lt;&gt;|@</code></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                  </row>
                                                                                                                                  <row>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p>Author(s)</p></cell>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<correspAction type="sent"> + <name>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                  </row>
                                                                                                                                  <row>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p>Date of Creation</p></cell>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<origin> — <origDate>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                  </row>
                                                                                                                                  <row>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p>Origin Place</p></cell>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<origin> — <origPlace>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                  </row>
                                                                                                                                  <row>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p>Date of Sending</p></cell>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<correspAction type="sent"> + <date>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                  </row>
                                                                                                                                  <row>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p>Recipient(s)</p></cell>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<correspAction type="received"> + <name>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                  </row>
                                                                                                                                  <row>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p>Destination</p></cell>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<correspAction type="received"> + <placeName>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                  </row>
                                                                                                                                  <row>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p>Date of Receipt</p></cell>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<correspAction type="received"> + <date>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                  </row>
                                                                                                                                </table>
                                                                                                                                <p>Correspondence titles recorded in <gi>title</gi> within <gi>msItem</gi> should follow a clear and consistent title pattern, using one of the following forms:</p>
                                                                                                                                <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">Letter from [sender] to [recipient]
Letter to [recipient] from [sender]</egXML></p>
                                                                                                                                <p>Once adopted, the same pattern should be used consistently throughout a project.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>For correspondence projects centred on a principal correspondent, the title pattern may prioritise that person consistently, whether as sender or recipient. For example, titles in The Heinrich Simon Papers prioritise Heinrich Simon, using forms such as Letter from Heinrich Simon to … or Letter to Heinrich Simon from ….</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>Names in <gi>title</gi> should appear in full. <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">Avoid</hi></hi> abbreviations, initials, or shortened forms unless these are the only forms attested in the source.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>The sender (author) and recipient should be recorded within the appropriate <gi>correspAction</gi> using <gi>name</gi>. Within <gi>name</gi>, include <gi>persName</gi> for a personal name or <gi>orgName</gi> for an organisational name. If the name is listed in VIAF, include both <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> on <gi>name</gi> to reference the appropriate VIAF authority record.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p><gi>date</gi> is used within <gi>correspAction</gi> to record dates associated with actions, such as when a communication was sent or received. Where the exact date is known, it should be recorded using <gi>date</gi> with <att>when</att>. In many cases, however, the exact date of sending cannot be established even though the letter preserves the date on which it was written. In such cases, the date the letter was written should be recorded within <gi>origin</gi> using <gi>origDate</gi>, rather than in <code>&lt;correspAction type="sent"&gt;</code>, which is used to record the date of sending when this is known.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p><gi>placeName</gi> is used within <gi>correspAction</gi> to record the place associated with actions, such as the place from which a communication was sent or at which it was received. Within <gi>placeName</gi>, record the normalised form of the place name. If the place is listed in TGN, include both <att>source</att> and <att>key</att> on <gi>placeName</gi> to reference the appropriate TGN authority record. In many cases, the place from which the letter was sent cannot be established even though the letter preserves the place where it was written. In such cases, the place the letter was written should be recorded within <gi>origin</gi> using <gi>origPlace</gi>, rather than in <code>&lt;correspAction type="sent"&gt;</code>, which is used to record the place of sending when this is known.</p>
                                                                                                                                <p>The following example shows a letter for which the date and place of writing are known, but the exact date of sending is not recorded. In this case, the title of the item is given in <gi>msItem</gi>, while the writing date and place are recorded within <gi>origin</gi> using <gi>origDate</gi> and <gi>origPlace</gi>. The participants in the correspondence are recorded within <gi>correspDesc</gi> using <gi>correspAction</gi>. The place of receipt is recorded using <gi>placeName</gi>. This pattern reflects an important distinction in correspondence encoding: the date on which a letter was written is not necessarily the same as the date on which it was sent. Likewise, the date of receipt may not always be known.</p>
                                                                                                                                <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                  <row>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p>Letter from Heinrich Simon to his father Herrmann Simon (SIM/1/198)</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p>Heinrich Simon asks his father for permission to attend physics lessons with a travelling private teacher.</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p>—</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Title:</hi> Letter from Heinrich Simon to his father Herrmann Simon</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Language(s):</hi> German</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p>—</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Author(s):</hi> Simon, Heinrich, 1805-1860</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Poland, Brieg (Brzeg)</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 29 April 1823</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Recipient(s):</hi> Simon, Friedrich Herrmann (Heymann), 1781-1851</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Destination:</hi> Poland, Breslau (Wrocław)</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p>—</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><teiHeader>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<msContents>
<summary>
<p>Heinrich Simon asks his father for permission to attend physics lessons with a travelling private teacher.</p>
</summary>
<msItem>
<title>Letter from Heinrich Simon to his father Herrmann Simon</title>
<textLang mainLang="ger">German</textLang>
</msItem>
</msContents>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<history>
<origin>
<origDate when="1823-04-29">29 April 1823</origDate>
<origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="7006366">Poland</country>, <settlement source="#tgn" key="7007623"><placeName type="historic" xml:lang="ger">Brieg</placeName> (<placeName type="modern" xml:lang="pol">Brzeg</placeName>)</settlement>
</origPlace>
</origin>
</history>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<correspDesc>
<correspAction type="sent">
<name source="#viaf" key="50001971"><persName>Simon, Heinrich, 1805-1860 </persName></name>
</correspAction>
<correspAction type="received">
<name><persName>Simon, Friedrich Herrmann (Heymann), 1781-1851</persName></name>
<placeName source="#tgn" key="7007601">Poland, Breslau (Wrocław)</placeName>
</correspAction>
</correspDesc>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</teiHeader></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                                      <p rend="right"><hi rend="italic">Letter from Heinrich Simon to his father Herrmann Simon:</hi> <ref target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/AR-SIM-00001-00198/4">SIM/1/198</ref></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                  </row>
                                                                                                                                </table>
                                                                                                                                <p>If the full correspondence information were available, the same letter could be encoded more fully by recording the dates and places associated with the sending and receiving actions directly within the relevant <gi>correspAction</gi>. In such a case, <gi>origin</gi> would still record the date and place at which the letter was written, while <gi>correspDesc</gi> would record the subsequent communicative actions. This is especially important because a letter may be written on one date and sent on another.</p>
                                                                                                                                <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                  <row>
                                                                                                                                    <cell><p>Heinrich Simon asks his father for permission to attend physics lessons with a travelling private teacher.</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p>—</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Title:</hi> Letter from Heinrich Simon to his father Herrmann Simon</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Language(s):</hi> German</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p>—</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Author(s):</hi> Simon, Heinrich, 1805-1860</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Origin Place:</hi> Poland, Brieg (Brzeg)</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Creation:</hi> 29 April 1823</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Sending:</hi> 1 May 1823</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Recipient(s):</hi> Simon, Friedrich Herrmann (Heymann), 1781-1851</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Destination:</hi> Poland, Breslau (Wrocław)</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Date of Receipt:</hi> 3 May 1823</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p>—</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><teiHeader>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<msContents>
<summary>
<p>Heinrich Simon asks his father for permission to attend physics lessons with a travelling private teacher.</p>
</summary>
<msItem>
<title>Letter from Heinrich Simon to his father Herrmann Simon</title>
<textLang mainLang="ger">German</textLang>
</msItem>
</msContents>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<history>
<origin>
<origDate when="1823-04-29">29 April 1823</origDate>
<origPlace><country source="#tgn" key="7006366">Poland</country>, <settlement source="#tgn" key="7007623"><placeName type="historic" xml:lang="ger">Brieg</placeName> (<placeName type="modern" xml:lang="pol">Brzeg</placeName>)</settlement>
</origPlace>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</origin>
</history>
<correspDesc>
<correspAction type="sent">
<name source="#viaf" key="50001971"><persName>Simon, Heinrich, 1805-1860 </persName></name>
<date when="1823-05-01">1 May 1823</date>
<placeName source="#tgn" key="7007623">Poland, Brieg (Brzeg)</placeName>
</correspAction>
<correspAction type="received">
<name><persName>Simon, Friedrich Herrmann (Heymann), 1781-1851</persName></name>
<date when="1823-05-03">3 May 1823</date>
<placeName source="#tgn" key="7007601">Poland, Breslau (Wrocław)</placeName>
</correspAction>
</correspDesc>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</teiHeader></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                    </row>
                                                                                                                                  </table>
                                                                                                                                  <p>Any authority file referenced using <att>source</att> must be declared in a corresponding <gi>taxonomy</gi> within <gi>teiHeader</gi>. The prefix <code>#</code> indicates that the value refers to the identifier defined there.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p><gi>origDate</gi> and <gi>origPlace</gi> indicate when and where the letter was written, whereas <gi>date</gi> and <gi>placeName</gi> in <code>&lt;correspAction type="sent"&gt;</code> indicate when and from where it was sent. These may coincide, but they should not be assumed to do so.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>If the date or place of sending cannot be established, the corresponding <gi>date</gi> or <gi>placeName</gi> may be omitted.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>Full dates should be given in the order day, month, year. Use cardinal, not ordinal, forms for days, for example, 30 August 1821 rather than 30th August, 1821. Do not use commas, leading zeroes for days 1 to 9, or abbreviated month names.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p><gi>origDate</gi> and its attributes follow the same encoding principles outlined in Section X &lt;!--insert hyperlink--&gt; of these guidelines.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p><gi>date</gi> usually refers to a modern or historically standardised calendar date, such as the day a letter was sent or received. In these cases, TEI assumes the Gregorian calendar by default, so <att>calendar</att>=<val>gregorian</val> is normally unnecessary.</p>
                                                                                                                                </div>
                                                                                                                                <div xml:id="revisionDesc">
                                                                                                                                  <head><code>&lt;revisionDesc&gt;</code> | revision description</head>
                                                                                                                                  <p rend="definition"><ref target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-revisionDesc.html"><gi>revisionDesc</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(revision description) summarizes the revision history for a file.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                  <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Author(s) of the Record</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                  <p><gi>revisionDesc</gi> is the final component of <gi>teiHeader</gi> and is used to record major changes to the file, including who made each change and when.  It must contain at least one <gi>change</gi>.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p><ref target="https://www.tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/ref-change.html"><gi>change</gi></ref> <hi rend="italic">(change) documents a change or set of changes made during the production of a source document, or during the revision of an electronic file.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                  <p><gi>change</gi> is repeatable, allowing multiple revision entries to be recorded within a single <gi>revisionDesc</gi>. These entries should be recorded in reverse chronological order, with the most recent change appearing first.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>Each <gi>change</gi>, should include <att>when</att> to record the date. Within <gi>change</gi>, the name of the contributor or revisor should be recorded first, typically using <gi>persName</gi>, followed, where necessary, by a brief description of the change itself.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>Only significant revisions should be recorded, such as the re-dating or re-location of an item, the addition of provenance information, or the identification of previously unrecognised contents.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <p>At a minimum, the date on which the TEI file was created and the name of the contributor responsible for its creation should be recorded.</p>
                                                                                                                                  <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                    <row>
                                                                                                                                      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Author(s) of the Record:</hi> Vanellope von Schweetz</p>
                                                                                                                                        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<revisionDesc>
<change when="2026-03-15"><persName>Vanellope von Schweetz</persName></change>
</revisionDesc>
</tieHeader>]]></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                      </row>
                                                                                                                                    </table>
                                                                                                                                    <p>Optionally, if a contributor has been defined in <gi>respStmt</gi> with <att>xml:id</att>, <gi>change</gi> may instead include <att>who</att> in addition to <att>when</att> to reference the contributor responsible for the recorded revision. This approach requires a matching identifier defined elsewhere, for example:</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><![CDATA[<respStmt xml:id="VvS">
<!-- additional metadata-->
<persName>Vanellope von Schweetz</persName>
</respStmt>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<revisionDesc>
<change when="2026-03-15" who="#VvS"></change>
</revisionDesc>
</tieHeader>]]></egXML></p>
                                                                                                                                    <p>Unless the system is configured to resolve <att>who</att> references and retrieve the contributor’s name from the referenced element, <gi>persName</gi> must be included within <gi>change</gi> if the name is intended to appear in the interface.</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p>Decisions about whether the information recorded in <gi>revisionDesc</gi> should be visible on the public interface should ultimately be determined at the project level. In practice, however, such information is most often retained for internal documentation purposes and therefore kept hidden from public view.</p>
                                                                                                                                    <div xml:id="note-10">
                                                                                                                                      <head>Customised <code>&lt;note&gt;</code> types and display fields</head>
                                                                                                                                      <p><gi>note</gi> in TEI provides a flexible mechanism for recording supplementary descriptive information. While the element itself forms part of the TEI standard, the values used for <att>type</att> are not fixed and may be defined locally to support project-specific descriptive requirements.</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p>In some cases, the TEI schema does not provide dedicated elements for recording certain kinds of information needed to describe particular collection formats, especially early printed books, maps, and visual collections. In such cases, locally defined <att>type</att> on <gi>note</gi> are used to encode this information.</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p>Each <att>type</att> value is mapped by the system to a predefined display label in the MDC interface, ensuring consistent presentation across TEI files.</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p>The following sections describe each customised <gi>note</gi> type, outlining its purpose, the collection formats to which it applies, and guidance on how the information should be encoded.</p>
                                                                                                                                    </div>
                                                                                                                                  </div>
                                                                                                                                  <div xml:id="note-2">
                                                                                                                                    <head><code>&lt;note type="publisher"&gt;</code> | publication</head>
                                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="italic">The publication statement appearing in a printed book, usually on the title page or colophon.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                    <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Publication</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><code>&lt;note type="publisher"&gt;</code> within <gi>origin</gi> is used to record verbatim publication or imprint statements for printed books. This may include the place of publication, the name of the publisher or printer, and the date of publication. In MARC-derived metadata and retroconversion workflows, this information usually derives from the publication or imprint information recorded in MARC fields 260 or 264.</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p>In catalogue metadata exported from Alma and displayed through Primo, publication information may appear in MARC field 264 and may also be reflected in the transcription of the colophon.</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="bold">Publisher</hi>     Venetia : Appresso Giouambattista, Marchiò Sessa, &amp; Fratelli</p>
                                                                                                                                    <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                      <row>
                                                                                                                                        <cell><p>264</p></cell>
                                                                                                                                        <cell><p>_1 |a Venetia : |b Appresso Giouambattista, Marchiò Sessa, &amp; Fratelli, |c 1578.</p></cell>
                                                                                                                                      </row>
                                                                                                                                    </table>
                                                                                                                                    <p>Description</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p>—</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p>Colophon reads: In Venetia, Appresso gli Heredi di Francesco Rampazetto. Ad instantia di Giouambattista, Marchio Sessa, &amp; Fratelli. MDLXXVIII.</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p>To ensure consistency across TEI files within the same project collection, publication statements are standardised following the format adopted by ICCU’s Edizioni Italiane del XVI Secolo (EDIT16).</p>
                                                                                                                                    <p>For example, the EDIT16 record <ref target="https://edit16.iccu.sbn.it/en/resultset-titoli/-/titoli/detail/CNCE001177">CNCE 1177</ref> provides the following standardised publication statement:</p>
                                                                                                                                    <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                      <row>
                                                                                                                                        <cell><p>Imprint</p></cell>
                                                                                                                                        <cell><p>In Venetia : appresso Giouambattista Marchiò Sessa et fratelli, 1578 (In Venetia : appresso gli heredi di Francesco Rampazetto : ad instantia di Giouambattista Marchio Sessa et fratelli, 1578)</p></cell>
                                                                                                                                      </row>
                                                                                                                                    </table>
                                                                                                                                    <p>This form is adopted in MDC and encoded as:</p>
                                                                                                                                    <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                      <row>
                                                                                                                                        <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Publication:</hi> In Venetia: appresso Giouambattista, Marchiò Sessa, &amp; Fratelli, 1578.</p>
                                                                                                                                          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<note type="publisher">In Venetia: appresso Giouambattista, Marchiò Sessa, &amp; Fratelli, 1578. </note>
</origin></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                        </row>
                                                                                                                                      </table>
                                                                                                                                      <p>The space before the colon used in MARC or ISBD punctuation should <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> be retained in MDC. Venetia : is encoded as Venetia:.</p>
                                                                                                                                    </div>
                                                                                                                                    <div xml:id="note-3">
                                                                                                                                      <head><code>&lt;note type="printersDevice"&gt;</code> | printer’s device</head>
                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="italic">The printer’s device appearing in a printed book, usually on the title page or colophon.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                      <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Printer’s Device</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                      <p><code>&lt;note type="printersDevice"&gt;</code> within <gi>origin</gi> is used to describe the printer’s device appearing in early printed books. A printer’s device (or printer's mark) is a distinctive design or visual trademark placed by the printer or publisher on the title page or elsewhere in the text, to distinguish their productions.</p>
                                                                                                                                      <p>Descriptions typically summarise the device as it appears in the book, for example by noting the main iconographic elements or motto associated with the device.</p>
                                                                                                                                      <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                        <row>
                                                                                                                                          <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Printer's Device:</hi> Aldine Press device on [pi1r] and [H7v]: a dolphin entwined around an anchor, Aldo.</p>
                                                                                                                                            <p>Variant of this device on a1r: Aldvs.</p>
                                                                                                                                            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><origin>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<note type="printersDevice">Aldine Press device on <locus from="[pi1r]" to="[pi1r]">[pi1r]</locus> and <locus from="[H7v]" to="[H7v]">[H7v]</locus>: a dolphin entwined around an anchor, Aldo.
<p>Variant of this device on <locus from="A1r" to="A1r">A1r</locus> a1r: Aldvs.</p></note>
</origin></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                          </row>
                                                                                                                                        </table>
                                                                                                                                      </div>
                                                                                                                                      <div xml:id="note-4">
                                                                                                                                        <head><code>&lt;note type="scale"&gt;</code> | scale</head>
                                                                                                                                        <p><hi rend="italic">The scale of a map or other cartographic material.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                        <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Scale</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                        <p><code>&lt;note type="scale"&gt;</code> within <gi>msItem</gi> is used to record the scale of a map.</p>
                                                                                                                                        <p>Map scale refers to the relationship, or ratio, between distance on a map and the corresponding distance on the ground. The scale may be transcribed verbatim from the item or inferred where it is not explicitly stated but can be determined. It may be expressed as a representative fraction (RF) or other numerical scale, or as a textual scale statement.</p>
                                                                                                                                        <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                          <row>
                                                                                                                                            <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Scale:</hi> 1:100,000</p>
                                                                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><msItem>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<note type="scale">1:100,000</note>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msItem></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                            </row>
                                                                                                                                          </table>
                                                                                                                                        </div>
                                                                                                                                        <div xml:id="note-5">
                                                                                                                                          <head><code>&lt;note type="technique"&gt;</code> | technique</head>
                                                                                                                                          <p><hi rend="italic">The method or process used to produce an item in art, visual, or material culture.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                          <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Technique</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                          <p><code>&lt;note type="technique"&gt;</code> within <gi>msItem</gi> is used primarily for visual collections and similar objects to record information about the artistic, photographic, or production technique used to create the item. This note may describe processes such as engraving, etching, lithography, woodcut, photographic processes, drawing techniques, or other methods of manufacture or artistic execution.</p>
                                                                                                                                          <p>It is strongly recommended that values for <code>&lt;note type="technique"&gt;</code> are drawn from a controlled vocabulary. The preferred source is the Getty Art &amp; Architecture Thesaurus (AAT).</p>
                                                                                                                                          <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                            <row>
                                                                                                                                              <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Technique:</hi> Gelatin dry plate process</p>
                                                                                                                                                <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><msItem>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<note type="technique">Gelatin dry plate process</note>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msItem></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                              </row>
                                                                                                                                              <row>
                                                                                                                                                <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Technique:</hi> Albumen process</p>
                                                                                                                                                  <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><msItem>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<note type="technique">Albumen process</note>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msItem></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                                </row>
                                                                                                                                                <row>
                                                                                                                                                  <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Technique:</hi> Painting</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><msItem>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<note type="technique">Painting</note>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msItem></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                                  </row>
                                                                                                                                                </table>
                                                                                                                                              </div>
                                                                                                                                              <div xml:id="note-6">
                                                                                                                                                <head><code>&lt;note type="medium"&gt;</code> | medium</head>
                                                                                                                                                <p><hi rend="italic">The material of the tool used to produce an item in art, visual, or material culture.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                                <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Medium</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                                <p><code>&lt;note type="medium"&gt;</code> within <gi>msItem</gi> is used primarily for visual collections and similar objects, to record the medium used to create the item. This note captures the specific substance or material applied by the maker in the creation process. It may include drawing media such as graphite, charcoal, and coloured pencil. It may include painting media such as oil paint, acrylic, tempera, and watercolour. It may include photographic media such as emulsion for glass plate negatives.</p>
                                                                                                                                                <p>It is strongly recommended that values for <code>&lt;note type="medium"&gt;</code> are drawn from a controlled vocabulary. The preferred source is the Getty Art &amp; Architecture Thesaurus (AAT).</p>
                                                                                                                                                <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                                  <row>
                                                                                                                                                    <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Medium:</hi> Emulsion</p>
                                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="bold">• Technique:</hi> Gelatin dry plate process</p>
                                                                                                                                                      <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><msItem>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<note type="technique">Gelatin dry plate process</note>
<note type="medium">Emulsion</note>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msItem></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                                    </row>
                                                                                                                                                    <row>
                                                                                                                                                      <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Medium:</hi> Oil paint</p>
                                                                                                                                                        <p><hi rend="bold">• Technique:</hi> Painting</p>
                                                                                                                                                        <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><msItem>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<note type="technique">Painting</note>
<note type="medium">Oil paint</note>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msItem></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                                      </row>
                                                                                                                                                    </table>
                                                                                                                                                    <p><code>&lt;note type="technique"&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;note type="medium"&gt;</code> are used only when it is desirable for this information to appear as labelled fields in MDC.</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <p>Otherwise, alternative encoding may be used. For example, medium information may be recorded using <code>&lt;term type="medium"&gt;</code> within <gi>decoNote</gi>. Similarly, technique information may be recorded using <code>&lt;term type="technique"&gt;</code>.</p>
                                                                                                                                                  </div>
                                                                                                                                                  <div xml:id="note-7">
                                                                                                                                                    <head><code>&lt;note type="shape"&gt;</code> | shape</head>
                                                                                                                                                    <p><hi rend="italic">The physical shape or outline of an object in material culture.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                                    <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Shape</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                                    <p><code>&lt;note type="shape"&gt;</code> within <gi>msItem</gi> is used to record the shape of the item. This note identifies the overall form, outline, or geometric configuration of the object. The shape should be recorded using consistent terminology. Acceptable terms include <hi rend="italic">circular</hi>, <hi rend="italic">diamond</hi>, <hi rend="italic">irregular</hi>, <hi rend="italic">oval</hi>, <hi rend="italic">pentagonal</hi>, <hi rend="italic">polygonal</hi>, <hi rend="italic">rectangular</hi>, <hi rend="italic">square</hi>, and <hi rend="italic">triangular</hi>. Do <hi rend="bold"><hi rend="italic">not</hi></hi> use <hi rend="italic">round</hi> or <hi rend="italic">circle</hi> for <hi rend="italic">circular</hi>, <hi rend="italic">lozenge</hi> for <hi rend="italic">diamond</hi>, <hi rend="italic">oblong</hi> for <hi rend="italic">oval</hi>, or <hi rend="italic">rectangle</hi> for <hi rend="italic">rectangular</hi>.</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                                      <row>
                                                                                                                                                        <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Shape:</hi> Circular</p>
                                                                                                                                                          <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><msItem>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<note type="shape">Circular</note>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msItem></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                                        </row>
                                                                                                                                                      </table>
                                                                                                                                                    </div>
                                                                                                                                                    <div xml:id="note-8">
                                                                                                                                                      <head><code>&lt;note type="mode"&gt;</code> | mode</head>
                                                                                                                                                      <p><hi rend="italic">The mode of use of an object in material culture.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                                      <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Mode</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                                      <p><code>&lt;note type="mode"&gt;</code> within <gi>msItem</gi> is used to record the mode in which an item is worn, carried, used, or positioned. This note may describe how an object is worn on the body, carried by a person, associated with a particular individual, or placed within a space or setting.</p>
                                                                                                                                                      <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                                        <row>
                                                                                                                                                          <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Mode:</hi> Worn or carried on the person.</p>
                                                                                                                                                            <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><msItem>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<note type="mode">Worn or carried on the person.</note>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msItem></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                                          </row>
                                                                                                                                                        </table>
                                                                                                                                                      </div>
                                                                                                                                                      <div xml:id="note-9">
                                                                                                                                                        <head><code>&lt;note type="function"&gt;</code> | function</head>
                                                                                                                                                        <p><hi rend="italic">The intended use or purpose of an object in material culture.</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                                        <p rend="displayLabel">MDC display label — <hi rend="bold">Function</hi></p>
                                                                                                                                                        <p><code>&lt;note type="function"&gt;</code> within <gi>msItem</gi> is used to record the functional purpose or intended use of an object, particularly when this provides additional contextual information about how the object operated within cultural, social, or ritual practice. This note may describe purposes such as protection, healing, commemoration, exchange, personal adornment, or symbolic or ritual intent.</p>
                                                                                                                                                        <table rend="rules">
                                                                                                                                                          <row>
                                                                                                                                                            <cell><p><hi rend="bold">• Function:</hi> Protection and prosperity.</p>
                                                                                                                                                              <p><egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples"><msItem>
<!-- additional metadata-->
<note type="function">Protection and prosperity.</note>
<!-- additional metadata-->
</msItem></egXML></p></cell>
                                                                                                                                                            </row>
                                                                                                                                                          </table>
                                                                                                                                                          <p><code>&lt;note type="shape"&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;note type="mode"&gt;</code>, and <code>&lt;note type="function"&gt;</code> were introduced as part of the <ref target="https://stage.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/collections/gasteramulets/1">Gaster Amulets</ref> project and are currently used only within this context.</p>
                                                                                                                                                          <p>While these <gi>note</gi> types may also be applicable to other visual or material collections, their broader use within MDC has not yet been tested and should therefore be considered provisional.</p>
                                                                                                                                                          <p>The forthcoming introduction of <gi>object</gi> may provide more appropriate TEI structures for recording this type of information. When implemented, the use of these <gi>note</gi> types may need to be reviewed and potentially replaced by more suitable elements.</p>
                                                                                                                                                        </div>
                                                                                                                                                      </div>
                                                                                                                                                      <!-- schemaSpec intentionally omitted: MDC validates against the CDCP profile (odd/cdcp.odd) of the TEI-CSC consolidated schema -->
                                                                                                                                                    </body>
                                                                                                                                                  </text>
                                                                                                                                                </TEI>
